<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Cuomo-Endorsement 1stLd-Writethru a0754 04-06 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Endorsement, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Builds In Possible Cuomo Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``He gets, with
Cuomo comment in Washington Post interview</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo is being courted
by candidates and pursued by the press as curiosity mounts over
whether he will endorse anyone before his state's important April
19 presidential primary.
   Cuomo's closest advisers insisted Wednesday that they didn't
know when or even whether the inscrutable governor would give his
blessing to one of the Democrats competing for the party's
nomination.
   ``They've made it clear both publicly and privately they want
his endorsement,'' Cuomo press secretary Gary Fryer said of the
candidates. ``But at this point nothing has changed, despite the
4,000 phone calls we got.''
   ``He gets a constant stream of calls from the various
candidates,'' said Cuomo political adviser Meyer Frucher.
``Obviously, the front-runners have always wanted him to endorse
and the others try to keep him from endorsing.''
   Cuomo said in an interview published in Thursday's editions of
The Washington Post that he has not ruled out endorsing someone,
but added, ``The closer you get to primary day, the less reason''
there is to do so.
   The newspaper quoted the New York governor as saying he
preferred to remain neutral until after the final primaries and
then back the leader.
   ``That's the time for leadership in this process,'' he told the
Post.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, fresh from twin victories
this week in Colorado and Wisconsin, is seeking to solidify his
front-runner status _ and clear his path to the nomination _ with
another win over Jesse Jackson in New York.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., for his part, is making a major
effort in New York to succeed outside his native South. He has not
won a contest in a month and is no longer eligible for federal
matching funds.
   There are two reasons candidates are eager for Cuomo's
endorsement.
   First, the governor supported Walter Mondale in the 1984
election and, with the Cuomo team running his New York campaign,
Mondale scored a major victory.
   Second, and perhaps even more important to this year's
candidates, a Cuomo endorsement would reduce speculation that the
New York governor is angling for the nomination himself from a
deadlocked national convention and that he might be an available
alternative for Democrats.
   Dukakis set off a new round of speculation Tuesday when, asked
about a possible Cuomo endorsement, he chuckled and told reporters
in Boston that he planned to ``talk to you tomorrow.''
   But on Wednesday, Dukakis said he had nothing new to report.
   ``I'd like to have it (Cuomo's endorsement). He knows that. But
it's his decision to make,'' Dukakis said.
   ``This is getting to be kind of fun,'' Fryer said of the
interest over what Cuomo will do. ``Yesterday, we were inundated
with a wave of early morning `he's going to go with the Duke'
calls, all out of Boston. Then, a little bit later in the day,
there was a wave of `he's going with Gore' calls out of
Washington.''
   Cuomo aides and advisers said the candidates were treating Cuomo
carefully, perhaps even warily, in seeking his backing.
   ``They're not pressuring the governor in any sense of the
word,'' insisted Andrew Cuomo, the governor's son and chief
political adviser.
   ``This is one guy that is not susceptible to pressure,'' Fryer
added. ``If anything, pressure with Cuomo is counterproductive.''
   Cuomo and the candidates are all expected to appear separately
Thursday at a New York City meeting of about 300 members of the
state Democratic Committee. The candidates will be making
individual pitches to the Democratic officials, and Cuomo could use
the opportunity to make a dramatic endorsement.
   While the governor's political advisers said they doubted that
would happen, they said they did expect him to again stress that he
does not intend to become a candidate and that there should not be
a convention draft.
   Thus far, Cuomo has refused to completely rule out accepting a
convention draft, although he's said it won't happen and shouldn't
happen. He has maintained that should be enough of a disclaimer to
satisfy everyone.
   ``He'll reinforce that people should not wait for him to
endorse,'' said Andrew Cuomo of his father's expected advice to
fellow New York Democrats. ``He'll say again what he's said before:
`I'm not interested in running myself.'''
</TEXT>
