<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:Oscars-BestActress     04-06 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Oscars-Best Actress,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Best Actress</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>60th Academy Awards: The Year Of The Actress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Motion Picture Arts &
Sciences' 60th awards might well be termed the Year of the Actress,
so impressive are the candidates for best performance by an actress
in 1987.
   After being overshadowed for a few decades by macho stars, film
actresses are now having powerful roles fashioned for them. This
year's nominees afford proof: Cher, the perplexed widow of
``Moonstruck''; Glenn Close, the vengeful spurned lover in ``Fatal
Attraction''; Holly Hunter, the dynamic news producer of
``Broadcast News''; Sally Kirkland, the faded Czech actress,
``Anna''; and Meryl Streep, the down-and-out ex-singer in
``Ironweed.''
   Adding to their impressive number are performances that many
felt warranted Academy consideration: Lillian Gish and Bette Davis,
``The Whales of August''; Sarah Miles, ``Hope and Glory''; Maggie
Smith, ``The Lonely Passion of Judith Hearn''; Christine Lahti,
``Housekeeping''; Faye Dunaway, ``Barfly''; Barbra Streisand,
``Nuts''; Joanne Woodward, ``The Glass Menagerie.''
   Cher has been drawing the most attention among the nominees,
attracting a media broadside of amazing proportions. The one-time
member of the Sonny and Cher singing team is justifiably proud of
her performance in ``Moonstruck'' and has been willing to talk
about it.
   ```Moonstruck' is the first movie of mine that I ever watched
without wanting to throw up,'' she says. ``I was in love with the
story; it's my best work since `Mask.'
   ``Usually everyone's first choice is Meryl (Streep) and then
so-and-so and then so-and-so. It's something to start being
someone's first choice. ... Jack Nicholson has clout, you know.
Barbra Streisand has clout. Jane Fonda has clout. I think relative
to them, I'm a newcomer. ... I'm not working my way toward power.
I'm working my way toward the best roles I can get.''
   Equally voluble is Sally Kirkland, who won the Golden Globe as
best dramatic actress for ``Anna.'' She has been enjoying her
success after years of trying: ``I have tested for the leading role
in 25 movies, and each time the choice has narrowed to another
actress and myself. Each time the other actress won.''
   The actress campaigned for the role in the low-budget film,
studying the Czech accent and absorbing the atmosphere of the
emigre community in New York. She even added 15 pounds and taped
her face to create wrinkles.
   Does she want the Oscar?
   ``I cannot tell a lie; my fantasy ever since I was 5 years old
has been to hold that (statue) and say, `Thank-you, thank-you,
thank-you.'''
   Holly Hunter, hailed as a bright new star because of ``Broadcast
News,'' has been as silent as Kirkland and Cher have been vocal.
She declined most interviews, arguing that she was too involved
with the Sam Shepard play, ``A Lie of the Mind,'' at Los Angeles'
Mark Taper Theater.
   Director James Brooks predicts the Georgia-born actress ``will
be around for decades.'' Of his script she commented: ``I loved it;
I thought it was remarkably three-dimensional.''
   She also talked about the differences between herself and the
news producer she portrays: ``Holly Hunter is certainly less driven
than Jane Craig. I think that my priorities are quite a bit
different, in that I'm probably retty obsessed myself, but not to
such a manic degree.''
   After three supporting-actress nominations in six film roles,
Glenn Close broke through in the starring category with ``Fatal
Attraction.'' She terms the demonic Alix the first woman she's
played ``who is out of control, who emotionally runs the gamut _
the first real, full-blooded role I've had.''
   Her comment on the huge reaction to ``Fatal Attraction'': ``The
whole male-female thing in this country is very volatile right now.
I think many women are feeling used by men. They invest a lot in a
relationship, in nurturing a man emotionally and in his career, but
they have their own careers and emotions, and they don't get that
nurturing in return.''
   After playing a number of glamorous roles, two-time Oscar winner
Meryl Streep found her role as the derelict in ``Ironweed'' had its
advantages: ``In this world of purgatory of the soul, there are
very few markers to go by. I liked that about her. I liked not
having to worry about how I looked and being able to strip away,
strip away everying, except what counts.''
   Streep has created a series of indelible performances, including
Oscar winners in ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' and ``Sophie's Choice,'' as
well as ``The Deer Hunter'' and ``Out of Africa.''
   She remains ambitious: ``There's so much I'd like to do. When
the public is used to you in heavy drama, it's hard to make them
take you seriously. But I want to play comedy.
   ``I can't stand it that stage fright inhibits me. At some point
I'm going to face up and do a play. But for now I just go day to
day.''
</TEXT>
