<1ST_LINE>u a BC-RatPack     04-06 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rat Pack,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sinatra, Sammy Davis Swing Radio City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Sinatra called himself and Sammy Davis Jr.
``the Springsteen and Michael Jackson of the Geritol set''
Wednesday night as they launched into a ``Guys and Dolls'' medley,
the encore in their Rat Pack show.
   Radio City Music Hall wasn't exactly rocking, but it was
swinging.
   The 6,000-seat hall was sold out, with a top ticket price of $75.
   ``Let's not overdo it,'' Sinatra cautioned as Davis, making use
of a new hip replacement, did a few dance steps during the encore,
``because I'm tired of working alone.''
   Dean Martin had embarked with his old Las Vegas buddies on the
so-called Rat Pack tour earlier this year but has been sidelined in
recent weeks by kidney problems.
   ``We check with him every day,'' Davis assured the crowd. ``He
is cooking; he'll be back to work soon.''
   Davis, as thin as Sinatra used to be, did the first 40 minutes
of the two-hour show. He really sang jazz, and sometimes seemed to
be trying to pull the 37-piece band's ponderous arrangements up to
his swinging tempo.
   He had listeners' fingers snapping to ``Satin Doll,'' inserted
little jokes into the lyrics of ``The Lady Is a Tramp,'' put
powerful emotion into ``What Kind of Fool Am I?'' and ``Birth of
the Blues'' and made ``Mr. Bojangles'' into a one-act play. He was
never slick.
   Sinatra's voice sometimes has a frayed edge but his masterful
phrasing and timing of pithy asides are intact. More important, his
vocal timbre _ the thing that makes one know it's Sinatra and not
Vic Damone or somebody else _ is still there.
   He sang the ``Soliloquy'' from ``Carousel'' and the audience
exploded in applause. In it, he did some of his best singing of the
evening. The audience also seemed to appreciate his ambition in
choosing this high-quality, lengthy musical passage.
   Even better moments were Sinatra's hard-swinging ``Mack the
Knife'' and ``New York, New York'' and the all-time saloon song,
``One More for the Road,'' which he has sung many times but this
time also acted.
   When Sinatra and Davis harmonized beautifully on the final lines
of ``The Oldest Established Permanent Floating Crap Game in New
York,'' you knew you'd been thoroughly entertained.
   On their final night in town, Sunday, the Geritol boys will be
joined by Peggy Lee in a benefit for cancer research.
</TEXT>
