<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RIsforRitalinIII-Clinic     04-06 0992</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-R Is for Ritalin III-Clinic,1013</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`R' Is for Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part III: Inside a Ritalin Clinic _ One Girl's Journey</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Ritalin III-School</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Daily doses of the drug Ritalin are increasingly
the treatment of choice for children diagnosed with attention
deficit disorder. Not surprisingly, more and more clinics are
specializing in such diagnosis and treatment. And schools are often
enthusiastic about Ritalin's success. Two stories offer inside
looks at one such clinic, where an 11-year-old girl learned she
would begin what might be years of Ritalin therapy, and at a school
where teachers credit Ritalin with helping children conquer their
emotional and academic despair. A third story looks at Utah, the
state with the youngest population, a reputation for moral
conservatism _ and the highest per capita use of Ritalin in the
nation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her school principal had urged her mother to make
the four-hour drive from rural northern Michigan. Now 11-year-old
Chrissie sat in a tiny, windowless office where a psychologist
peppered her with questions.
   The morning would end with doctors at the Attention Deficit
Disorder Clinic of Children's Hospital telling Chrissie her
baffling problems at home and in school would mean treatment with
the stimulant Ritalin, quite likely for years.
   But first doctors tested Chrissie: spelling tests, math tests,
reading tests, questions about her family life. They probed her
moods, whether she ever felt like committing suicide (``once or
twice,'' she said.) They examined her school grades, read reports
from teachers.
   They even had Chrissie, a sliver-thin, pretty girl with straight
blond hair, draw a picture of herself. The 2-inch-high sketch spoke
volumes to the psychologist about the youngster's poor self-image.
   Finally the psychologist asked Chrissie for three wishes.
   ``A horse ranch,'' the girl said after several moments. ``A
happy life. And people who care who can help me through this tough
time.
   ``I haven't really been happy since I was 2 or so. I yell at my
parents. Later I wish I hadn't done it. They're very good to me. So
I haven't had a very happy life.''
   Chrissie, which is not the girl's real name, indeed had many
problems, the doctors concluded. But she hardly fit the popular,
often mistaken, stereotype of children who take Ritalin.
   First, boys are eight times more likely than girls to be
diagnosed as having ADD. Second, Chrissie wasn't ``bouncing off the
walls.'' In fact, many youngsters recommended for Ritalin treatment
are not discipline problems and appear calm in most situations.
   Chrissie, said psychologist Arthur Robin, is ``a classic case of
a kid whose ADD was not caught as a young kid.'' Pre-adolescents
and teen-agers who unexplainedly struggle with school for years
often arrive at ADD clinics deeply depressed as a result of their
attention problems.
   The key was her inability to complete tasks and concentrate.
Tests suggested she was weak in math, easily frustrated,
dangerously depressed, and had a poor self-image.
   Chrissie knows she has troubles. ``I have quite a problem paying
attention in school. I've had it since kindergarten,'' she told a
visitor in a brief break from testing. ``I sometimes just have to
get out of my seat. I go to the drinking fountain, and I'm not even
thirsty. It's weird.
   ``If I have a problem, I'd really like to know about it.''
   Fewer than 100 such ADD clinics operate around the country,
according to Wade Horn, a psychologist who heads one at Children's
Hospital National Medical Center in Washington, D.C. Nearly all
start with the assumption that ADD is essentially a physiological
disease that in most cases can be treated chemically.
   Some clinics simply juggle prescriptions, using placebos and
Ritalin or other stimulant drugs alternately to find the most
effective treatment. They leave the followup and monitoring to
others, often the family pediatrician.
   Others, like the Detroit clinic, employ pediatricians,
psychologists and social workers to look at the child in totality.
That means that counseling and changes in lessons or surroundings
are often part of the treatment. But at the heart of these clinics
is the conviction that Ritalin therapy helps most patients.
   Since it opened in September 1986, the ADD Clinic here has
examined some 600 patients and has a three-month waiting list, said
Dr. Sheldon Brenner, a pediatrician and co-director of the clinic.
At least three-quarters were diagnosed as having ADD, and about 85
percent of those were placed on medication, usually Ritalin.
   Once treatment begins, doctors rely on teacher questionnaires,
report cards and parents to monitor whether Ritalin is helping the
child in school and whether it is having side effects.
   Chrissie's teacher wrote this description of her on a Conners
Questionnaire, the standardized form used to evaluate children
suspected of having attention deficit disorder:
   ``Chrissie is not a behavior problem,'' her teacher wrote. ``I
just do not have her attention 90 percent of the time. ... On the
day we had our first bit of snow last fall, I was trying to help
her understand something. She looked at me and smiled, saying `I
wonder what my kitten thinks of snow? She never saw it before.'
Sometimes it seems her mind is way off somewhere else.''
   Chrissie and her mother sat expressionless as the doctors later
told them that Ritalin and psychological counseling ``should make a
difference.''
   Her mother expressed mild surprise over the prescription.
``Ritalin has a bad name,'' she said after the doctors had left the
room. ``I was somewhat surprised because I associated Ritalin with
hyperactivity.''
   How is Chrissie doing? After six weeks of Ritalin and
counseling, Chrissie's teachers told doctors she had shown mild
improvement in attention span and a marked improvement in her
ability to sit still and stick to school work. Even with an
increase in dosage, to 30 milligrams a day, she has exhibited no
side effects.
   Progress, but no quick miracles, then, for Chrissie. The Ritalin
therapy continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
