<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RIsforRitalinIII-School     04-06 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-R Is for Ritalin III-School,0881</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`R' Is for Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part III: At One Elementary School, They `Work Magic' With Ritalin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report; Recommended for side-by-side
use with PM-R Is for Ritalin III-Clinic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BIRMINGHAM, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Jane Easton's pupils takes
the drug Ritalin to calm his hyperactivity and help him pay
attention. She challenged a visitor to guess who.
   Chris was the obvious choice. Seated with three other boys at a
semicircular desk in a special education class at Scotch Elementary
School, the third-grader fidgeted in his chair, got up several
times to sharpen his pencil, drummed his fingers, asked questions
repeatedly and never seemed to hear the answers.
   The guess was wrong. Instead, the child on Ritalin was a slender
boy with flaming red hair who calmly sailed through a reading
comprehension quiz and listened attentively to a lesson on
homonyms. Easton says he's doing so well he probably will leave
handicapped classes forever in the fall.
   At Scotch Elementary, they believe in Ritalin _ and teachers
point to cases like these to vindicate their faith in the
controversial drug.
   Far from thinking Ritalin creates passive ``zombies,'' as some
critics have charged, teachers and parents alike in this affluent
northwest Detroit suburb seem convinced of Ritalin's track record
for turning emotional and academic despair into success.
   Grades and attention span often improve, and some youngsters who
might have spent entire school careers isolated in classes for the
disabled have managed to rejoin their regular peers with the help
of the drug.
   Most of all, teachers like Easton resent the assertion by some
that Ritalin is merely a cynical way for schools to silence problem
children while claiming they are trying to help them.
   ``I read that this is the way we treat kids we can't handle.
It's not true. It's just not true,'' said Easton, whose daughter
has taken the drug for four years.
   While an estimated 1-2 percent of the nation's 40 million
schoolchildren take Ritalin, Dr. Paul H. Wender, a Salt Lake City
psychiatrist and author of several books on attention deficit
disorder, or ADD, believes 3-to-10 percent of all children have
hyperactivity problems.
   At Scotch Elementary, approximately 5 percent of the 550 pupils
drop by principal Carl Childress's office each day to take a pill.
   Several elements help explain why Ritalin is commonplace at
Scotch Elementary; teachers and school administrators have attended
seminars and taken other training to recognize symptoms of ADD.
Area doctors are not only willing to prescribe Ritalin but also to
work with teachers and schools to monitor its success. And parents
generally seem to accept the professionalism, good faith and
judgment of the teachers and doctors.
   ``When you first start talking to parents about this, they're
devastated,'' said principal Carl Childress. ``Then 90 percent
react that it is a medical problem.''
   Childress tells of a youngster named George who has taken
Ritalin for two years. He had been assigned to a ``resource room,''
where handicapped children get individual instruction for part of
each day.
   ``He had an incident every day of losing his temper, punching
someone or screaming in vile terms,'' said Childress. ``Now he's
out of special education. He's a winner.''
   Childress, like other educators, insists ``we never recommend
medication.'' But that's only partly true. If the school's
psychologist, social worker or reading specialist believes a child
has ADD, they know which doctors will nearly always prescribe
Ritalin.
   At the top of the list is Dr. Ruth Robin, a pediatrician who
operates the Attention Deficit Center in nearby Southfield, Mich.
Schools from all over Michigan and northern Ohio recommend her, and
prospective patients often wait 6-8 weeks for an appointment. She
now treats 1,500 youngsters for ADD, some as young as 3. Almost
invariably, she prescribes Ritalin or similar medication.
   ``I work magic with the medicine,'' she said in an interview in
her office. ``I'm willing to try things.
   ``We're talking about large numbers of kids who are getting a
bum steer in life, from kindergarten on. Some look like couch
potatoes. They don't all look alike,'' she said.
   But even Ritalin's advocates admit it isn't always
well-monitored. Teachers are supposed to provide crucial
information enabling doctors to set the right dosage, or to
determine if drugs are necessary at all to academic success.
   Such monitoring is frequent when medication first begins. After
that, ``there really isn't that much to do unless there's a
problem,'' the doctor said.
   Childress said Robin and other ADD specialists typically send
teachers questionnaires to fill out for the first 2-4 weeks of
medication, then gradually less frequently until ``we feel we're on
a steady course. At a certain point we step out of the picture
unless the teacher notices a problem.''
   Still, Ritalin remains a ``last resort,'' said Childress.
Teachers might, for example, put distractible children in study
carrels _ desks with three sides blocked off so the child can't see
in front or to either side.
   But when ``we've exhausted all those things ... logged the
classroom observations,'' Childress said, ``we would just as soon
get a recommendation to try something else.''
</TEXT>
