<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Bomb,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Defuse Fire Bomb Planted In Department Store</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police defused an incendiary bomb planted in a
department store belonging to the Debenhams chain, which previously
has been targeted by animal rights activists for selling fur coats.
   The bomb was found Tuesday by an employee in the third-floor,
furniture section of Debenhams in Oxford Street, a busy shopping
thoroughfare in central London, shortly after the store closed at 6
p.m. (1 p.m. EDT), Scotland Yard said. The store was evacuated and
part of Oxford Street was closed to traffic.
   Inspector John Chilvers said a bomb disposal unit took nearly
three hours to defuse the device. He said police were investigating
whether the bomb was linked to the previous attacks by an animal
rights group.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility.
   Debenhams has been a target of firebomb and other attacks by the
Animal Liberation Front for more than four years.
