<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Amnesty-Libya     04-06 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Amnesty-Libya,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Urges Libya To Abolish Death Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed to the Libyan
people's congresses to support Col. Moammar Gadhafi's stated aim to
abolish the death penalty in the north African nation.
   The London-based human rights organization said the Libyan
leader called on the people's congresses to hold a special session
soon to discuss his proposed changes in human rights' laws,
including the abolition of the death penalty.
   The congresses are supposed to have absolute power over
government policy under the socialist system devised by Gadhafi in
1977.
   Amnesty International opposes the death penalty as cruel,
inhuman and degrading punishment.
   Its abolition, the organization said in a statement Tuesday,
would be a ``major step in the respect of human rights by the
Libyan Jamahiriya,'' or ``the masses,'' which is how Libya refers
to itself.
</TEXT>
