<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Austria-Iranian,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Reportedly Wounded In Chemical Gas Attack Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of more than 30 people flown to
Western Europe and New York for treatment of mustard gas poisoning
suffered in alleged chemical weapons attacks in the Persian Gulf
war has died, a doctor said.
   Zaindi, a 20-year-old Iranian volunteer soldier was one of the
most seriously injured patients brought to Europe by Iran on March
29.
   Dr. Gerhard Freilinger, head of Vienna's University Clinic
plastic surgery, said Zaindi had improved, but then got worse and
died of his injuries Tuesday.
   The plane made its first stop in Vienna, and Freilinger, who has
treated more than 30 alleged chemical weapons attack victims since
1984, had the Iranian removed from the plane for treatment in
Vienna because his condition was too serious for him to be able to
bear the continued trip.
   Iran charged the Iraqi air force in March dropped cyanide and
mustard gas bombs on three Kurdish towns in Iraq that had been
captured by Iran, killing 5,000 Kurds and injuring 5,000.
</TEXT>
