<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-USAToday     04-06 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-USA Today,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spiffy `USA Today - The Television Show' Previewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's fast, it's colorful, it's as spiffy as can
be. It's ``USA Today'' on TV.
   Executive producer Steve Friedman unveiled a prototype of the
syndicated, daily television show and his four-person anchor team
Tuesday at one of a series of news conferences, this one in the
Rainbow Room, upstairs from his old office at NBC where he was
executive producer of ``Today.''
   ``USA Today _ The Television Show'' premieres on Sept. 12, but
is already a hit, having been sold in 118 markets covering 85
percent of the country. That gives it, higher coverage than any
syndicated show except ``Wheel of Fortune,'' Friedman said.
   The promotional reel Friedman showed reporters promised stations
considering buying the show that it would take them ``into the
'90s.''
   ``It's a fast-paced world and I think a lot of the media hasn't
caught up,'' said Friedman, after showing the tape. The pace of the
promotional show, complete with commercials, was fast to spin heads.
   Not surprisingly, Friedman assured reporters that ``USA Today''
won't be a ``traditional'' news show but rather will rely on upbeat
human-interest stories, polls and interviews.
   Since it's based on the colorful, successful, young national
newspaper, it ``doesn't have any baggage from the past,'' he said.
``We don't have to worry about what Ed Murrow said.''
   The show is the first product from GTG Entertainment, the
partnership between former NBC Chairman Grant Tinker, who is also
former president of MTM Productions, and Gannett, the publisher of
USA Today and the nation's largest newspaper group. GTG is also
producing network entertainment shows.
   ``USA Today _ The Television Show'' will be a half hour daily,
an hour on weekends. The show will be fed to stations each day via
satellite at 4:30 p.m. Eastern time. Friedman said 96 of the
stations will broadcast the show in what he considers its ideal
time period, the hour between the evening news and the beginning of
prime time.
   Friedman has assembled a good-looking cast of network veterans
to anchor the four segments, based on the four sections of the
newspaper: Edie Magnus from ABC as ``Front Page'' anchor; Kenneth
Walker, also formerly with ABC, as ``Money'' editor; Bill Macatee
of NBC for ``Sports'' and Robin Young, also formerly with NBC, for
``Life.''
   The show will preview the next day's edition of ``USA Today,''
but not necessarily have the same stories as the newspaper.
   ``It will be topical, but to be successful it will have to be
different,'' said Magnus. ``We will be doing what would be the next
day's lead the night before.''
   Macatee suggested he might have coaches other than baseball
managers wear uniforms for a segment.
   ``Or let's have the head of an airline dress like a pilot for a
day to see how it fits, see how people react,'' he said.
   A daily poll will be the centerpiece of the show, Friedman said.
The promotional tape featured a poll on marriage, using clips from
movies to illustrate the results, for example, ``Body Heat''
illustrating a question about infidelity.
   Academy Award-winning composer John Barry, who wrote the theme,
was featured in an interview in the promotional tape describing the
music, much like the show, as having ``a happy, laid-back feeling,
but with a sense of urgency.''
   USA Today isn't the only newspaper getting into the act. The
Christian Science Monitor, which has a radio show, is holding a
news conference later this week to announce its own television show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0022 </DOCNO>
