<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GassingVictims     04-06 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gassing Victims,0808</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outlook Clouded For Poison Gas Victims of Iran-Iraq War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hands shielding swollen eyes from the glare of
television lights, the three little girls squirmed uncomfortably in
the hospital room as they were displayed as survivors of a poison
gas attack.
   The girls are among five victims being treated in the United
States for chemical burns to the lung, eyes and skin. Iran says
they are survivors of a March 16 chemical attack by Iraq on the
Kurdish village of Halabjah.
   Four of them met reporters Tuesday in an event organized by the
Iranian mission to the United Nations, the arena for a bitter
propaganda war between Iran and Iraq. The Persian Gulf enemies have
been fighting for 7{ years.
   One patient, Nazanin Hassan, 30, was not shown to reporters
because she is in the intensive care unit.
   The Tehran government says Iraq bombed its own citizens with
chemical weapons _ killing 5,000 and injuring 7,000 _ after members
of the restive Kurdish minority welcomed invading Iranian troops to
Halabjah.
   Mohamed Azizi, a 25-year-old university student, said Iraqi
forces attacked the village several times in response to Kurdish
unrest. But Azizi said even from the shelter of his basement, he
knew the March 16 attack was different.
   ``We smelled the gas,'' he explained through an intepreter. ``We
knew it was not the other kind of bomb,'' the ordinary kind.
   Azizi said from his hospital bed that when he ventured outside
hours later, he saw streets strewn with the victims of what doctors
in the United States suspect was mustard gas, a World War I weapon
outlawed worldwide since 1925.
   ``Any door you opened there were children, men and women, dying,
dead,'' Azizi said, his words punctuated by rough coughs. ``I saw a
lot of people in cars. As many as 10, 11, 12 in a car. They were
dying.''
   He said he and other stunned survivors began streaming out of
Halabjah.
   ``We tried to run out,'' Azizi said. ``We didn't want to see
that.''
   But he said that once outside, he was soon sickened by the gas.
   ``My eyes felt heavy. It was hard to breathe. Eight or nine
times I threw up. I smelled gas,'' he recounted.
   Doctors at St. John's Episcopal Hospital, in New York City's
borough of Queens, said all five of those brought to New York
suffered lung and eye damage and from burns. One child is also
showing signs of bone marrow damage, said Dr. Deborah
Lief-Dienstag, head of the pediatrics department.
   She said the long-term prognogis for a gassing victim is unclear.
   ``I can tell you what a gunshot wound is. I can tell you what's
going to happen to the patient,'' she said.
   ``But I don't know what's going to happen to these children. I
don't know what's going to happen to their lungs in six months and
I don't think anyone else does either, including all the experts
we've spoken to.''
   Dr. Lief-Dienstag's young patients were clearly uneasy when
Iranian officials escorted journalists to their room. Several
doctors expressed concern about infection. One, speaking on
condition he not be identified, said emphatically that the news
media visit ``wasn't our idea.''
   Iran transferred small contingents of survivors from hospitals
in Tehran to hospitals in major European cities and to St. John's.
   Dr. Meyd Atabaki, an Iranian who is an attending physician at
St. John's, said all five brought to New York had to be sedated at
first before they could be treated.
   ``They cried for 24 hours after they got here,'' Dr.
Lief-Dienstag said.
   Hospital officials say psychiatrists are following the progress
of all five patients, particularly the children, who were orphaned
by the attack.
   ``They are innocent bystanders who ... were in the wrong place
at the wrong time,'' Dr. Lief-Dienstag said of Javan Mohammed
Abdollah, 12, and her sister, Rezen Mohammed Abdollah, 9, and Kobra
Mohammad, also 9.
   Dr. Victor Burnett, head of the department of medicine, said he
and the other doctors at St. John's consulted experts in chemical
injuries from the University of Ghent in Belgium and from the U.S.
Army.
   Amir Zamani, a first secretary at the Iranian mission, said Iran
sent about 100 victims to hospitals abroad because Iran's hospitals
ran out of room.
   The United Nations, which earlier confirmed several Iraqi
attacks with outlawed mustard gas and nerve gas during the war, has
sent a team to investigate the Halabjah attack.
   Iraq, meanwhile, is accusing Iran of using the banned weapons.
On Monday, it asked for a U.N. team to go to Baghdad to examine 88
soldiers it says were gassed.
</TEXT>
