<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Italy-Strikes     04-06 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Italy-Strikes,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Airport Strikes Announced In Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ground personnel at Rome's Leonardo Da Vinci airport
announced they will stage 12-hour strikes on April 16 and 24.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the strikes are expected to
force the cancellation or postponement of most flights on those two
days.
   Union leaders on Tuesday said the strike would not interfere
with flights for emergency, military or government purposes.
Flights to and from Italy's islands also will not be interrupted.
   Waves of recent airline and railway strikes in Italy over the
last five months have made traveling difficult to plan.
   Ground crews have been negotiating for a new contract for eight
months. For the last five months, the crews have staged periodic
strikes.
   They are demanding better working conditions in the control
towers, salary increases and fewer hours in the work week.
