<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Ferries     04-06 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Ferries,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes, Lost Traffic Mean Lost Revenue At Dover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dover Harbor Board said the nine-week
ferry workers' strike at the English Channel port coupled with a
two-week French seamen's dispute has cost the board $3.8 million in
lost revenue.
   The loss is due to a sharp reduction in passenger, tourist
vehicle and freight traffic and lost ferry berthing fees, said
Jonathan Sloggett, the port's managing director.
   ``We are implementing a number of ways of saving money such as
reducing budgets, canceling non-essential work and not taking on
seasonal staff,'' Sloggett said.
   The 2,300 members of the National Union of Seamen employed by P
and O European Ferries at Dover voted last weekend to continue
their strike over staffing levels. French ferry workers called off
their strike on the Sealink ferry company's Dover to Calais route
over the Easter holiday weekend.
</TEXT>
