<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ColoradoCaucuses     04-06 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colorado Caucuses,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Complains About Colorado Democrats' Handling Of Caucus
Count</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse Jackson,
narrowly outpolled by rival Michael Dukakis in Colorado's caucuses,
is criticizing the state party here for the slow pace of its count
and the party chief's ties to Dukakis.
   The Democratic caucuses were held across Colorado on Monday
night, but significant returns were not reported until Tuesday
afternoon by the state Democratic Party.
   Even before Dukakis pulled out his victory, Jackson accused
state Democratic chairman Buie Seawell of being ``biased and
politically unethical'' and ``deliberately controlling the
process'' by remaining as party chairman after publicly supporting
Dukakis.
   ``The state chairman endorsed Mr. Dukakis,'' Jackson told
reporters in Kenosha, Wis., on Tuesday. ``You cannot very well be a
fair referee and coaching another player.''
   He added that the party's ``long and slow count represents a
certain ineptness. ... It heightens suspicions.''
   Seawell countered that ``the Reverend Jackson is just wrong. I
have never known him to just attack for his own political gain, but
that appears to be what this is.''
   He said his staff of six people had worked until 3 a.m. Tuesday
and was back on the job by 8:30 a.m. that day.
   Jackson also contended that Colorado Democrats had changed 30
caucus sites as late as Friday or Saturday without telling his
campaign. ``It comes very close to obstructing justice,'' he said.
   Jackson's campaign manager, Gerald Austin, complained about the
Colorado situation Tuesday to Paul Kirk, chairman of the Democratic
National Committee.
   DNC spokeswoman Julie Anbender said the committee had contacted
the state party and ``they've assured us that they're doing
everything they can to get the results out.''
   Returns from 77 percent of Colorado's 2,784 precincts showed the
Massachusetts governor leading with 4,029 delegates, or 44.3
percent, to Jackson's 3,528 delegates or 36.5 percent.
   The uncommitted delegates totaled 1,547, or 16.3 percent, and
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. received 236 delegates, or 2.7
percent.
   If the caucus results hold up at Colorado's congressional
district and state Democratic conventions in the next few weeks,
Dukakis would win 20 national convention delegates, while Jackson
would gain 17 and another eight would be uncommitted. Those
calculations are based on returns from 77 percent of the precincts
in the state.
   On the Republican side, Vice President George Bush swept most of
Colorado's 36 GOP delegates to the Republican National Convention,
cornering over 70 percent of the vote in straw polls taken at
caucuses Monday night.
   Actual GOP delegate selection will come at congressional
district conventions and the state convention in June.
   Dukakis and Jackson had hoped to use the Colorado caucuses as a
springboard for Tuesday's Wisconsin Democratic primary.
   Dukakis went on to win that contest, but since there was no
clear Colorado victor when the Wisconsin polls opened Tuesday
morning, it was not thought to have had much of an effect.
   Still, the Dukakis campaign hailed the Colorado win. Bob
Johnson, a spokesman for the campaign in Colorado, said the victory
demonstrates ``that Mike Dukakis can win in any region of the
country.''
   Johnson also said he thought the count was fair. ``To the best
of my knowledge, the party officials conducted the caucuses in a
fair and appropriate manner,'' he said.
   Dukakis himself, commenting on the Colorado contest to reporters
in Boston, said as far as he knew, ``it was run fairly and well.''
   Colorado will send 51 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, with six of them ``super delegates'' who include
Seawell and Gov. Roy Romer, another Dukakis supporter. The Monday
night caucuses began a complicated, four-tier process of selecting
45 of those delegates.
</TEXT>
