<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSBabies     04-06 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Babies,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children With AIDS Run Into Red Tape, Funding Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who try to care for children with AIDS
told a government panel that red tape and a lack of funding make a
painful job even more trying.
   ``These most innocent victims of the AIDS crisis have the right
to live and smile if only for a short time,'' Bronx, N.Y., social
worker Dolores Smithies told the White House AIDS commission on
Tuesday.
   Smithies, who has four children of her own, spends her evenings
raising money to provide care for children with AIDS. Also
appearing before the commission were a Harlem physician who asked
the panel to make it easier for young AIDS victims to receive
Medicaid coverage, and a single Virginia woman having trouble
taking in a second AIDS-stricken child.
   Dr. Elaine Abrams, assistant professor of Clinical Pediatrics at
New York's Harlem Hospital, said her hospital has cared for 37
infants with AIDS even though it gets no money for the care from
public or private sources.
   Abrams told of a 9-year-old child whose mother died of AIDS six
months ago and who now lives with her grandmother.
   The physician said the child does not automatically qualify for
Medicaid just by having the virus, and that to certify her as
having the disease itself would result in her being taken from her
grandmother and placed in line for foster care even though that
would not be in the child's best interest.
   ``Help me get this child on Medicaid so I don't have to sneak
her into the hospital when she needs treatment,'' Abrams said.
``Each child with HIV (AIDS virus) infection needs Medicaid whether
the parent makes a million dollars or zero dollars.''
   Michelle Valentine, the young Virginia woman adopting a baby
girl with AIDS, told the commission she is having trouble getting
permission to take in a second child.
   ``You're single, we can't consider you,'' she said she has been
told.
   Then, in exasperation, she said: ``The typical young yuppie
couple wants one of these kids like they want a hole in the head.''
   Smithies said child placement agencies should rethink the family
criteria they use when placing children with AIDS.
   She cited instances, for example, ``where gay men have been
absolutely extraordinary as care givers.''
   ``We have to expand our vision of what a family is,'' Abrams
added.
   The three women were among 14 witnesses heard by the commission
during the first of four days of hearings this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
