<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Eastern     04-06 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Retreats From Plan To Sell Boston-New York-Washington
Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines will appeal an injunction and
contempt citation even though it has dropped plans to sell its
Northeast shuttle to another subsidiary of Texas Air Corp.,
Eastern's president says.
   On Tuesday, U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt accepted the
company's report of compliance with an order he issued last month
and said Eastern will no longer be in contempt once it informs
employees it has dropped plans to sell the shuttle.
   On March 10, Pratt had found Eastern in civil contempt of an
earlier injunction issued in a labor dispute with the International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   At a brief hearing, Eastern's president, Philip Bakes, said the
financially troubled carrier had abandoned the sale plans.
   Bakes assured the judge that Eastern would comply with the
order. But outside the courtroom, the airline executive reiterated
the company's plan to appeal the contempt citation and the
injunction that bars the shuttle sale.
   Air Shuttle LP, the subsidiary that was to buy the Boston-to-New
York-to-Washington shuttle, withdrew its application with the
Transportation Department to complete the $225 million sale, Bakes
said.
   Pratt ruled that the proposed sale violated a 1987 injunction
that required Eastern to maintain current working conditions. That
injunction prohibited Eastern from transferring ground crews to
another subsidiary.
   The IAM contended that the proposed transactions were intended
to undermine the union.
   Bakes told the judge the company acted on advice of its lawyers
and ``never believed ... we were violating an order of the court.''
</TEXT>
