<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0402,0608</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Boss and dropped word `said' in 2nd graf on Scholl obit.
AMs separate moved as a0824 on Shearman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Thomas Shearman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Broadus Shearman, a publisher of
the Lake Charles American Press who crusaded against gambling in
the 1950s, died Monday. He was 94.
   Shearman entered the newspaper business as an advertising
salesman for The Chicago Tribune in 1914. He bought the Lake
Charles paper in 1943 and acquired the Roswell (N.M.) Daily Record
in 1933 and the Hobbs (N.M.) Daily Sun and the Trinidad (Colo.)
Chronicle News in 1936.
   As a result of his crusade against gambling in southwestern
Louisiana, he and four other journalists were indicted by a special
Calcasieu Parish grand jury on charges they defamed 16 public
officials and three admitted gamblers.
   A special judge appointed to hear the case acquitted the five,
saying every allegation made in articles and editorials was without
malice and was either true or could reasonably be believed to be
true. With legislative help casinos and slot machines were
eventually eliminated.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Scholl</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Trevor ``Jack'' Scholl, a
songwriter who wrote such hits as ``Loving You the Way I Do'' and
``Making Love, Mountain Style,'' died March 25 at age 85.
   A lyricist and scriptwriter, Scholl often collaborated with
Eubie Blake and M.K. Jerome, said David Petrone of the American
Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers. He spent 10 years as
a staff songwriter for Warner Bros., 10 years with MGM and also
wrote songs for Columbia and Universal Pictures.
   Other songs written by Scholl include ``Throw Another Log on the
Fire,'' ``The Gay Parisienne'' with Sigmund Romberg; ``The Wish
That I Wish Tonight,'' ``The Glad Song'' made famous by Teresa
Brewer; ``The Old Apple Tree,'' ``You, You Darling'' and ``My
Little Buckaroo.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Susie Marmon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA PUEBLO, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susie Rayos Marmon, born 35 years
before New Mexico became a state and later one of its educators for
almost half a century, died Monday. She was 110.
   Mrs Marmon attended Bloomsburg State College in Pennsylvania,
graduating in 1906. She returned to what was then the territory of
New Mexico and taught school at the pueblos of Laguna and Isleta
for nearly 50 years. Among her former pupils were several pueblo
governors and tribal leaders.
   State and Indian leaders last year joined in paying tribute to
Mrs. Marmon a week after her 110th birthday. The governors of 14
pueblos joined state officials and members of her family in the
celebration at Laguna Pueblo.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hazel Garland</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McKEESPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazel Garland, a pioneering black woman
journalist, died Tuesday of a heart attack at age 75.
   Mrs. Garland was editor-in-chief of the Pittsburgh Courier from
1974 to 1977. She had been with the Courier since 1943 in a variety
of jobs, including columnist, consultant and writer of ``Video
Vignettes.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>W. Russell Boss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   W. Russell Boss, former president
and chairman of A.T. Cross Co., manufacturer of topshelf pens and
mechanical pencils, died Monday. He was 79.
   Boss went to work as sales manager and treasurer of Cross in
1937, shortly after the death of his father Walter Russell Boss
Sr., owner of the Rhode Island-based company.
   Over the next 27 years, Boss rose to become chairman and
president of the company and helped it evolve from a private,
family-owned business with a dozen employees to a public company
with $155.4 million in revenues and more than 1,400 emplyees
worldwide.
</TEXT>
