<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     04-06 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Agrees To Pay $750,000 Penalty To Settle Antitrust Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York real-estate magnate Donald Trump says
he agreed to pay a $750,000 civil penalty stemming from his
attempted takeover of two companies in order to avoid a long, drawn
out legal battle with the government.
   The payment settles a suit filed by the Federal Trade Commission
over his 1986 stock purchases in Holiday Corp. and Bally
Manufacturing Corp.
   Both cases involved the purchase of stock options through Bear,
Stearns & Co., which, in turn, bought actual shares. The FTC
contends the exercise of stock options was covered by rules
requiring that buyers notify the government before purchasing more
than $15 million worth of voting stock in a company and wait 30
days before completing the transaction.
   Trump said Tuesday he was advised by his lawyers and the
investment firm that stock options were exempt and he should be
reimbursed by Bear, Stearns. A Bear, Stearns spokeswoman had no
immediate comment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Express Mail To Reach Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Express Mail will be extended to the Soviet
Union on May 1, but the special overnight service will be limited
to business correspondence and parcels sent to Moscow, the U.S.
Postal Service says.
   Letters and goods being sent to private people will not be
covered, Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank said Tuesday.
   Soviets will be able to send high-speed mail to the United
States in return.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Senator Denies He Called Defense Secretary, Joint Chiefs Cowards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Sen. Alfonse D'Amato denies calling
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and the Joint Chiefs of Staff
``cowards'' for not doing more to oust Panamanian strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``My recollection of the conversation was that (I said) the
inaction would be perceived as cowardly,'' D'Amato said Tuesday
through a spokeswoman.
   Carlucci made the allegations in a letter to D'Amato that
followed a telephone conversation the two had last week. After
learning D'Amato had denied the alleged name-calling, Defense
Department spokesman Col. Arnold Williams said, ``I think the
letter probably speaks for itself.''
   In the phone call, D'Amato had complained that the defense
secretary was willing to send 3,200 soldiers to Honduras but would
not send a senior military officer to Panama to tell Noriega to
leave, said Jack Kinnicutt, a spokesman for D'Amato.
</TEXT>
