<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--LATimes-Editor     04-06 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--LA Times-Editor,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffey Becomes Executive Editor of Los Angeles Times</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C. Shelby Coffey III has been named executive
editor of the Los Angeles Times in a promotion that puts him in
line to succeed Editor William F. Thomas, who is to retire next
year, Publisher Tom Johnson says.
   Coffey, 41, deputy associate editor of the Times, assumes his
new post next Monday and will report to Thomas during the
transition, Johnson said.
   Coffey will have responsibility for all news departments except
the editorial pages, which will continue to report to Thomas.
   ``Bill Thomas will retire in 1989, after 18 splendid years as
editor. This announcement is being made now to provide for an
orderly transition,'' Johnson said Monday.
   Coffey joined The Washington Post in 1968 as a sports writer and
subsequently became editor of the Post's magazine, editor of its
Style section, deputy managing editor and assistant managing editor
for national news.
   He became editor of U.S. News & World Report in 1985 and editor
of the Dallas Times Herald in 1986, before joining the Times that
year.
</TEXT>
