<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BinderTwins     04-06 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Binder Twins,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Siamese Twins Going Home To West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benjamin and Patrick Binder, who spent their
first seven months joined at the head, are seriously underdeveloped
but have the potential to lead normal lives, said doctors preparing
to release the babies from the hospital.
   The separated Siamese twins, now 14 months old, will return to
Germany in the next few days, physicians at Johns Hopkins Hospital
said Tuesday. Benjamin should begin crawling soon and will go home
to Ulm, West Germany, with his parents. Patrick will go to a German
hospital for observation.
   ``There is no reason for us to think they will not continue to
improve,'' said Dr. Ben Carson, a member of the medical team that
has treated the infants since they were admitted in August.
   ``They have made very substantial progress in the past few
months and ... we're very hopeful the potential will culminate in
normal existence,'' Carson said at a news conference.
   However, Dr. Mark Rogers stressed that the boys are not now
normal. Their development is equivalent to that of 2-to-5-month-old
babies.
   Carson said he was unwilling to project the mental and physical
level the boys will reach, but when the twins return here for
evaluation next year, doctors will be able to predict fairly
accurately the boys' future development.
   The twins have had several setbacks since they were separated in
a 22-hour operation during the Labor Day weekend by a 70-member
medical team. In October, their temperatures rose inexplicably for
several days. The latest occurred March 13 when Patrick choked on
formula fed to him through a nasal tube.
   Rogers said it's unknown if the incident will have long-term
effects, although Patrick had reached the point of turning over
before the incident and has not returned to that level.
   Benjamin is at about the level as when he entered the hospital
and is expected to begin crawling soon, the doctors said.
   Because they were joined at the head, the twins were not
normally developed when they arrived. The trauma of the operation
and long hospital stay account at least partially for the
developmental lag, Carson said.
   At the time of the separation operation, doctors had given it a
50-50 chance of success.
   ``Certainly in terms of a medical or technical feat, it has
clearly been successful,'' Carson said.
   He said there were 48 cases in medical history of Siamese twins
joined at the head. This was the first separation where both twins
lived. Their kind of joining _ at the back of the head with a
shared vein _ was the rarest, he said.
   In February, doctors implanted titanium mesh plates in the
opening at the back of their heads, created by the separation of
their joined skulls and a shared vein.
   Benjamin has a bald spot on the back of his head from the
operation, `but if he grows his hair long he can comb it down,''
said Dr. Craig Dufresne. Patrick has a full head of hair.
   The twins' parents have refused to speak with reporters here.
Before the separation at Hopkins they sold their story to a West
German magazine.
   Their mother, Theresia Parlagi Binder, has been at the hospital
with the boys and has taken Benjamin outside in a carriage, doctors
said Tuesday.
   Rogers said the doctors donated all their time and care and
Hopkins treated the boys at no cost except for a small portion of
the about $800,000 expense covered by German government insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CrackWars Bjt   04-06 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack Wars, Bjt,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crack Cocaine Wars Trigger Violence, Fear</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite police declarations of war on
cheap, potent crack cocaine, drug turf wars are transforming the
city's low-income housing projects into twilight zones of violence,
death and terror.
   ``Families are selling (crack), families are using,'' said
Charlotte Tillman, director of the Bayview-Hunters Point Foundation
Youth Drug counseling. ``It's a way of life _ survival in the
projects.''
   Her program has 36 clients, a waiting list of 18 and has to turn
away referrals. Tillman, a social worker for 23 years, said the
crack situation is the worst she's ever seen _ and there's no end
in sight.
   ``We're losing a generation of young people,'' Tillman said.
``In one night you can make at least $400 off one person buying all
night. (On) heroin you nod out after a couple hundred dollars'
(worth of the drug). On crack you go on for days or as long as your
heart can stand it.''
   Crack, a rock-like, smokeable form of cocaine that goes for as
little as $5 for a whitish pebble, is intensely addictive and
potentially deadly to users, dealers and anyone crossing their
paths.
   On Jan. 22, Daniel Foster visited his old Hunters Point
neighborhood, stepping off a bus just after midnight into a crowd
of men and women, many high on crack.
   ``They asked him if he was a cop,'' said police Inspector Earl
Sanders. ``He told them, `No,' and kept walking. Then they asked
him if he was from Sunnydale (turf of a rival gang), but when he
said, `No,' someone in the crowd said he was lying. Then they began
to chase him.''
   Police said someone fired a pistol at least four times, hitting
Foster once in the back. He died less than an hour later.
   On Jan. 29, police broke up a battle between two competing gangs
in a Mission District housing project. There were 32 shots fired
from weapons such as an M-16 rifle, 12-gauge shotgun and handguns.
   On Jan. 17, a 13-year-old retarded boy in the Potrero Annex
housing project three blocks from Mayor Art Agnos' home was fatally
shot by police, already tense from gang violence, who mistook his
toy gun for a real one.
   Since last fall, when the city set up a crack cocaine task force
of police, the state Justice Department and U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration, officers have made 5,506 arrests for drug sales and
possession.
   They have seized more than 400 pounds of cocaine, $2.7 million
in cash and 302 guns, said police Lt. Jim Molinari.
   ``We do put organizations out of business ... but somebody else
always seems to pick up the banner and carry along. I think we're
failing, quite frankly,'' said Jerry Smith of the California Bureau
of Narcotics Enforcement.
   The city has 47 projects with 6,800 units and 17,000 residents,
but its security force merged with city police five years ago
because of budget constraints. During the past year, the city has
doubled its narcotics officers to 157 and the state recently
assigned 18 more narcotics agents to the region.
   Betty Brooks, a 20-year resident of Potrero Annex and a San
Francisco Housing Authority commissioner, said residents live in
constant fear.
   ``Everyone in the area has been victimized by the shootings, the
rash of burglaries,'' she said. ``No one has gone untouched in some
manner. I mean, you have to get to your car, to the bus stop.''
   The Rand Corp. ranks San Francisco No. 5 nationally among major
cities in cocaine-related hospital admissions, with 2.90 for every
1,000.
   At San Francisco General, Dr. Don Wong said that like other
metropolitan public hospitals, 1 in 10 of the approximately 200
infants born there each month are addicted because of maternal drug
use.
   The city has 11 foster homes to care for 17 ``medically
fragile'' infants suffering from drug, alcohol or other medical
problems. There are two or three newborns always on the waiting
list, said spokesman Jan Esbaugh.
   ``Practically all drug-addicted babies we are now seeing ... are
at least in part cocaine babies,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Press Bjt   04-06 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Press, Bjt,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Newspaper Suspends Publication; Blames Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa,
which reopened six months ago after a government-ordered shutdown,
said it will cease publishing indefinitely today because the
Sandinistas have withheld newsprint.
   The leftist government, which controls the purchase and sale of
newsprint in Nicaragua, said its supply was exhausted and claimed
it had warned newspapers to conserve paper until a new shipment
arrives later this month.
   ``La Prensa suspends publication,'' said the banner headline in
Tuesday's editions of the afternoon newspaper. ``Future undecided
because of state control of paper,'' read another headline.
   ``We don't have paper to publish tomorrow or on the following
days because the government alleges that there isn't any paper in
the country, but we know there is,'' said Cristiana Chamorro,
assistant director of La Prensa.
   The Ministry of Industry said in a statement in Tuesday morning
papers that it didn't have newsprint because a shipment scheduled
for March has been delayed. It said a shipment was expected by
April 17. ``Once this shipment is received, the Ministry of
Industry will proceed to distribute paper proportionally according
to the established mechanisms,'' it said.
   The ministry said it told La Prensa and two other newspapers, El
Nuevo Diario and Barricada, that ``the contraction of paper for the
year had suffered delays and that all possible efforts were being
made to assure the first shipment during the month of May.''
   It said the government had urged the papers to take precautions
against using up their stockpiles before the end of that month. The
pro-government Barricada said it, too, was running low on paper,
but planned to publish today.
   Miss Chamorro said La Prensa was told to hold on until March,
not the end of May. She said the paper shortage marks the first
time La Prensa has been forced to interrupt service because of the
government since it was allowed to reopen Oct. 1, 1987 after a
15-month shutdown. The paper was allowed to reopen under the terms
of a regional peace plan signed by the Sandinistas.
   La Prensa said the paper shortage ``could be avoided if we were
permitted to handle imports ourselves.''
   The government, saying La Prensa was promoting U.S. aggression
in this war-torn country, forced the newspaper to cease operations
June 26, 1986.
   ``La Prensa, acting as a voice for the interests of a powerful
aggressor, has been elevating its levels of provocation (and)
disinformation, through trying to justify North American
aggression,'' the government said at the time.
   The newspaper, whose mottos are ``Serving truth and justice''
and ``Without press liberty, there is no liberty,'' has been a
vocal opponent of the Sandinista regime and has suffered censorship
and shutdowns many times before.
   Its directors say the Sandinistas betrayed the country after the
1979 revolution that toppled the rightist regime of the late
Anastasio Somoza.
   ``Nicaragua is at war because the Marxist-Leninist government
betrayed the Nicaraguan people by deviating from the original idea
of the revolution,'' Violeta Chamorro, La Prensa co-owner, said
after the 1986 shutdown.
   Her son, Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, lives in Miami and is a leader
of the Contra rebels who with U.S. aid have been trying for more
than six years to oust the Sandinistas.
   La Prensa, founded March 2, 1926, is Nicaragua's oldest
newspaper. It suffered censorship, repression and shutdowns during
the Somoza regime, too.
   Violeta Chamorro is the widow of Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, La
Prensa's former director who was slain in 1977. The newspaper
offices were destroyed in the revolution and La Prensa was rebuilt
only to suffer a major ideological division among its editors
shortly afterward.
   About 80 percent of the staff, including Pedro Joaquin
Chamorro's brother, Xavier, left to establish the newspaper El
Nuevo Diario.
   Cristiana Chamorro, daughter of Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, said La
Prensa didn't circulate during Holy Week because of a shortage of
newsprint.
   ``What's strange about the case is that the newspapers Barricada
and El Nuevo Diario have published as normal,'' she said.
   Barricada, the official voice of the National Sandinista
Liberation Front, and El Nuevo Diario, the pro-government
newspaper, didn't publish for four days over the Easter holidays,
as is customary in Nicaragua.
   A secretary for Barricada director Carlos Fernando Chamorro said
the newspaper also is running short of paper, but plans to publish
today. She spoke on condition of anonymity. Barracada has loaned
newsprint to La Prensa before.
</TEXT>
