<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SequoiaLogging     04-06 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sequoia Logging,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Logging Halt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to clear hundreds of square miles of
timber around giant redwoods in Sequoia National Forest was halted
by a federal appeals court, which said the government approved the
logging too hastily.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' ruling on Tuesday
came too late to block logging of about half the non-redwood timber
in widely scattered areas of the forest. A different panel of the
court refused to halt that operation last December while the appeal
was pending.
   ``If you were a tourist in a redwood grove of the Sequoia
National Forest, instead of finding a lush natural-vegetation
forest you would find dirt and redwood trees alone,'' said Ralph
Bradley, a lawyer for the Sierra Club, which went to court last May
to block the logging.
   ``They're going in with tractors and removing everything from
brush to pine to oak,'' he said.
   The court ordered a ban on further logging in seven tracts in
the forest 200 miles south of San Francisco, saying the government
approved an untested logging plan without a proper environmental
analysis.
   An industry spokesman, however, claimed victory because all
logging was not banned around the towering sequoias, some of them
400 to 500 years old.
   ``The forest is not shut down and the mills are going to
continue to operate,'' said Michael Haglund, who represented Sierra
Forest Products and Sequoia Forest Industries. ``This is a much
more limited injunction than the Sierra Club sought. It's much more
of a victory for us than it is for them.''
   The Sierra Club went to court after the U.S. Forest Service
decided that nine timber sale contracts would cause no significant
damage and would not require full-scale environmental impact
statements assessing the effects on the forest.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Price last fall refused to halt the
logging, saying the dispute was one over management of the forest.
The environmental group appealed.
   Haglund said Tuesday's injunction prevents logging of about 9
million board-feet of timber, at least temporarily until an
environmental plan is developed. In a five-year plan covering the
entire forest, the Forest Service proposes logging of 80 million to
90 million board-feet a year, Haglund said.
   The Sierra Club had hoped the court would address the five-year
plan for the entire forest, a subject not mentioned in the ruling.
But Bradley said the ruling at least will require the Forest
Service to take review the plan.
   In approving the clear-cutting plan, the Forest Service said it
would help to regenerate the redwoods by creating areas of bare
mineral soil and sunlight. But the court quoted a professional
forester as saying the method was experimental and unproven.
   Bradley said experts have told him it ultimately would destroy
the redwoods.
   ``By tractor-logging, almost assuredly you will end up with
damage to the roots ... and often exposure of the roots,'' he said.
``The other problem is tremendous soil compaction. The water that
normally would hit the ground and percolate down and provide
nourishment instead erodes off of the land.''
</TEXT>
