<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Democratic Hopefuls Set for NYC Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopefuls Gov. Michael
Dukakis of Massachusetts, Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee, Jesse
Jackson and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon will participate in a live
April 14 debate in New York.
   WCBS-TV and Newsday, the two news organizations sponsoring the
debate, said in a joint announcement Tuesday that the four have
accepted invitations to the debate five days before the pivotal New
York state primary.
   The live hour-long debate will consist of questions from
reporters _ one from WCBS-TV, one from Newsday; questions among the
candidates; and closing statements from each candidate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunn Says He Could Be Elected If Democrats Nominate Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn said if he were to
emerge from a brokered Democratic National Convention this summer
with the party's nomination, he would go on to win the presidency.
   ``If I were nominated, I think I'd be elected,'' Nunn said
Tuesday after a speech to college students in Cochran.
   However Nunn told a Dublin gathering he's not likely to get the
nomination.
   ``I think it's most likely that someone running now will get the
nomination,'' said Nunn. ``But it's not impossible for someone
who's not running to get the nomination.
   ``But if that happens, it's not likely to be somebody from the
moderate-conservative wing of the Democratic Party,'' he noted.
``It's more likely to be someone who would come from the more
liberal wing of the Democratic Party.
   ``Whether it's Rev. (Jesse) Jackson or (Massachusetts) Gov.
(Michael) Dukakis or anyone else, if they don't go to the
convention with a majority, I don't think they ought to be
guaranteed they're going to get one,'' he said. ``The purpose of
the convention is to get the very best nominee for the Democratic
Party.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dole's Remaining New Jersey Supporters Rally Around Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With their candidate out of the
presidential race, the leaders of Kansas Sen. Bob Dole's New Jersey
campaign have formally thrown their support to Vice President
George Bush.
   With the announcement Tuesday, virtually everyone in New
Jersey's Republican establishment is now publicly backing Bush's
bid for the White House.
   ``The code word of the day is unity,'' former state
Transportation Commissioner Roger Bodman, the vice chairman of
Bush's New Jersey campaign, said at a news conference.
   Four of the most visible Dole supporters in New Jersey attending
the news conference wearing Bush buttons, included Assembly
Majority Leader Garabed `Chuck' Haytaian, who had been co-chairman
of Dole's campaign in the Garden State, former state Transportation
Secretary John Sheridan, who had been Dole's New Jersey campaign
manager, State Sen. Richard Zimmer and Assemblyman John T.
Hendrickson Jr.
   Republican Rep. Marge S. Roukema, another leader of Dole's New
Jersey drive, did not attend the news conference but she has phoned
Bush to express her support for him, fellow Republicans said.
   Two weeks ago Gov. Thomas H. Kean and the state's county
Republican chairmen formally endorsed Bush's candidacy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Governor Predicts Democrats Would Bar Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, preacher of the
Republican Party's ``politics of inclusion,'' says he believes
Democratic leaders will do all they can to keep Jesse Jackson from
getting the presidential nomination.
   Kean, who is mentioned as a GOP vice presidential possibility,
said he believes Democratic ``super delegates'' would team to block
Jackson's nomination.
   The super delegates are national, state and local leaders
allowed by party rules to remain uncommitted until the Democrats'
convention, which begins July 18 in Atlanta.
   Kean, speaking to reporters here, said he believes Jackson's
candidacy would be opposed because party leaders believe a black
can't win the White House, and because of Jackson's sometimes
radical ideas.
   ``They don't think he can win, and they don't want him as
president,'' Kean said.
   Kean said he believes Jackson can capture enough delegates in
upcoming New York, New Jersey and California primary elections to
keep him in numerical competition with Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, the party's other possible presidential contender.
</TEXT>
