<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens 1stLd-Writethru a0439 04-06 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0439,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holiday Viewers Choose British Royalty Over American Immigrants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to include reference to A.C. Nielsen Co.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday television viewers opted for a love
story about British royalty over a tale of American immigrants
starring Sophia Loren, but part of the network audience simply
tuned out.
   Easter Sunday was a battle of the network movies, with CBS
handily winning over NBC. That didn't keep NBC from winning the
week, though, its fifth straight and 24th in the 30-week season,
which ends in two weeks.
   For the week that ended Sunday, NBC had an average rating of
14.6. ABC had 12.8 and CBS 12.6, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
The season-to-date averages are: NBC 16.2, ABC 13.8, CBS 13.5. CBS
is finishing in last place in prime time for the first time ever.
   The ``CBS Evening News,'' however, continued in first place,
adding to the consternation of NBC, which has seen ``Nightly News''
fall from first to third in the three-way network news race this
season.
   In the most recent ratings, the ``CBS Evening News'' had a
rating of 10.5; ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 10.3; and ``NBC
Nightly News'' 9.0.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions.
   The top-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``The Cosby
Show'' NBC, with a 25.1 rating; ``A Different World'' NBC;
``Cheers'' NBC; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC; ``Golden Girls'' NBC;
``ALF'' NBC; ``The Wonder Years'' ABC; ``Matlock'' NBC; ``Growing
Pains'' ABC; and ``Addicted to His Love'' ABC.
   The three networks lost viewers on Easter Sunday. The
three-network share, or percentage of the viewing audience, is an
average 71 for the season. On Sunday it was 67. It was 69 for the
week.
   ``The Woman He Loved,'' the story of King Edward VIII's
abdication to marry American divorcee Wallis Warfield Simpson won
the night for CBS. The movie, starring Jane Seymour and Anthony
Andrews, had a rating of 14.5 and a 25 share and ranked 27th.
   But the highest-rated made-for-TV movie was last Monday's
``Addicted to His Love'' on ABC, which was 10th with an 18.1 rating
and 29 share.
   ABC came in second for the night with ``Superman II'' followed
by a news special, ``The Unruly Dragon.''
   NBC launched the two-part ``The Fortunate Pilgrim,'' starring
Sophia Loren, on Sunday, but it got a 13.1 and 22 share and ranked
40th.
   NBC attributed the low rating to the holiday and a poor start on
the evening with a repeat of an Andy Williams special that was dead
last in the network rankings.
   That showing also contributed to the low rating for a repeat
``Family Ties,'' a formerly top-10 show that landed in the bottom
10 last week.
   Saturday's NCAA basketball semifinals on CBS ranked 38th, but
apparently gave a boost to ``West 57th,'' which had a 20 share and
wasn't among the bottom 10 for a change. NBC won the night with
repeats.
</TEXT>
