<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-06 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Brushes Aside Wisconsin Loss, Says Has Momentum For New
York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson says he is going on
to New York's big primary with momentum and a broadening base of
white support despite falling short in Wisconsin, where he had
hoped to claim an important second Northern victory over Michael
Dukakis.
   ``I'm a long-distance runner,'' Jackson said Tuesday, trying to
look beyond the disappointment of two loses to Dukakis in two
days.``It is a 50-state, decathalon event.
   ``I'm not inclined to pull the flower out of the vase after
every race to see if the flower's still growing,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson lost to Dukakis, 47 percent to 28 percent, in Wisconsin,
a traditionally liberal-voting state where he had hoped to deal
another blow to Dukakis as he did in Michigan's caucuses a week and
a half ago. He also lost narrowly to Dukakis in Colorado's caucuses.
   Both were states where expectations had been raised for Jackson
by his landslide victory in Michigan, his apparent growth in white
voter support in Michigan and Connecticut last week, and the huge,
enthusiastic crowds he had drawn in campaigning in both states.
   In both states he had waged a populist campaign of appeal to the
downtrodden and working people in an effort to forge a coalition of
blacks, whites and Hispanics.
   Jackson continued to draw big crowds Tuesday as he began his
campaign toward Arizona's caucuses on April 16.
   He spoke to more than 7,000 students in the domed stadium at
Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, where he also met with
Indian tribal leaders.
   In his Tempe speech, Jackson outlined in new specifics his plan
for cutting $100 billion in annual deficits by the year 1993. He
said he would freeze Pentagon spending, raising the top income tax
rate from 28 percent to 38.5 percent, and moving corporate taxes
back toward 1970s levels as a percentage of gross national product.
   Jackson appeared with the former Democratic presidential
candidate and former Arizona governor, Bruce Babbitt, at a large
rally at Arizona State University in Tempe, before some 8,000
people.
   Babbitt, who dropped out of the race Feb. 18, praised Jackson as
having ``brought new fire into the hearts of the American people,''
but stopped short of endorsing his candidacy.
   Jackson insisted there was no disappointment with his twin
loses, contending he had run good campaigns and clearly established
a broader base among white voters.
   ``We got to New York with a good campaign, a broad-based
campaign, momentum, a clear message _ a message that applies to New
York,'' he said.
   Jackson said he has finished first or second in 30 of 40
delegate contests.
   ``I feel good with the pace, our momentum, and our growth at
this stage,'' he said.
   Polling of voters leaving voting sites by television networks
suggested Jackson received a quarter or more of the white vote in
Wisconsin _ somewhat more than he received in Connecticut and
beyond what once had seemed a 10 percent barrier for his candidacy.
   ``Our white vote base continues to expand dramatically,'' he
said.
   He said the Wisconsin results show he has ``the broadest base of
support'' among the Democrats.
   ``We went against the odds of machinery and money and culture,
and yet we see cultural expansion, we see greater participation, we
see more white support, and we come out of Colorado and Wisconsin
with a (total) popular vote lead. ... I have to feel good about
that going into New York.''
   In all the primaries so far, however, Dukakis leads by a slight
margin in the popular vote, with 3,559,364 to Jackson's 3,487,843.
   Jackson continued to protest the slow count of caucus results in
Colorado and his criticism of the state party chairman there, Buie
Seawell, who endorsed Dukakis. He said the slow count ``represents
a sort of manipulation that's not good.''
</TEXT>
