<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial     04-06 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Refuses To Declassify Records Sought By LaRouche Lawyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge and the FBI are at loggerheads
over the agency's refusal to declassify seven files the judge has
ruled as relevant to Lyndon LaRouche's claims of government
infiltration and harassment.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham said the FBI notified him
Tuesday afternoon that the agency did not want to declassify the
files because they contain information about sensitive national
security matters.
   The agency reviewed the files following U.S. District Judge
Robert Keeton's ruling that material in them is relevant to defense
claims that the FBI used a former LaRouche security consultant as
an informant during the investigation that led to LaRouche's July
1987 indictment.
   Keeton, who reviewed the files, has not indicated what in them
he considers relevant to the case. Markham said he would ask the
judge at a hearing today to list the material in the files he
considered relevant.
   If judge rules the entire files should be given to defense
lawyers, or that the FBI should release portions it believes should
be kept secret, the government could ask the 1st U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals to overrule Keeton.
   Testimony in the case has been halted four of the last five
weeks because of battles over access to government records, mostly
files of Vice President George Bush, the National Security Council,
the CIA and the FBI. The earliest testimony could resume is Monday.
   The seven classified FBI files were given to Keeton last week
during hearings on whether the FBI employed former LaRouche
security consultant Ryan Quade Emerson as an informant during the
LaRouche investigation.
   The FBI has said it used Emerson very briefly during the
investigation of the political extremist, but the defense contends
the agency is concealing Emerson's true role because he was used to
entrap the defendants.
   The defense raised the infiltration allegations during pretrial
hearings more than a year ago, but unsucessfully pursued the theory
in court until gaining access a month ago to declassified documents
that discuss apparent infiltration of LaRouche groups. The
declassified documents included a memo between former White House
aide Oliver North and another pivotal figure in the Iran-Contra
scandal.
   LaRouche lawyers have accused Markham of withholding the
documents and other evidence, and have said they would seek
dismissal of the case following the infiltration hearings. Keeton
also has the option to dismiss the case if he orders the FBI to
release information and it refuses to do so.
   LaRouche, six aides and five LaRouche political organizations
are charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury
investigation into allegations LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign raised more than $2 million through credit card and loan
fraud.
</TEXT>
