<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kuwait-Shiites     04-06 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Shiites,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijackers Linked To Shiites Holding Americans In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Hijack, Bjt
^By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arabs who hijacked a Kuwaiti jetliner
to Iran appear to be part of the Iranian-linked network of
terrorists that includes the Shiite Moslem extremists who hold
Americans hostage in Lebanon.
   The hijackers, whose identity and nationality are not known,
have made the same demand as the Americans' captors _ freedom for
17 pro-Iranian extremists jailed in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and
French embassies there in 1983.
   Kuwait, a tiny oil-rich desert emirate trapped in the crossfire
of the Iran-Iraq war, has doggedly refused to free any of them. It
reiterated Tuesday that it will not bow to ``blackmail.''
   Like Terry Anderson and Thomas Sutherland, the two Americans
held captive in Lebanon since 1985, the passengers and crew members
held hostage aboard Kuwait Airways Flight 422 have become pawns in
a war between the acolytes of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and
opponents of his Islamic revolution.
   Kuwait, like most of Iran's Persian Gulf Arab neighbors, is a
conservative state ruled by Sunni Moslems, historic rivals of the
Shiite sect who make up the vast majority of Iran's 50 million
people.
   Like other Arab states, Kuwait fears that Iran's fundamentalist
Islamic revolution will spread its way, inciting its Shiite
minority into insurrection.
   Galvanized by Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon and Khomeini's
revolution, Lebanon's long-downtrodden Shiites launched suicide
bombings against the Israelis and later U.S. and French troops who
took part in an ill-fated multinational peacekeeping force in
Lebanon.
   In the past five years, Shiite extremists have particularly
targeted Kuwait, which Iran accuses of aiding Iraq in the Persian
Gulf war.
   The 17 people whose release the hijackers demand were convicted
of a wave of bombings in 1983 that killed five people and wounded
86 and culminated in attacks on the U.S. and French embassies in
Kuwait.
   Later terrorist attacks on Kuwait included an abortive 1985
assassination attempt on the emir, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah.
   Three of the 17 were sentenced to death _ two Iraqis, Baqer
Ibrahim Abdel-Reda and Hussein Qassem Hassan, and a Lebanese named
as Elias Fuad Saab.
   The Shiite kidnappers in Lebanon are particularly interested in
springing Saab because he is a cousin of Imad Mugniyeh, who Western
and Lebanese intelligence believe to be the mastermind of Islamic
Jihad, or Holy War, and other extremist Shiite factions behind a
chain of suicide bombings, kidnappings and aircraft hijackings in
recent years.
   Saab's real name is Mustafa Youssef, and Western intelligence
officials believe he rigged the bombs used in the Kuwait attacks.
   Kuwait has so far not carried out the death sentences handed
down on Youssef and his fellow bombers, apparently after appeals
from Washington.
   But that appears to have been its only concession. Scores of
other Shiites have been arrested for sabotage since 1983. In 1985,
Kuwait's now-suspended Parliament passed a law decreeing capital
punishment for using explosives to kill or cause terror, and life
imprisonment for possessing explosives.
   Mugniyeh, 36, is a key figure in the security apparatus of
Hezbollah, or Party of God, an Iranian-backed Shiite movement
believed to be the umbrella for factions holding most of the 22
foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   His family has been closely linked for many years with the
Hamadis, another Shiite clan deeply involved in kidnappings.
   Both clans are from the Bekaa Valley in eastern Lebanon.
   Mugniyeh and Mohammed Ali Hamadi, held in West Germany on
charges of smuggling explosives, have been named by U.S.
authorities as two of the four Lebanese Shiites involved in the
June 1985 hijacking of a TWA airliner in which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Dean Stethem was killed.
   The Hamadis, using various cover names, allegedly kidnapped
three West Germans in Beirut in an effort to force Bonn to free
Mohammed and one of his brothers, Abbas, who is currently on trial
in Duesseldorf for kidnapping two Germans. A third Hamadi brother,
Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, the linchpin of the clan, is Hezbollah's
security chief.
   The Mugniyehs are thought to have kidnapped Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. Seized March
16, 1985, Anderson is the longest held of the missing foreigners.
</TEXT>
