<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Market     04-06 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Market,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar and Stocks Close Higher In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
today in Tokyo, while stock prices also posted a moderate gain
following the overnight advance on Wall Street.
   The dollar closed at 125.03 yen, up 0.60 yen from its close of
124.43 yen on Tuesday. It had opened the day higher at 125.23 and
ranged between 124.83-125.40 yen.
   ``Trading was in narrow range without anything in particular to
direct the market,'' said Michiko Kawai of the Bank of Tokyo.
   A senior trader at the same bank said eyes are turning to the
annoucement next week of the U.S. trade figures for February. The
dollar may trade narrowly until then, he said.
   According to Kawai, traders maintained favorable prospect for
the trade figures.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which added a small 19.94 points Tuesday, gained
another 195.82 points, or 0.74 percent and finished the day at
26,511.17 points.
   ``Buying spreaded among more issues as participants were
confident about the market condition,'' said Masahiro Umemori of
Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   The overnight advance on Wall Street and the stabilizing foreign
exchange market prompted buying, he said.
   Traders said New York stocks' firmness overnight helped
investors overcome their reservations about how New York might
respond to recent weakness in the U.S. bond market.
   Share prices were generally higher with popular issues being
large-capitals such as steels and heavy electricals.
   The volume of the first section trade was a heavy 1.2 billion
shares, up from 700 million shares Tuesday.
</TEXT>
