<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BigCatch     04-06 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Big Catch,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fisherman Snags $5 Million In Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angler says he knew ``something was fishy''
when he snagged a floating courier's bag that contained $5 million
in negotiable bonds while heading home in a boat after a day
fishing.
   Raymond Lucas, a 40-year-old maintenance man, turned the bag of
bank securities _ five negotiable bonds worth $5,090,058, and some
non-negotiable securities _ over to police on Tuesday.
   ``I didn't know what to do with them, but I knew something was
fishy,'' Lucas said Tuesday. After plucking the bag from Jamaica
Bay on Saturday, he asked asked neighbor Frank LaSpisa to look at
the papers.
   ``He was flabbergasted when I told him what they were,'' LaSpisa
said. ``He said `Oh, my God.' We started to shake.''
   Bonds that are negotiable can be cashed in by the bearer rather
than the registered owner of the bonds.
   LaSpisa, a retired district manager for a book manufacturer,
said the pair didn't really consider keeping the bonds.
   ``I'm sure there was a way to cash them in if we wanted to, but
we wanted to take the honest way,'' LaSpisa said. ``We're hoping
we'll get a little compensation for it.''
   He said that after he examined the bonds he called a friend, a
retired police detective, who advised him to turn in the satchel.
   The bag, stamped ``DHL-Worldwide,'' was reported missing
Saturday from Kennedy International Airport, where it was being
moved from a terminal by a DHL Worldwide Express van, said police
spokesman James Coleman.
   Port Authority police began investigating after the van driver,
Stephen Doer, reported that the bag apparently had fallen out of
the van, Coleman said.
   DHL collected the satchel Tuesday. A company spokesman in San
Francisco, Dick Rossi, said he could not comment because the matter
was under investigation.
   Rossi said the courier service's policy is not to carry
negotiable instruments.
   Asked why he was turning in the bonds, Lucas replied, ``I'm just
trying to do the right thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
