<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MovieOrdinance     04-06 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Movie Ordinance,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Finds No Attraction In Movie-Making</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Fatal Attraction,'' nominated for an
Academy Award as best film, will not win any prizes from this
quiet, suburban hamlet.
   In fact, the ruckus that accompanied the movie's filming here
prompted the town board to approve an ordinance Tuesday tightening
restrictions on movie-making.
   Board members voted 3-2 to make film crews appear before the
board to obtain a permit, whether the filming is on private or
public land.
   Town Supervisor Larry Dwyer said the community is often used for
films and television commercials, but ``Fatal Attraction'' caused
too many problems. He said the film crew blocked roads when school
buses were trying to get by, annoyed townspeople with bright lights
for night filming and rented private property for commercial use.
   ``No matter what urging we gave, no matter what cooperation we
asked, there was continued abuse,'' Dwyer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
