<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Marshal,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Fires Marshal Who Allegedly Faked His Own Abduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE MOUNTAIN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small-town marshal who may have
faked his own abduction to gain attention from his estranged wife,
prompting a search by about 200 law officers and volunteers, has
been fired.
   Gary Stokes' dismissal Tuesday by the town aldermen was made
retroactive to Friday, when he reappeared from a daylong absence
saying he had been kidnapped at gunpoint and escaped.
   Stokes, the only police officer for the town of 870 residents,
didn't attend the aldermen's meeting Tuesday night. City Attorney
Joe Gay said he would meet with Sheriff Leroy Meeks today to
discuss the case.
   The search began after Stokes' patrol car, its engine running,
and handgun were found outside a convenience store where he had
reportedly gone to investigate a burglary early Thursday.
   Stokes reappeared about 2:30 a.m. Friday in Myrtle, about 20
miles southwest of Blue Mountain, and told authorities the
abduction story. He had spent a night in an abandoned house,
investigators said.
   Investigators with the state Highway Patrol said Saturday that
they had determined the kidnapping story was false, but offered no
motive.
   Stokes has declined to comment on the case, but his stepmother
Mary Stokes has said he fabricated the highly-publicized incident
to gain attention from his estranged wife.
   ``It pushed him to the deepest end to do such a horrible
thing,'' she said earlier this week. ``It's a sad situation.''
   ``It hurt us,'' she said. ``We're relieved we know about it and
can get him some help.''
   Stokes' estranged wife, Denise Stokes, said Monday that she was
shocked by the incident, but declined any further comment.
</TEXT>
