<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ProstitutionRing     04-06 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prostitution Ring,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computerized Call Girl Ring Busted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a couple accused of running a
multimillion-dollar prostitution ring that used a computerized
client list and beepers to page its 450 hookers, authorities said.
   A woman cooperating in the investigation led police to the
alleged ringleaders, Dominick Volpe, 40, and his wife Sharon, 39.
They and Stuart Vigoda, 43, were indicted Tuesday on charges of
promoting prostitution.
   The alleged ring advertised in the Village Voice and Screw
Magazine as the Play Mate Escort Service and Party Mates. It had a
client list of 4,500 and operated out of an apartment in the
Whitestone district of Queens.
   Investigators infiltrated the ring in December by inviting two
of the service's employees to a bogus bachelor party. Police said
the women agreed to strip, perform lesbian sex and entertain the
groom and best man for two hours for $750.
   Police raiding the apartment found six phone lines and 20 phones.
   ``Their records and client list were computerized and the
prostitutes carried beepers,'' said Bruce Pless, an assistant
Suffolk County district attorney.
   ``From what we could gather, the take was over a million
(dollars) a year and they had been in operation for a couple
years,'' Pless said.
   Volpe was freed on $50,000 bail after being arraigned before
Suffolk County Supreme Court Justice George McInerny. His wife was
freed on $5,000 bail and Vigoda, a driver for the firm, on $10,000
bail.
</TEXT>
