<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kuwait-Rulers 1stLd-Writethru a0526 04-06 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Rulers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Members of Kuwait's Ruling Royal Family Aboard Hijacked Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt
^Eds: CORRECTS style on Al-Sabah thruout, spelling of `Ebtesam' in
2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of the 30 Kuwaitis aboard the Kuwait Airways
jumbo jet hijacked to Iran are named Al-Sabah, indicating they are
among the estimated 1,200 people who belong to the Persian Gulf
state's royal family.
   The airline identified the three, who were in the first-class
section, as Fadel Khaled Al-Sabah, a man, and two women, Ebtesam
and Anware Khaled Al-Sabah. The two women have been identified as
sisters of Fadel.
   Like all other male members of the royal clan, Fadel can carry
the title of sheik. Sources in Kuwait who spoke on condition of
anonymity on Tuesday said Fadel is a businessman and distant
relative of the royal family.
   The Al-Sabah dynasty has ruled Kuwait for more than two
centuries and oversees vast oil wealth that gives it one of the
world's highest per capita incomes.
   The riches that began to flow from the discovery of oil were
used in the 1970s to set up a modern welfare state. Kuwait, until
recently, also boasted the only elected parliament in the region.
   But since 1980, Kuwait and its royal family have been plagued by
terrorism blamed on Iranian fundamentalists who have pledged to
spread their revolution throughout the Persian Gulf states.
   The emir, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, survived an
assassination attempt in May 1985 by a suicide driver who tried to
crash a bomb-laden car into the royal motorcade.
   Sheik Jaber escaped with minor wounds, but two security men and
two pedestrians were killed along with the bomber.
   The terrorist attacks have included bombings and the hijacking
of a Kuwait Airways jetliner in 1984.
   In that incident, two American passengers were slain by the
hijackers, who demanded freedom for 17 pro-Iranian extremists
imprisoned in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French embassies and
other targets in Kuwait in 1983.
   The Arabs who hijacked the Kuwaiti airliner Tuesday made the
same demand.
   The fundamentalist Islamic rulers of Iran, who have been at war
with Iraq for 7{ years, accuse Kuwait of aiding Iraq.
   Members of the Al-Sabah clan fill most senior posts in the
government, the army, the police and both the private and public
sectors of the emirate, which has a population of 1.7 million.
   They include the crown prince and prime minister, Sheik Saad
al-Abdullah al-Salem Al-Sabah, and the ministers of defense,
interior, foreign affairs and information.
   Even the hijacked plane is named after the ruler and has the
word Al-Jaberiya, Arabic for ``the plane of the Al-Jabers,''
emblazoned on its side.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar stayed mostly higher in quiet European
trading this morning after a brief early rally lost momentum.
   Gold prices fell as the dollar appeared to hold on to recent
gains, but dealers said they didn't expect the precious metal to
fall much further.
   Traders in Rome said any movement in the dollar this week is
likely to be limited, slow and hesitant because no major economic
news is expected.
   ``People are still bearish, but there is fear that the United
States is tightening monetary policy in order to control inflation,
and this has created some uncertainty,'' one Italian trader said.
   He added that this uncertainty is likely to persist until the
April 14 announcement of the U.S. trade figures for February.
   Dealers in Frankfurt cited few fundamental reasons for the
dollar's recovery. One cited higher U.S. interest rates and another
said the dollar received some support Tuesday from U.S. Federal
Reserve sales of Britain's pound.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.60 yen to a closing 125.03. Later, in London, it was
quoted slightly higher at 125.055 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates:
   _1.6692 West German marks, up from 1.6690
   _1.3770 Swiss francs, up from 1.3765
   _5.6575 French francs, down from 5.6605
   _1.8735 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8700
   _1,237.50 Italian lire, up from 1,234.50
   _1.2390 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.8780 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8800 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $452.30 a troy ounce. At
midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $450.80, down from Tuesday's late bid of
$451.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $451.10, down from $453.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped $5.60 to close at a bid
$453.21.
   Silver also fell in London today. It was selling at a bid price
of $6.59 a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.65.
</TEXT>
