<1ST_LINE>r a PM-McClatchy-Laxalt     04-06 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-McClatchy-Laxalt,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laxalt Gets Partial Award of Legal Fees In Suit Against Newspaper
Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Paul Laxalt says an award
of nearly $650,000 in legal costs makes him the victor in a more
than four-year libel battle against McClatchy Newspapers.
   ``The public knows well that winners aren't ordered to fork over
hundreds of thousands of dollars, and no amount of distortion by
the Bee (newspaper) regarding today's decision will dispel that
basic fact,'' Laxalt said in a statement issued in Washington.
   ``This should prove that it is not impossible for a public
servant to win the good fight against a wealthy and powerful
newspaper chain.''
   The award, announced Monday, marks the end of a protracted legal
battle that began in November 1983 when the Bee newspapers in
Sacramento, Modesto and Fresno published an article about the
family of Laxalt, a longtime confidante of President Reagan and
then a Republican senator from Nevada.
   The article alleged that the Internal Revenue Service had
evidence of skimming at the Ormsby House hotel-casino in Carson
City, Nev. while the Laxalt family owned it in the early 1970s.
   The action was dropped in June 1987, and the two sides then
entered arbitration over fees, with Laxalt's side requesting
approximately $4.3 million in fees and costs. The three-member
panel _ Griffin B. Bell, Charles B. Renfrew and Philip W. Tone _
entered their award last Thursday for $647,454 in fees and costs,
which will be paid by McClatchy's insurance carrier.
   The award also provides that $130,363 in fees and expenses for
the arbitrators will be shared by both parties.
   McClatchy Newspapers said in a statement it would have preferred
its insurance company not pay any of the fees, but called the award
``fair to all parties.''
   ``We are pleased that this long legal battle is finally over,
but let's hope its lessons are not forgotten,'' the publishing
company said in a statement. ``The First Amendment is meaningless
without a strong, independent and vigilant press willing to stand
up for its beliefs.''
   ``It's a hell of a victory,'' said attorney James Beasley, who
represented Laxalt. ``That's over half a million in counsel fees
that Laxalt doesn't have to pay. You only pay counsel fees to the
winner.''
   The Laxalt Libel Defense Fund already has paid $680,000 in legal
fees related to the case, according to Laxalt's daughter, Michelle,
who runs a political consulting firm in Washington, D.C. McClatchy
Newspapers is not required to pay reimbursement for those costs.
</TEXT>
