<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ExplodingLaundry     04-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exploding Laundry,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gasoline-Soaked Laundry Causes Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men fled from a laundry after their
gasoline-soaked clothes caused an explosion in a washing machine,
and the laundry manager's hair was singed when the machine exploded
again while he tried to drain it.
   ``They probably just didn't know any better. It was just a
stupid thing to do,'' said Charles G. Lloyd, manager of White Star
Laundry & Cleaners.
   He said the garments appeared to be those of painters. He said
the men may have used gasoline to remove paint from the clothes
before washing them and he doesn't think they meant to endanger
anybody.
   Lloyd said he was sitting in his office Monday when he heard a
boom, and he saw two men running out the door, one of them with
singed hair. He said five to 10 people were washing their clothes
at the time in the coin-operated laundry.
   ``I assumed the guy had been hurt; I didn't think they were
running away,'' Lloyd said.
   Then Lloyd found that the five machines the men had been using
reeked of gasoline.
   ``I opened the lid and you could smell the fumes,'' Lloyd said.
``You could see the gasoline floating on top of the water.''
   A few minutes later, Lloyd was trying to drain the water from
the machines when fumes from the machine he was standing in front
of ignited.
   ``It singed my eyebrows and hair. I've got some blisters on my
cheeks,'' he said. Several machines were damaged and the laundry's
front window shattered, Lloyd said.
   Fire investigator J.C. Wilson said investigators are looking for
the man who loaded the clothes, just to make sure he isn't hurt and
to warn him of the danger of gasoline.
   ``But I'm pretty sure he knows now,'' Wilson said.
</TEXT>
