<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0542 04-06 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0542,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Attacks Tehran, Supertanker In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with reports of casualties.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Lavan island...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi gunners fired four rockets into
Tehran during this morning's rush hour, and Iran said 16 people
were killed. Earlier, Iraqi warplanes blasted a supertanker near an
Iranian oil complex in the Persian Gulf.
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said six children
were among those killed when four rockets hit Iran's capital at the
same time. It said ``many'' others were wounded and that a hospital
and nursery school were hit.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said 15 other civilians were killed
in Iraqi air raids on six towns in the southeasetern Khuzestan
province.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said four missiles were fired
into Tehran, ``the nest of hypocrites and charlatans,'' at 9:29
a.m. (1:29 a.m. EDT).
   It was one of the heaviest single barrages on the Iranian
capital since the so-called ``war of the cities'' was rekindled
Feb. 29. Since then, Iraq has been pounding the Iranian capital
with missiles, usually firing only one or two at a time.
   The Iraqi agency said Basra and the Umm Qasr port cities were
hit with missiles and artillery during the night. It said one
missile hit an elementary school in Umm Qasr, killing three
students and wounding 50 other children and teachers.
   The agency also quoted a military spokesman as saying Iraqi jets
attacked ``a very large maritime target,'' a usual reference to a
supertanker, off Sheik Sho'eyb, which is more commonly known as
Lavan Island. There was no immediate independent confirmation of
the air raid, which apparently occurred Tuesday night.
   Lavan island is a key offshore Iranian terminal for underwater
pipelines from central gulf oilfields of Rostam and Sassan. It lies
450 miles south of the main Iran-Iraq battle ground which is at the
northern edge of the gulf.
   The unidentified Iraqi spokesman said the Iraqi warplanes
``dealt an accurate and effective'' to the vessel off Lavan.
   He said the attack was ``a part of Iraq's continuous effort to
cut off the criminal Iranian regime's oil supplies.'' Iran depends
on a tanker fleet to shuttle its oil through the gulf under the
threat of Iraqi attacks.
   Iraq has safer outlets for its oil exports, which both countries
badly need to finance their costly war, now 7{ years old. Iraqi oil
is shipped through piplines across Turkey and Saudi Arabia.
   The Iraqi News Agency reported its gunners fired two missiles
into Tehran on Tuesday, two into the holy city of Qom and one into
Isfahan in central Iran.
</TEXT>
