<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlagFlap-NAACP     04-06 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flag Flap-NAACP,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Members From Neighboring States Say They'll Protest
Confederate Flag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NAACP members in four neighboring states have
offered to march with Oklahomans in protest if the Confederate flag
flies again at the Oklahoma Capitol, the state president of the
organization said.
   Roy Carter of Enid, 93 miles north of Oklahoma City, said
executive committees and members of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People in New Mexico, Texas, Louisiana
and Arkansas offered to march at the Oklahoma Capitol and in their
own states.
   ``We are also soliciting a coalition of other groups to
participate,'' Carter said.
   On Tuesday, Gov. Henry Bellmon signed a joint resolution
requiring the Confederate flag be flown over the Capitol but said
the flagpole will remain empty until the Legislature tells him
which of three flags used by the Confederacy from 1861 to 1865 they
want.
   Black legislators had opposed the resolution, saying the
Confederate flag was a symbol of racism and slavery and had been
used by groups such as the Ku Klux Klan.
   ``They fly it, we're marching,'' Carter said.
   The flag has sparked controversy in several other Southern
states recently. In Georgia, legislators have introduced a bill to
redesign the state flag, which incorporates the design of the
Confederate banner, and in Alabama, black lawmakers were arrested
for trying to remove a Confederate flag from the Capitol dome.
   For years, the Stars and Bars flag used by the Confederacy until
1863 was part of a 14-flag display south of the Capitol steps, but
the Office of Public Affairs removed the flags during recent
renovations.
   The flag display represents the countries that have claimed a
portion of Oklahoma territory in the past, including France and
Spain. Bellmon has said the existence of the Confederacy and its
control over a portion of Oklahoma are undisputed facts, and the
display is in historical context.
</TEXT>
