<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-COCOM     04-06 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-COCOM,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search Trading Firms For Illegal Exports To China</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version on financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched two trading firms after the
government accused the companies of exporting high-technology
measurement equipment to China between 1985 and 1986 without
obtaining permission.
   The searches were conducted Tuesday at Kyokuto Shokai, homes of
the firm's executives, and Shinsei Koeki, a Tokyo Metropolitan
Police official said.
   The Ministry of International Trade and Industry charged Monday
that both firms violated the nation's Foreign Exchange and Foreign
Trade law by exporting high-technology equipment without obtaining
permission, the official said.
   Seiji Murata, chief of MITI's export division, said Kyokuto
Shokai exported to China five digital memory devices, an
oscilloscope and one signal analyzer worth a total of $276,000
between June 1985 and June 1986.
   Shinsei Koeki is accused of shipping two sets of the digital
memory devices worth $113,000 to China between August 1986 and
November 1986.
   The memory devices are used to gauge the intensity of an
earthquake, but can have military applications, Murata said. An
oscilloscope is used to test microwave communications, while the
signal analyzer is used to pin down the source of noise. Both items
can also be applied for military purposes, he added.
   Officials of the two firms could not be reached Tuesday despite
repeated telephone calls.
</TEXT>
