<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     04-06 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Clashes Kill 12 in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-allied Moslem militiamen struck
back today at forces supported by Iran in a second day of fierce
gunbattles in south Lebanon. Police said 12 people were killed and
34 wounded.
   It was the heaviest fighting in the region between Justice
Minister Nabih Berri's Amal militia, which is allied with Syria,
and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The two Shiite Moslem groups have been struggling for control of
south Lebanon. Relations have rapidly deteriorated since Feb. 17
when Amal captured dozens of Hezbollah members and linked them to
the abduction of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins. Hezbollah
has denied involvement.
   Lebanon's most influential Shiite cleric, Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, called on both sides to lay down their weapons.
   ``We prohibit this fighting because it burns Islam's causes and
the Moslems,'' Fadlallah said.
   The battles, which started Tuesday near the inland market town
of Nabatiyeh, today spread to the port of Tyre and surrounding
villages, police said.
   In today's bloodiest clash, Amal militiamen fought Hezbollah
fighters in Nabatiyeh before dawn and recaptured three offices lost
late Tuesday, said a police spokesman who insisted on anonymity.
Six people were killed and 17 injured.
   Amal militiamen also stormed Hezbollah positions in the village
of Siddiqine, 8 miles southeast of Tyre, killing one person and
wounding four.
   The duel started Tuesday when Hezbollah gunmen attacked an Amal
checkpoint near Nabatiyeh, killing an Amal militiaman.
   Relations between the two groups unraveled after Hezbollah said
Amal was ``harassing the believers by seaching for an American
spy.''
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was serving as chief U.N.
observer in the area when he was kidnapped Feb. 17. His abduction
has been claimed by the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, a
pro-Iranian underground group believed to be affiliated with
Hezbollah.
   Hezbollah, whose members are loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella group for pro-Iranian
underground factions holding most of the 22 foreigners missing and
believed kidnapped in Lebanon since 1985.
   The hostage held the longest is Associated Press chief Middle
East correspondent Terry Anderson. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
