<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0597 04-06 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0597,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israeli Girl, Two Palestinians Reported Killed in West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Combines Urgent with pvs. Clarifies that clash was today.
Picks up 2nd graf of a0574, `The Palestinians...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli girl and two
Palestinians were killed in a clash today between Israeli civilians
and Arabs in a West Bank village, Israel radio and other sources
said.
   The radio said the dead girl was in a group of Israeli tourists
in Beita, a village near Nablus. It said three Israeli children
were injured.
   Arab sources said the Israelis were settlers.
   The Palestinians, identified by hospital officials as Mousa
Saleh Abu Shamseh, 20, and Hatem Fayez Al Jabr, 22, died in a clash
with Jewish settlers while working in their fields at Beita, Arab
reports said.
   Both were shot in the head during a clash at Beita, officials at
Al Ittihad Hospital said. They said two other Palestinians were
seriously wounded.
   Before today, U.N. reports listed 138 Palestinians as being
killed by Israelis since unrest broke out in the occupied
territories on Dec. 8. One Israeli soldier has been killed.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in the Middle East to
promote a peace plan aimed at settling the Arab-Israeli dispute,
met today with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres. Shultz acknowledged he did not win needed support for
the peace initiative but vowed to continue his efforts.
   Shultz went to Jordan and Syria on Tuesday to discuss the peace
plan. Later, he said he could not report any progress.
   In the West Bank today, the army took over the homes of six Arab
families east of Nablus for 10 days, forcing them to live in tents,
Israel radio said. The army earlier had converted about a dozen
Arab schools into military bases and used some as temporary
detention centers.
   In Gaza City, troops ordered Arab passers-by to paint over
slogans proclaiming ``No to Shultz'' and ``Shultz Go Away''
scrawled on shop walls, an Arab shopowner said.
   In the morning, troops forced stores and vegetable markets shut
in Gaza City, in the Jabaliya refugee camp in Gaza and in the West
Bank city of Ramallah. Protest leaders have ordered merchants to
stay open in the morning and observe a strike in the afternoons.
   In Jabaliya, the soldiers' orders prompted a brief clash between
stone-throwing refugees and troops firing tear gas, Arab witnesses
said. In Gaza City, Arabs sold produce on street corners near the
market area, running away when troops appeared, the witnesses said.
   In Gaza on Tuesday, an Arab teen-ager lost his left eye after
being hit by a rubber bullet fired by troops, and soldiers wounded
a second Arab youth in a separate clash, the army said.
   In Jerusalem, a group of Israelis who have been hurt in
Palestinian terror attacks held a vigil in front of the hotel where
Shultz was staying. They said the secretary's peace mission rewards
Arab violence.
   ``Shultz's visit is like oil on the fire of terror,'' said
reserve Gen. Yehoshua Sagi, former head of army intelligence.
   Israeli soldiers on Tuesday foiled an attempt by Palestinian
guerrillas to cross the northern border about 100 yards from the
Israeli settlement Kfar Yuval, the army said.
   Troops exchanged fire with the guerrillas, who were armed with
Soviet-made Kalashnikov rifles, a rocket-propelled grenade launcher
and about a dozen hand grenades, army officials said.
   Two guerrillas were killed and a third was captured. Four
soldiers were wounded.
   Two groups affiliated with the Palestine Liberation Organization
claimed responsibility for the infiltration attempt: Fatah, headed
by PLO chief Yasser Arafat, and the pro-Syrian Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine.
</TEXT>
