<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColemanRetrial     04-06 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleman Retrial,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Holds A.C. Nielsen In Contempt In Murder Retrial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge held A.C. Nielsen Co. in contempt of
court today and fined the television rating company $500 a day for
failing to turn over ratings of Atlanta newscasts sought by
attorneys in a murder retrial.
   Attorneys for Wayne Carl Coleman had sought the ratings
information as a basis for motions to delay or move Coleman's
retrial for the 1973 slayings of six members of the Alday family in
southwest Georgia's Seminole County.
   Defense attorney Tom West said he wants to use the ratings of
local television news programs to show how widely the Alday case
has been publicized in DeKalb County.
   Jury selection began Monday for the retrial, which was moved
from Seminole County to DeKalb County in suburban Atlanta.
   Superior Court Judge Hugh Lawson ruled Nielsen in willful
contempt of court and said he was concerned that its refusal to
produce the information would ``cause real problems in the
prosecution of this case.''
   Nielsen attorney Bernard Rosenthal told Lawson the Chicago-based
company regretted not being able to produce the material, but said
complying with the subpoena would disrupt Nielsen's business by
making it compile information that is not already available.
   He also said it would present a continual threat of requests in
similar trials.
   Rosenthal said Nielsen would appeal immediately to the Georgia
Supreme Court.
   Coleman was one of three Maryland prison escapees convicted of
murder and sentenced to death in Seminole County for the slayings
of Ned Alday, his brother, his three sons and his daughter-in-law.
   In 1985, a federal appeals court threw out the convictions of
Coleman, his half-brother Carl Isaacs and George Elder Dungee on
grounds that pretrial publicity made a fair trial impossible in
Seminole County.
   Isaacs was retried in Houston County earlier this year and was
again convicted and sentenced to death. Dungee is to be tried later
in Muscogee County.
   Lawson is presiding at all three trials.
</TEXT>
