<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-EastGermany     04-06 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-East Germany,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East German Official Will Hold Talks with Shultz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking East German official to
visit the United States will hold talks with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz next month, an East German diplomat said today.
   Hermann Axen, member of the Politburo and party Central
Committee with responsibility for foreign affairs, was invited to
give a lecture at the Johns-Hopkins University Institute for
Contemporary German Studies on May 4 and will meet Shultz the day
before.
   Axen will speak to the National Press Club and meet members of
Congress.
   The two countries established diplomatic ties in 1974, but
relations have remained cool because U.S. officials regard
communist East Germany as one of the Soviet Union's staunchest
allies and have found the country among the least responsive to
U.S. pleas to improve human rights conditions.
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, who met East German
leaders in Berlin last year, was the highest-ranking American
official to visit East Germany.
   ``The main intention of these talks will be to promote the
relationship between both countries and contribute to a further
buildup of the relationship,'' said the East German diplomat,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said Axen would spend a brief time in New York during the
trip.
</TEXT>
