<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0563 04-06 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0563,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waiting Lengthens as Jurors Deliberate Sedition Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 2nd graf to update with deliberations delayed by
illness.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge denied a request by
jurors for a trial transcript, telling them to rely on memory and
notes while deliberating in the case of 13 white supremacists,
including nine accused of sedition.
   Deliberations were delayed today because one of the jurors has a
sick child. U.S. District Judge Morris Arnold said juror Harold C.
Whittenburg went to a hospital to see about his baby and that the
third day of deliberations was postponed until he could rejoin the
jury.
   Nine defendants are charged with conspiring to overthrow the
government by violence, and one of them, along with four other
defendants, is charged with conspiring to kill a federal judge and
an FBI agent. Two of the sedition defendants are accused of the
interstate transportation of stolen money.
   In denying three jurors' requestion for the transcript Tuesday,
Arnold said the document would be 7,000 pages long and would not be
ready for three or four months. He also denied their request to
re-hear lengthy portions of testimony.
   The government called 113 witnesses and the defense had 79 in
the trial which began Feb. 16.
   The case went to the jury Monday afternoon and lawyers,
defendants and others waited at the federal courthouse on Tuesday.
   One defendant, Bruce Carroll Pierce, is serving a 150-year
sentence for violating the civil rights of Denver radio talk show
host Alan Berg by killing him, and 100 years on a Seattle
conviction for racketeering.
   Defendant Robert E. Miles, free on $50,000 bond, said he would
have attended the trial even if he were not a defendant. ``I
wouldn't have missed it for the world,'' he said. ``This is where
the devil is. This is evil personified, the whole crew.''
   Defendant Richard G. Butler said the trial is a move by the
government to snuff out views that do not meet government approval.
He said he expects to be acquitted, ``but in any case, they win:
They break us financially.''
   Butler, Miles and Louis Ray Beam Jr., who also is on trial and
is being held without bond, are considered three of the top leaders
of the white-supremacist movement in the United States.
   But one of Beam's lawyers, Kirk Lyons of Houston, said Butler,
Beam and Miles are ``through fighting. Miles is 63. Butler is 70.
Beam has got a 20-year-old wife.''
   Acquittal would slow the movement, Lyons said, because it would
show that white supremacists ``can get a fair trial in American
courts.''
   The sedition defendants face up to 20 years in prison and a
$20,000 fine if convicted. The murder charge carries a maximum of
life imprisonment and the interstate transportation charges have a
maximum term of 10 years and a $10,000 fine.
   The government also contends that some of the defendants
committed a series of robberies to finance their activities. The
robberies netted about $4.1 million, of which about $1 million is
unaccounted for, the government said.
   The key government witness, James Ellison, testified that the
white supremacist group he led in Arkansas carried out bombings to
advance a conspiracy begun in July 1983 at Hayden Lake, Idaho, at
an Aryan Nations conference.
   Ellison is serving a 20-year prison sentence. Defendants who
attended the 1983 meeting have said that there was no conspiracy
and that Ellison has made up the story in hopes of getting a
sentence reduction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NY-04-06-88 1104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Replacements 1stLd-Writethru a0441 04-06 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Replacements, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, The choices, with Thurmond
saying Meese had not notified him in advance of the choices.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III is trying to
fill a key Justice Department post left vacant by a protest
resignation, after settling for his second choice for the
department's No. 2 post.
   Meese announced Tuesday that he is recommending former American
Bar Association president John C. Shepherd for the No. 2 job. He
also said he has chosen Treasury Department enforcement chief
Francis A. Keating for the department's No. 3 position, which had
opened before six protest resignations rocked the department last
week.
   Still unfilled is the job of head of the department's criminal
division.
   The choices announced Tuesday drew support from the ranking
Republican on the Senate Judiciary Committee. Sen. Strom Thurmond
of South Carolina last week had conveyed congressional concern to
Meese over problems at the Justice Department in the wake of the
protest resignations by Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns,
Assistant Attorney General William Weld of the criminal division,
and four of their aides.
   Meese said he had notified several members of Congress about his
choices ahead of time, but Thurmond, a member of the committee that
will hold confirmation hearings on Shepherd and Keating, pointedly
stated that Meese had not advised him in advance.
   Burns and Weld resigned out of concern that the nearly 11-month
criminal investigation of Meese by independent counsel James C.
McKay was hurting the department's operations and image.
   Shepherd was Meese's second choice to replace Burns, after
former federal appeals judge Arlin Adams of Philadelphia turned it
down, citing a heavy private caseload.
   Keating, a former FBI agent, would fill the post vacated by
Associate Attorney General Stephen Trott, who is leaving the
department to become a federal appeals court judge.
   Thurmond said of Shepherd and Keating, ``From what I now know
about these two fine individuals, I look forward to supporting
their confirmation.''
   Meese said he probably will announce a recommended replacement
for Weld after returning from a week-long trip to South America to
discuss drugs with officials in several countries.
   A Justice Department source said Salvatore R. Martoche, now an
assistant secretary in the Labor Department, had rejected a request
from Meese to take Weld's job, assistant attorney general in charge
of the criminal division.
   Martoche decided not to take the job ``because of the taint
factor'' relating to the continuing criminal investigation of
Meese, said the source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Meese declined to say whether he had offered Martoche the job,
but said he had spoken to a number of people about it.
   Keating was asked whether he had had second thoughts about
accepting his appointment.
   ``Certainly the events of last week made me, as a professional,
pause,'' he said. ``But I have every confidence in the leadership
of the department and the attorney general. I think with our new
team here the operation of the department will continue.''
   Shepherd said he had no reservations about taking the job in the
wake of Burns' protest resignation. But Shepherd did acknowledge
Meese's continuing legal problems, saying ``we all see that.''
   The White House allowed Meese to proceed with the replacements,
despite a lack of completed FBI background checks. The move was an
attempt to quell questions about Meese's ability to lead the
department effectively in the aftermath of the Burns-Weld
resignations.
   Shepherd and Keating will begin serving shortly on an acting
basis until after their nomination by President Reagan and Senate
confirmation. Burns and Trott will stay on while Meese is in South
America.
   Such nominations normally are announced by the president, but
Meese was allowed to announce them at a Justice Department news
conference after checking with White House chief of staff Howard
Baker.
   Shepherd, who is 62, was ABA president in 1984-85 and is a
partner in a St. Louis law firm. Meese said he ``will be a highly
distinguished and most welcome addition to the Justice Department.''
   Meese said Keating, 44, the assistant Treasury secretary for
enforcement, ``can hit the ground running'' in the Justice
Department's work combating illegal drugs.
</TEXT>
