<HEAD>Missing Newlyweds Seen By Service Station Attendant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Wheaton College students missing for four
days may be on a secret honeymoon, say authorities, who are
appealing to the newlyweds to confirm their safety with a call to
their parents.
   Carolyn MacLean, 22, of Haddonfield, N.J., and Scott Swanson,
23, of the west Chicago suburb of Elgin, who were married secretly
March 23, disappeared Saturday. A $35,000 BMW the couple was
driving was discovered in a downtown alley with the engine running,
police said.
   Cmdr. Ettore Di Vito of the Chicago Police Department's Youth
Division said Tuesday that police are hoping some ``personal
things'' they discovered while going through the car would help
them find the couple. In a televised interview, he urged the couple
to contact their parents.
   The couple were expected at the home of Swanson's parents
Saturday night. The parents last heard from the couple by telephone
Friday afternoon. But despite news coverage and the widespread
display of posters with their pictures, they had not contacted
police or their families as of Tuesday.
   ``They're on their honeymoon. They might not have seen the
papers,'' Officer Ronald Mohrs said.
   Police said earlier that an attendant at a Northwest Side gas
station and a few other Chicagoans have reported seeing the couple.
   The attendant, Peter Youkhanna, said he spoke with the missing
couple about 2 a.m. Monday and ``they were happy.''
   The couple asked him if any nightclubs in the area were still
open, and when Youkhanna told them everything was closed, they
called a taxi, Mohrs said.
   The couple were students at Wheaton College, a private Christian
school about 30 miles west of Chicago.
