<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TransplantTurmoil     04-06 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transplant Turmoil,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oversight Panel Says Doctors' Dissent Must Stop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute between transplant specialists and
anesthesiologists at Children's Hospital has resulted in boycotts
of meetings and other conflicts, says an official of a transplant
oversight committee.
   The Very Rev. George Werner, vice chairman of the committee,
said Tuesday that the panel probably will discuss the controversy
at its April 14 meeting.
   Werner began investigating dissension at the hospital after
several internal memos criticizing its liver transplant program
were disclosed late last month. The memos were released by Maria
DeSillers, a Miami woman who is being sued by the hospital for not
paying her late son's medical bills.
   ``It is obvious that an institution which has internal memos
getting out on the street and personality clashes being made public
needs to look at its administration,'' Werner said.
   Mrs. DeSillers said she released the memos in hopes of spurring
a federal investigation of the hospital's liver transplant program.
Her 7-year-old son, Ronnie, died last year after three liver
transplants.
   Ms. DeSillers has refused to pay the $261,189 still owed the
hospital, saying her son received negligent care.
   The boy's plight generated hundreds of thousands of dollars in
donations from sympathetic Americans, including President Reagan.
Florida officials are investigating Ms. DeSillers' handling of the
money.
   The memos, some of which were written by Dr. D. Ryan Cook, an
anesthesiologist, spoke of confusion in the hospital's liver
transplant program. He also referred to ``growing distrust,
disillusionment and negativism.''
   ``Recently, we had two current transplants in which the donor
organs were switched about like peas under shells until no one
could easily recall which liver was to go into which patient,''
Cook wrote in a Feb. 2 letter to Dr. William Donaldson, the
hospital's medical director.
   Werner said both patients are doing well.
   ``Dr. Cook is using exciting language, but he really didn't look
at the results,'' Werner said. ``It seems that whoever moved on
this case did a good job.''
   Mortality rates for pediatric liver transplants are excellent,
Werner said. As of two weeks ago, 44 of 49 patients operated on
since August have survived, he said.
   Werner said, however, that the transplant surgeons who work
under the direction of transplant pioneer Dr. Thomas E. Starzl
occasionally act like ``cowboys'' in the hospital bureaucracy. The
surgeons sometimes ignore surgical schedules and expect
anesthesiologists to show up on short notice, he said.
   Werner chided the anesthesiologists for not attending the weekly
liver transplant reviews, when hospital staff members assign
priorities to the list of patients awaiting transplants.
   ``There didn't seem to be a chain of command so that the
anesthesiologists and transplant surgeons knew what was happening
with the scheduling and with the reviews,'' Werner said.
   ``What needs to be emphasized here is that this is a good
program, and what Dr. Cook will tell you, I'm sure, is that he
wants to make a good program better,'' Werner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
