<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia-Relief 1stLd-Writethru a0608 04-06 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Relief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Relief Workers Told To Leave Northern Ethiopia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 2 grafs on agencies with programs in Tigray and Eritrea.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today told
international relief agencies to recall all their foreign workers
from the war-torn northern regions of Tigray and Eritrea for
security reasons, a U.N. official said.
   The request was made in a two-page statement distributed to
relief agencies in Addis Ababa, the capital, by the Relief and
Rehabilitation Commission, the government agency responsible for
drought and famine relief in Ethiopia.
   ``The RRC notified relief agencies operating to recall to Addis
Ababa their expatriate staff to avoid personnel security risks,''
said David Morton, head of the World Food Program in Ethiopia.
``Donor agencies are advised to turn over their operations to the
RRC to guarantee the continuity of relief activities.''
   The order comes a week after President Mengistu Haile Mariam
told Ethiopians in a radio address that government troops were
facing a ``grim struggle'' against rebels in Eritrea and Tigray.
Mengistu said the government was mobilizing troops to crush the
long-time rebellions and appealed to his countrymen to give
``everything to the warfront.''
   Rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Eritrea, Africa's
longest civil war, and for 14 years in Tigray. The fighting has
disrupted relief efforts in both regions, where crop failures
threaten 3.5 million people with starvation.
   Morton said the statement did not give a deadline for withdrawal
of foreigners from the northern regions and the order did not apply
to Ethiopians working with the international agencies.
   The number of foreign relief workers affected by the order was
not immediately known.
   There are about 60 non-governmental relief organizations working
in Ethiopia, but only a few operate in Eritrea and Tigray.
   Those agencies operating in the war area include the
International Committee of the Red Cross, Medicins Sans Frontieres
of Belguim and Catholic Relief Services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
