<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Gore     04-06 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Touts Underdog Status In New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE ROTHENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. brought his
presidential campaign to the voters here today, trying to turn to
his advantage a distant third-place finish in the Wisconsin primary.
   ``New York state has always been friendly to underdogs, and I'm
the underdog,'' Gore told reporters as he shook hands with
rush-hour commuters boarding the Staten Island ferry for Manhattan.
   Gore has not won a contest since his six victories on Super
Tuesday, March 8. He is campaigning and spending heavily in New
York, which holds a primary April 19, hoping to demonstrate that he
can prevail outside his native South.
   With 99 percent of Wisconsin precincts reporting, Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis had 48 percent of the vote to 28 percent for
Jesse Jackson and 17 percent for Gore.
   On Tuesday night, Gore said he had done much better than
expected and maintained the results portend a trend that will bring
voters to his camp.
   With Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois expected to suspend his
campaign Thursday, Gore proclaimed the bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination a three-man race.
   He minimized his recent criticism of Jackson, saying he has
spent the great majority of his time outlining his own political
agenda as opposed to attacking other candidates.
   Gore reiterated his strong support for Israel and said as
president he would create a Cabinet level position to focus on
Mideast negotiations full time, rather than the ``on-again,
off-again approach'' taken by the Reagan administration.
   He rejected the notion that he is targeting New York's large
Jewish population in the upcoming primary, saying ``I'm not putting
people in different categories. I'm campaigning for all the votes
here in this state.''
</TEXT>
