<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZaccaroTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0586 04-06 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zaccaro Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0586,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Potential Juror: Media Picked On Geraldine Ferraro and Her Family</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with jury selection continuing
today, picking up 9th graf pvs, `Zaccaro, then ....'
^By DANICA KIRKA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potential juror in the cocaine trial of
John Zaccaro Jr. said she thought the press picked on his family
during the 1984 vice presidential candidacy of his mother,
Geraldine Ferraro.
   The woman was one of 15 candidates selected after painstaking
questioning of 25 people during jury selection, which resumed this
morning for a third day.
   Opening arguments were expected later today or Thursday. Twelve
jurors and two alternates are needed for the trial.
   Addison County State's Attorney John Quinn said the selection of
a jury was slowed by the publicity given the case and the fact
Ferraro is so well-known.
   ``Selecting a jury is probably the most important part of the
case,'' he said. Quinn said if even one juror bore a grudge, it
could influence the jury's verdict.
   Most of those questioned said they had read newspaper accounts
of the case since Zaccaro, 24, was charged in 1986 with selling
one-quarter gram of cocaine to an undercover police agent.
   One potential juror said today that he would discount anything
he read in the newspapers though because of a basic distrust of the
press. ``They have a tendency to present people as guilty just
because they have been charged,'' said Donald Cioffi.
   Only one person has been dismissed for acknowleging that the
prominence of Zaccaro's mother could affect his view of the case.
   Jury pool member Joanne Cillo said Tuesday that she felt that
press treatment of Ferraro during the 1984 campaign carried over to
Zaccaro.
   ``I can't say I don't feel the press picked on these people,''
Cillo said when asked if she was pleased with how Ferraro has been
treated.
   She said her views would not interfere with her judgment if she
is chosen to hear the case. ``The press is not trying this case,''
she said. ``The issue is, did this gentleman sell drugs?''
   ``I don't believe it's up to me to make restitution for what the
press may or may not have done,'' she added.
   Zaccaro, then a senior at Middlebury College, pleaded innocent
to the charge. He has been accompanied to court each day by his
mother and father, John Zaccaro Sr.
   Ferraro, a lawyer, sat behind her son and his lawyers, taking
notes intently, but stopping when Cillo spoke about her family. At
that point she rested her head in her hand and looked down.
   She later declined to comment on the case, telling one reporter,
``It's nothing against you personally. We're just not answering
anything for anybody.''
   The start of Monday's trial came two years after her son was
arrested outside the Middlebury restaurant where he worked.
   Six reporters were allowed to watch the questioning, which was
briefly interrupted Monday when Judge Francis McCaffrey imposed and
then lifted a gag order on reporters covering jury selection.
   Defense lawyers sought the gag order for fear too many reporters
could intimidate potential jurors. But McCaffrey lifted it
following a challenge from reporters and an agreement to limit
their number in the courtroom.
   The case has wound its way slowly through the courts. Zaccaro's
attorneys challenged several aspects of the case and claimed
unsuccessfully that Zaccaro was singled out for prosecution because
of his mother.
   The Vermont Supreme Court refused to dismiss the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   04-06 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0763</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   April 4
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on Edwin Meese:
   When a high official's political foes call for his resignation,
he does well to ignore them. But when political friends urge him to
leave, he ought to pay attention.
   Unfortunately, Attorney General Edwin Meese insists on hanging
on to his job by his fingernails, despite well-intentioned advice
by respected associates that he no longer can fulfill his important
duties.
   Meese, the Artful Dodger of the Reagan administration, has had a
special prosecutor on his tail for much of the four years he has
been the nation's highest law enforcement officer. That doesn't
seem untoward to him, but it does to many of us.
   We know a defendant must be presumed innocent until proven
guilty. But the attorney general should be presumed honorable,
clean and competent, which his top aides at Justice decline to do.
Time to go, Ed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 2
   Evansville (Ind.) Courier on privatization of the U.S. Postal
Service:
   In a report more likely to gather dust than to trigger immediate
action, a presidential commission has come up with an intelligent
plan for privatizing the U.S. Postal Service.
   Opponents of privatization point out that the existing
government monopoly subsidizies the extra costs of rural mail
delivery with revenues from urban and suburban delivery.
   They predict that if private delivery companies were allowed to
enter the market, they would concentrate only on high-volume,
low-cost areas and leave the Feds stuck with the unprofitable rural
routes.
   The commission's response: Start by allowing free competition
only in rural delivery.
   If private companies succeed in serving rural households at
prices no higher than those of the Postal Service, ``this strategy
could go a long way toward calming the fears of rural America that
postal privatization would leave them underserved.''
   President Reagan's successor should see to it that the
experiment gets a chance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 5
   The Miami News on U.S.-Panama relations:
   The United States huffed when it indicted Gen. Manuel Noriega on
drug trafficking charges. It puffed when it froze Panamanian assets
and put tolls in escrow. But Noriega's house has not fallen down.
   There is a temptation to use the teeth of the big, bad wolf:
U.S. troops. White House sources said over the weekend that
intervention was being considered, then settled for sending 1,300
more troops to the Canal Zone for the legitimate purpose of
protecting U.S. citizens.
   But military intervention to oust Noriega is unwarranted.
   Besides, huffing and puffing have not yet had enough time to
work. Intervention would draw attention away from the cause of
Panama's crisis, which is Noriega.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 31
   The Times, Trenton, N.J., on Edwin Meese:
   If (the) Justice (Department) has been ``functioning just
fine,'' we'd hate to see it when it needed a tune-up.
   Two top officials ... and their four highest aides quit abruptly.
   (Attorney General Edwin) Meese is the focus of protracted
criminal investigations by a special prosecutor into two separate
cases, Wedtech and the Iraqi oil pipeline. ...
   The attorney general is the nation's chief law enforcement
officer. ... He must also be on top of the day-to-day efforts of
the federal government to fight crime.
   Yet upper management at the department is being decimated, and
the man at the very top is preoccupied with extraneous matters and
precluded from participating in important issues.
   The resignations in the department loudly signal the necessity
for just one more. ...
   Meese should quit. Now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 4
   The Houston Post on the legacy of the Rev. Martin Luther King:
   It was 20 years ago today that the Rev. Martin Luther King was
gunned down while standing on the balcony of a Memphis, Tenn.,
motel.
   But, without a doubt, the King legacy lives on.
   To hear some people speak about him today, one would think the
man is still with us. Indeed, that is what legacies are made of.
   People across the nation will observe this day with marches,
rallies and silent prayers. ...
   While some Americans remain reluctant to admit it, King did much
of the work necessary to make this country a better place to live.
   He is still missed by many.
</TEXT>
