   This late in President Reagan's term, one wonders what good it
would do to dump (Attorney General Edwin) Meese, anyway. ...
   Unless the independent counsel uncovers evidence that directly
ties Meese to criminal or unethical behavior, Meese should stay on
as attorney general.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 1
   The Columbia (Mo.) Daily Tribune on Edwin Meese:
   Haven't you had enough of Ed Meese? I have.
   President Ronald Reagan's attorney general is a discredit to the
administration and to the U.S. government. ...
   Even if his friend and boss Reagan has faith in him, the high
government official is causing so many problems for the White House
that he should have long ago been graciously moved aside. Now, it's
too late.
   The fact that Reagan has presided over this stumbling entourage
without becoming thoroughly discredited himself, is the ultimate
testimony to the Teflon presidency.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 1
   Lawrence (Kan.) Journal World on presidential campaigns:
   So far, the race for the President of the United States has been
largely an activity for ambitious politicians, with the great mass
of Americans on the sidelines waiting to see for whom they should
vote. ...
   The pace is furious and exhausting. Candidates find themselves
saying and doing things they never intended when they first
announced as candidates.
   The campaign periods last far too long. The costs are terrific
with a large portion of the expense coming out of tax funds. ...
   The United States needs a discussion of domestic and
international issues instead of an entertaining endurance contest.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 1
   The Athens (Ga.) Daily News on the Republican presidential
campaign:
   Although it has seemed inevitable since his defeat on Super
Tuesday, Sen. Bob Dole's decision to withdraw from the Republican
presidential race leaves us with a feeling of frustration about the
campaign and the system.
   Dole is an appealing candidate who appears to have a good grasp
of the country's needs and how to attack them, yet his candidacy is
over long before much of the country's voters had an opportunity to
consider him in primaries.
   It's possible that Republicans would have preferred Vice
President George Bush if there had been a national primary after
extensive campaigning throughout the country. But it seems
unfortunate that a true competition never really developed. ...
   The selection of Bush as the nominee this early may give the
Republicans an edge in planning and organizing for the fall
campaigns. But it also gives the Democrats a single Republican
target to shoot at when they're not shooting at each other.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 4
   Salem (Ore.) Statesman-Journal on Larry Speakes' book:
   A look at the inside from a former insider who left the fold is
always intensely interesting, in a gossipy sort of way, although we
feel a bit soiled after reading the intimate details.
   That's true for Larry Speakes. The former press aide to
President Reagan has spilled his guts in the book ``Speaking Out''.
...
   The book ... will be a best seller, but we would rather Speakes
had kept his mouth shut for a while.
   When dollar signs light up the eyeballs, however, it's not
silence that's golden. The gold comes from prattling the gossip.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 30
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on Edwin Meese:
   What will it take to get Attorney General Edwin Meese to step
aside as a criminal investigation against him unfolds? It might
take nine months.
   In that time, regardless of what transpires in the
investigation, a new president will appoint a new attorney general.
   However, Meese should get a strong message from (the) tandem
resignations of his top deputy and another high Justice Department
official, along with four of their aides.
   The two Justice Department officials' resignations are still
another indication that, guilty or not, Meese has become
ineffective as attorney general.
   He should resign and face the charges without crippling the
activities of the Justice Department. He can best serve by not
serving.
</TEXT>
