<HEAD>Engineer Arrested in Fatal Train Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested the engineer of a train that
crashed head-on with a second passenger train in Shanghai last
month, killing 28 people, according to an official report.
   The National Committee for Industrial Safety said Zhou Xaioniu
and his assistant Liu Guolong violated railway traffic rules,
according to the Xinhua News Agency. Liu was being detained for
questioning, Xinhua said Tuesday.
   Earlier accounts blamed brake failure for the March 24 collision
that killed 27 Japanese high school students on a school-sponsored
tour of China. A Chinese railway worker also was killed.
   Officials had quoted the engineer as saying the brakes failed.
It was not clear if they now were discounting brake failure.
