<1ST_LINE>r i AM-StringQuartets     04-06 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-String Quartets,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four U.S. String Quartets Compete in Portsmouth Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. string quartets will try to
outplay 18 other ensembles in this south England port city's fourth
international string quartet competition beginning Wednesday.
   The musicians will compete for a first prize of about $12,200
and the chance to perform under the baton of violinist Sir Yehudi
Menuhin, president of the jury and conductor of a victory contest
Sunday for the winning quartet, said Christina Eveleigh, a
spokesman with the competition.
   Other prizes range from an award worth about $7,000 for the
second-best musicians to a $900 seventh-place prize to be decided
by audience vote after the finals, she said.
   Another prize will be awarded by the three-member jury to the
most promising quartet which does not make it beyond the first
round of competition.
   In addition to Menuhin, British quartet leader Sidney Griller
and Yfrah Neaman, artistic consultant of the competition, will
judge the contest.
   The competition has been held every three years since 1979, and
has been won by a Hungarian, Austrian, and most recently a U.S.
ensemble called the Alexander Quartet from Binghamton, N.Y.
   Competing this year are groups from Australia, Austria, China,
Czechoslovakia, Denmark, East Germany, France, Great Britain,
Hungary, Italy, New Zealand, Poland and the United States.
   A group from Beijing, China withdrew last week for unknown
reasons but one from Shanghai remains in the competition. Another
group from Poland was forced to withdraw when a player was injured.
   The U.S. groups are: the Harrington String Quartet from Canyon,
Texas; the Tidewater Area Musicians from Portsmouth, Va.; the
Lafayette Quartet from Rochester, Mich., and the Sierra Quartet
from San Francisco.
</TEXT>
