<HEAD>Former Lead Singer of the Temptations Charged with Cocaine
Possession
^Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Ruffin released from jail,
picking up in the 3rd graf, Ruffin, 46 ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Ruffin, former lead singer for the
Temptations, was released from jail today after spending the night
there on a cocaine possession charge.
   Wayne County Sheriff's Department spokeswoman Nancy Mouradian
said Ruffin left the Wayne County Jail on posting either a $1,500
surety or $150 cash bond.
   Ruffin, 46, was arraigned Tuesday before Magistrate Vesta
Svenson on a charge of possession with intent to distribute less
than 20 grams of cocaine. If convicted, Ruffin could be sentenced
to 20 years in prison.
   The singer, who left the Motown group in 1968, was scheduled for
a preliminary examination Monday.
   Ruffin was charged in connection with a July raid on a Detroit
house. Officials said he was in the basement, but a pouch
containing suspected cocaine residue and personal papers with his
name was found on a kitchen table.
   In 1982, Ruffin pleaded guilty to evading $177,359 in federal
income taxes on 1976 earnings.
   The Temptations, a cornerstone of the Motown sound, was formed
in 1960 and recorded dozens of hits including ``My Girl,'' ``Ain't
Too Proud to Beg'' and ``(I Know I'm) Losing You.''
</TEXT>
