<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ParkingTickets     04-06 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Parking Tickets,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parking Tickets May Go to $100</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fine for parking illegally in problem
traffic areas of Manhattan may leap from $40 to $100, city
officials said.
   The higher fines would be for illegally parking at fire
hydrants, expired meters, in no-parking and no-standing zones, and
for blocking driveways in the most congested areas.
   In addition, the city wants to boost the towing fee from $100 to
$125.
   ``In a way we're competing with garages,'' said Samuel Schwartz,
first deputy transportation commissioner. ``Garage fees are so high
that people think it's cheaper to park illegally. The $100 parking
ticket will change that.''
   The new fines require the approval of the Legislature, which has
a $50 cap for the fees municipalities can charge for illegal
parking.
   Schwartz said passage is expected.
</TEXT>
