<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomeRaffle     04-06 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Raffle,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Gets Tentative Go-Ahead To Raffle Repossessed Homes To Poor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city has gotten tentative approval
to buy homes repossessed for unpaid government mortgages and sell
them for $1 to poor families chosen through a raffle, officials
said.
   ``There are going to be some mighty lucky people out there'' if
the program wins full approval, said Phillip Aguirre, local urban
homesteading coordinator for the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development.
   The city had asked for $600,000 to buy homes in three
neighborhoods, but the amount is likely to be less, Aguirre said
Tuesday.
   The application has been approved by HUD, but the contract
agreement between the city and the federal government has yet to be
drawn up.
   ``HUD agrees with the plan in principle,'' Aguirre said. ``I
just doubt that it will come out with full funding the first time
around.''
   Under the homesteading program, the buyers must repair, maintain
and occupy the homes for a minimum of five consecutive years.
   Margi Gant, the city's Community Development Office coordinator,
said that if $600,000 is approved, 24 homes could be bought at the
$25,000 maximum allowed.
   The development office should receive a contract from HUD later
this month, officials said.
   To get in the lottery, home seekers will have to show they
qualify for a government loan or can do repairs to ensure the home
is rehabilitated. Once the work is complete, the deed to the home
will be sold to the purchaser for $1.
   The houses repossessed will be those foreclosed on HUD or
Federal Housing Administration loans.
</TEXT>
