<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RFKJournalismAwards     04-06 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RFK Journalism Awards,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Journal Wins Top Prize in Kennedy Journalism Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wall Street Journal reporter won the grand
prize in the 20th annual Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Awards for
best overall coverage of problems of the disadvantaged in 1987.
   Alex Kotlowitz, who works in the Journal's Chicago bureau, won
for a story, ``Urban Trauma,'' that depicted the brutality of life
in a Chicago housing project.
   In preparing the story, Kotlowitz spent three months with a
12-year-old boy and his family in the Henry Horner Homes in
Chicago. He will receive a $2,000 grand prize, Susan Pastrick of
the awards office said Wednesday.
   ``Mr. Kotlowitz has given us a common story from an uncommon
viewpoint,'' said Lesley Stahl of CBS News and chairwoman of the
awards committee. ``It is an important piece of journalism and an
outstanding example of what the RFK awards program is about.''
   First prize in television went to WCVB-TV in Boston for ``Inside
Bridgewater,'' first prize in photojournalism went to Donna Ferrato
of The Philadelphia Inquirer for ``Domestic Violence,'' and first
prize in the editorial cartoon category went to Don Wright of The
Miami News.
   Honorable mentions (second place) went to:
   _Television: WCBV-TV, Boston, for ``Back Country Blues.''
   _Print: The Atlanta Constitution and Journal, ``Rural Justice.''
   _Photojournalism: Michel duCille, The Miami Herald, ``Crack the
Graveyard.''
   _Editorial Cartoons: Bill Day, The Detroit Free Press.
   Citations (third place) went to:
   _Television: WBZ-TV, Boston, ``AIDS: The Paul Cronan Story.''
   _Print: The Sacramento Bee, ``Hunger in California.''
   _Photojournalism: Manny Crisostomo, The Detroit Free Press,
``Too Young To Die.''
   _Editorial Cartoons: Doug Marlette, The Atlanta Constitution.
   The awards _ accompanied by $1,000 each for the first-prize
winners _ will be presented May 16 by Mrs. Robert F. Kennedy at a
ceremony and reception at her home in northern Virginia, Ms.
Pastrick said.
   The awards program is dedicated to the memory and concerns of
Kennedy, the late senator from New York who was assassinated in Los
Angeles in 1968 while he was running for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   The program is sponsored by the Robert F. Kennedy Memorial and
is open to professional and student journalists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     04-06 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Militias Fight in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias fought in
the streets of south Lebanon on Wednesday, the second day of a
battle for supremacy in which police say 12 people have been killed
and 34 wounded.
   A police spokesman said the mainstream Amal militia used armored
vehicles, artillery, mortars and rocket-propelled grenades against
the Hezbollah, or Party of God, in 14 towns and villages.
   Amal is led by Nabih Berri, the Lebanese justice minister, and
has Syrian support. The fundamentalist Hezbollah is loyal to Iran.
   Militia officers also ``toured the south in loudspeaker vans
blaring warnings to Hezbollah fighters to surrender their weapons
and avert the bloodshed,'' the police spokesman said.
   He quoted Amal as telling Hezbollah gunmen: ``Our main aim is
security and stability for the south. Whoever surrenders his weapon
will live in peace.''
   Fear was expressed in many circles that the war for supremacy in
the predominantly Shiite region would spread to the rest of
Lebanon, which has been ravaged by civil war for 13 years. This led
the nation's most leading Shiite cleric, Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, to order an end to the battle.
   ``We prohibit this fighting because it burns Islam's causes and
the Moslems,'' he said in a fatwa, or religious ruling.
   Despite Fadlallah's declaration, Amal-Hezbollah fighting raged
all day from Nabatiyeh, an inland market town, to the ancient port
of Tyre.
   The police spokesman, whose name was withheld in accordance with
regulations, gave this account:
   Amal forces with armored personnel carriers and 106mm recoilless
artillery advanced across Nabatiyeh's main street to the town's old
sector, where Hezbollah fighters were installed in sniping nests.
   ``The fighting in Nabatiyeh is ferocious. Rescue teams have not
been able to evacuate casualties in some parts of the town.
Nabatiyeh citizens have been hiding in basements and bomb shelters
since Tuesday.''
   About 50 women and old men ventured out in a relatively quiet
neighborhood ``chanting slogans demanding an end to the fighting''
but ``dashed for cover again when two mortar rounds slammed into
the neighborhood.''
   Berri's militiamen stormed Hezbollah positions in the village of
Siddiqine, eight miles southeast of Tyre, before dawn.
   Hezbollah fighters sought refugee at Siddiqine's
Iranian-financed Shiite religious school, the main base of Sheik
Abdul Moneem Mhanna, said to be a Hezbollah leader in the Tyre
region.
   ``Amal militiamen surrounded Mhanna's school and are calling on
Hezbollah fighters to surrender.''
   All Amal and Hezbollah fighters in south Lebanon are on ``full
alert. Each side has erected checkpoints in its areas of influence
to prevent the other from reinforcing its positions.''
   Fighting began Tuesday when Hezbollah gunmen attacked an Amal
checkpoint near Nabatiyeh, killing an Amal militiaman and wounding
four others. The police spokesman said the attack followed Amal
raids on houses in Nabatiyeh and surrounding villages in which 10
Hezbollah members were captured.
   He said Amal was searching for Hezbollah members suspected of
opening fire Monday on the car of the Amal chief in Nabatiyeh,
Mahmoud Faqih, who was not in the vehicle.
   Relations between Amal and Hezbollah have deteriorated since
Feb. 17 when Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, the U.S. Marine who
commands the U.N. truce observer unit, was kidnapped near Tyre.
Amal rounded up dozens of Hezbollah members it accused of
involvement.
   Hezbollah has denied involvement in the abduction of Higgins,
43, of Danville, Ky., and said Amal was ``harassing the believers
by searching for an American spy.''
   A group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth, a pro-Iranian underground group believed affiliated with
Hezbollah, has claimed responsibility for abducting Higgins.
   Hezbollah is thought to be an umbrella group for pro-Iranian
underground factions holding most of the 22 foreigners missing and
presumably kidnapped in Lebanon.
   Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
