<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneCrash     04-06 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Killed in Crash of Single-Engine Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANASSAS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed in a field about a
half-mile south of Manassas Municipal Airport, killing four people,
authorities said today.
   Before the crash, the pilot had reported poor visibility and
requested weather information for two other airports, said Federal
Aviation Administration spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen. The plane was
headed for the Manassas airport.
   The names of the victims were not immediately released. Manassas
police said the victims included a male pilot, 60, and three female
passengers, ages 60, 30 and 12.
   The wreckage was spotted shortly after dawn today. Rescue
workers had to cut the aircraft in half to remove the bodies.
   The plane, a Piper Archer, was registered to Johnnie Q. Herrin
of Nahunta, Ga., the FAA said. The flight's origination point was
not known, Ms. Bergen said.
   The plane crashed after the pilot radioed a Washington flight
control center at about 8 p.m. Tuesday and reported poor
visibility, Ms. Bergen said. The pilot requested weather
information for Charlottesville and Dulles International Airport
near Washington.
   The National Transportation Safety Board is investigating the
crash.
</TEXT>
