<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0446 04-06 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with judge's ruling</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case today ruled
he needed more time to study independent counsel Lawrence E.
Walsh's plan to prevent unauthorized disclosure of 150,000 pages of
classified documents.
   In a brief opinion, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell denied
Walsh's motion for expedited consideration of the proposed
protective order, saying it ``appears to be far too complex, lacks
definite time restrictions and creates undue obstacles to the fair
and expeditious disposition of this case.''
   But the judge said he wants to set an April deadline for Walsh's
review of the classified material and fix a time for the defense to
notify the court whether it intends to use any of the secret
documents as evidence.
   Gesell said he would hear further argument at next Tuesday's
hearing on ``the timing of discovery disclosures in relation to a
realistic trial date.''
   The documents, which Walsh says ``describe in detail some of the
nation's most carefully held secrets about its foreign policy, its
intelligence activities and its covert activities,'' must be turned
over to the defense as part of pre-trial discovery.
   Some of the documents from the CIA, the State Department, the
National Security Council and other agencies may be introduced as
evidence after they are declassified or secret material is deleted.
   Lawyers for former national security adviser John Poindexter,
Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and arms dealers Richard V. Secord and
Albert Hakim had filed a motion opposing Walsh's plan to require
them and their clients to obtain security clearances to examine the
material.
   The four are accused of conspiracy to defraud the government by
diverting arms-sale proceeds to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Walsh had sought expedited consideration of his plan by the
judge.
   But Gesell said: ``It will be necessary to frame a more limited
protective order fashioned to the nature of this case, which in
essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified
materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.''
   The proposal includes setting up a ``secure compartmented
information facility'' where the defense lawyers would be required
to work with the documents and compose any pleadings that quote the
material.
   Without such procedures, Walsh said, he cannot begin turning
over the material to the defense for pre-trial discovery.
   Walsh had also asked Gesell to establish intricate procedures
under the Classified Information Procedures Act (CIPA) for court
review of classified documents to determine how such information
could be disclosed in court.
   The act empowers a trial judge to delete classified portions of
a document if it is irrelevent to the case or to substitute a
statement of facts that secret material would prove if shown to a
jury.
   In a joint pleading filed Tuesday, defense lawyers opposed
Walsh's motion because it raised questions about ``the
constitutionality (as well as the statutory propriety) of various
aspects of the proposed order even if the CIPA itself is
constitutional.''
   The defense said it wants more time to file briefs on a number
of issues it contends are raised by Walsh's proposal.
   The defense contends that the proposed order would impose
``improper and questionable'' conditions on the defense lawyers and
their clients.
   The defense noted that the order would apply to classified
information that had already been known to the defendants,
particularly North and Poindexter.
   The attorneys also questioned whether Walsh, as an independent
counsel, has the proper authority to enforce the Classified
Information Procedures Act.
   The defense said Walsh's request raises ``questions whether the
president's foreign affairs and national security responsibilities
can be delegated to an official such as Mr. Walsh.''
   In reply, Walsh said the defense was attempting ``to invent
substantive isues concerning the proposed protective order where
none exists.''
   Walsh labeled ``transparent'' the defense objection to applying
the restrictions to North and Poindexter.
   ``Classified information does not become declassified because a
criminal defendant knew it before he was indicted; if that were the
case, there would have been no need for the CIPA in the many
espionage trials where the statute has been used extensively,''
Walsh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
