<1ST_LINE>r a AM-McDonald'sMilestone     04-06 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McDonald's Milestone,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McDonald's Opens 10,000th Restaurant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALE CITY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may seem as if a new set of golden
arches is springing up every day, but the McDonald's fast-food
restaurant that opened for business Wednesday was special. It was
No. 10,000.
   The corporation known for reciting numbers as if they had
mystical properties _ more than 65 billion hamburgers served _
dispatched about 20,000 balloons skyward at the opening in Dale
City and another 10,000 exactly at the Convention Center in
Washington, where it was holding its biannual convention for
franchisees and partners, said Richard G. Starmann, senior vice
president.
   ``It's almost 33 years to the day when Ray Kroc opened his first
McDonald's,'' said the corporation's president and chief executive
officer, Mike Quinlan. ``If Ray were here, he would be fiercely
proud of the McDonald's family.''
   The fast-food chain branched into Eastern Europe on March 24
when it opened a restaurant in Belgrade, the capital of Yugoslavia,
and plans to open another one in Budapest in May. Hungary will thus
become the 50th country around the world to have a McDonald's.
   Of the 10,000 restaurants, 75 percent are locally operated by
independent entrepreneurs. Others are joint-venture partnerships
and some wholly owned subsidiaries, Starmann said.
   Kroc opened the first McDonald's restaurant on April 15, 1955,
in Des Plaines, Ill. Sales on that rainy day, according to a
statement from the company, were $366.12.
   Last year, McDonald's worldwide sales were $14.3 billion and it
served 22 million customers in 49 countries. It passed the mark of
60 billion hamburgers served in November 1986.
</TEXT>
