<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hijack-Thailand     04-06 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Thailand,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai Officials Contacted about Possible Forged Passports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials investigating the hijack of a
Kuwait Airways jet that departed from Bangkok were told Wednesday
that four passengers may have boarded with forged Bahraini
passports.
   A senior member of the Thai police force who asked not to be
identified told The Associated Press that Bahraini officials had
contacted the Thais concerning the possible fogery. The identities
of the four have not been released.
   The Thai government has made virtually no statements on the
hijack of Flight 422, which was commandeered Tuesday while en route
from Bangkok to Kuwait, and it appeared to be trying to keep the
investigation on a low key, possibly to avoid embarrassment should
a security flaw at the airport be discovered.
   Vidhya Rayanonda, a Foreign Ministry spokesman, told reporters
he did not think Thailand's image would be damaged because
``hijacks occur everywhere.''
   Vidhya said security at Bangkok's Don Muang International
Airport was adequate and he raised the possibility that the weapons
used by the hijackers might have been put on the Boeing 747 in
Kuwait. The airliner flew into Bangkok from Kuwait on Monday and
was on the ground for about 15 hours before taking off for Kuwait.
   One passenger was quoted by Iranian media as saying the
hijackers were armed with pistols and hand grenades.
   ``We still don't know where the weapons came from or how they
got there (on the plane) in the first place,'' said Charoon
Peetong, the general manager of the airport.
   ``But we are looking for serious answers to our questions,
though answers will more likely be found in Mashhad,'' he said,
referring to the northeastern Iranian city where the plane was
diverted.
   Charoon said authorities were double-checking all personnel who
were near the jumbo jet before take-off Tuesday, including the
airline's caterer, ground mechanics and those who refueled the
aircraft, he said.
   There have been no known major complaints from foreign
governments or international agencies about security at Bangkok
airport. Passengers and carry-on luggage are searched by electronic
devices.
</TEXT>
