<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Future 2ndLd-Writethru a0642 04-06 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Future, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0642,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Not Quitting Politics Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham-Mofford, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Earlier, the ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Mecham's name ordered off recall ballot. 11th graf, `He
jokingly ...' may be offensive to some readers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Mecham may be the first U.S. governor
in 59 years to have lost his job through impeachment conviction,
but he isn't ready to say he's giving up politics.
   Interviewed this morning on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
Mecham said that he'd ``definitely run in it (a recall election)
unless they get it so tied up in legal technicalities. I can win
the re-election, win the recall election, I think.''
   Acting Secretary of State Karen Osborne's office said today that
she had ordered Mecham's name removed from the recall ballot
pending a resolution of legal issues. The attorney general's office
said that because Mecham was placed on the ballot through his
status as governor, and not by gathering petitions as the other
candidates did, he is no longer entitled to be on it.
   Earlier, the ousted Republican governor told a Kiwanis club,
``This is just another chapter in a book, and this book isn't near
the end.''
   ``I haven't yet determined what my course will be,'' Mecham told
the group Tuesday, one day after he was ousted by the Senate. ``I
haven't yet said that I'm not going to be a candidate in the recall
(on May 17). I'm not even sure that I choose to be in.''
   As Mecham's replacement, former Secretary of State Rose Mofford,
was sworn in Tuesday, Attorney General Bob Corbin said he hoped the
Arizona Supreme Court would decide within a week whether the recall
election must still be held.
   Concerned Arizona Voters, a pro-Mecham group, has dropped its
opposition to the election because it now sees the recall as the
former governor's last hope for regaining his office.
   Mecham, who described himself as the ``recent former governor,''
appeared relaxed Tuesday. ``I have no rancor in my heart for
anybody,'' he said.
   However, he warned that those who ousted him may not realize
they have ``awakened a sleeping giant'' in the Arizona electorate.
   ``I know that they are aroused, I know that they are incensed, I
know that they are right-down angry,'' said Mecham.
   He jokingly referred to the Kiwanis group as the ``round-eyes
club,'' recalling the day several months ago when Mecham was
severely criticized for telling the same group that when a group of
Japanese people were told about Arizona's golf courses, ``suddenly
they got round eyes.''
   Recalling his remark, the former governor said, ``That's an
in-house joke between me and this club and, let's see, about half
the world, I think.''
   Mecham, who also provoked criticism for comments that were
perceived as slurs against blacks, homosexuals and Jews, became the
first governor to be removed from office in 59 years on Monday when
the Senate convicted him of obstructing justice and misusing
$80,000 from the governor's protocol fund.
   Several weeks ago, Mecham had said that if the Senate convicted
him, he might go to the U.S. Supreme Court to claim that his rights
had been violated. He said Tuesday he had not decided whether he
will do so.
   Mecham also faces a criminal trial April 21 on charges of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan. If convicted, he would be
barred from holding office again.
   But Mecham said today he was confident that if justice prevails,
he will be found innocent. ``If we can get a fair jury, we should
get acquitted quite easily,'' he said on ``Good Morning America.''
</TEXT>
