<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers     04-06 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders DeSillers To Return Attorney Fees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a woman to return $25,000 she
paid her lawyers from money donated for her 7-year-old son's liver
transplants.
   ``The withdrawal was an illegal and unlawful act,'' Circuit
Judge Francis J. Christie said Tuesday during a hearing on the
action by Maria DeSillers. ``She must return that sum to the
(Ronnie's) estate, which subsequently, and ironically, she could
very well become heir to.''
   Ronnie died April 29 while awaiting a fourth liver transplant at
Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh. His plight moved hundreds of
people, including President Reagan, to donate more than $670,000
for his operations.
   Ms. DeSillers paid $25,000 to the father-and-son law office of
Leonard and Harry Robbins, who argued Tuesday that she was entitled
to use the money.
   ``DeSillers was a woman alone in the world,'' Leonard Robbins
said. ``All she knew (was) that she was being attacked from all
sides when she went to hire an attorney.''
   During the hearing, trust curator Karen Gievers claimed that the
law office had violated state probate and banking laws by accepting
the money. Ms. Gievers was appointed trust curator last month to
oversee the $239,287 that remains in Ronnie's trust accounts.
   Harry Robbins said he will continue representing Ms. DeSillers
regardless of her financial troubles.
   Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh is suing Ms. DeSillers for
$262,000, what it claims is the unpaid portion of Ronnie's $424,300
medical bill. Ms. DeSillers has said she refused to pay the balance
because of allegedly poor care. She and Harry Robbins have said
they plan to countersue the hospital.
   The state has filed an administrative complaint against Ms.
DeSillers and fined her $1,000 for allegedly violating charity
laws. The complaint and fine are being appealed.
   Ms. DeSillers' use of Ronnie's trust also is being investigated
by Dade State Attorney Janet Reno. That investigation prompted Ms.
Gievers' appointment.
</TEXT>
