<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JerryBrown     04-06 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jerry Brown,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jerry Brown Celebrates 50th Birthday Privately</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Brown, whose unorthodox style
and ideas made him one of the nation's hot young politicians in the
1970s, celebrates his 50th birthday Thursday the way he has spent
most of the last six years _ in private.
   Brown has been dropping hints in recent months that he plans a
comeback, possibly a race for the U.S. Senate in 1992. But he says
the time is not yet right to seek the media spotlight again.
   Therefore, he vetoed plans by a group of friends and supporters
for a birthday celebration this week at a Los Angeles hotel with
1,000 to 1,500 guests.
   ``It's just not the right time,'' Brown told reporters. ``If I
were more active in the public domain, then it might be
appropriate.''
   Instead, Brown will celebrate Thursday with what he describes as
a small family gathering.
   Reclusiveness has been Brown's way since he lost a race for the
U.S. Senate six years ago to Republican Pete Wilson. He has spent
most of the past six years traveling, with especially long stays in
Mexico and Japan, and writing a still-unfinished book.
   That defeat ended eight years in which Brown was constantly in
the media spotlight with two successful races for governor, two
unsuccessful campaigns for the Democratic nomination for president
and the Senate race.
   Brown chafed at the constant attention even during the campaign
periods when he was working hardest to attract coverage, and he
seemed to be genuinely relieved at his close defeat in the Senate
race. ``The people ... would like a respite from me, and in some
ways, I need a respite from them,'' he said in his concession
speech.
   Even in that speech, Brown said he planned to return to
political life eventually.
   In a long interview four months ago, Brown told The Associated
Press that he still plans to return to politics. He refused to cite
a specific race but as he ruled out various options in response to
questions, he eliminated nearly everything except running for the
Senate if Democrat Alan Cranston retires in 1992.
   On personal subjects, Brown was as evasive as ever, confirming
only that marrying and raising a family ``is on my mind ... but it
hasn't happened yet.''
   Brown is spending part of his time practicing what he described
as ``business law'' with a large Los Angeles firm. He declined to
discuss that except to say that it involves ``a number of things
I've learned in government I can help clients with.''
</TEXT>
