<HEAD>Ailing Chinese Priest Gets OK for U.S. Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop, formerly imprisoned for
30 years for loyalty to the Vatican, has won permission to seek
medical treatment in the United States, a state-supported church
group said Wednesday.
   The Shanghai municipal government and the state-sanctioned
Patriotic Catholic Church decided to let Bishop Ignatius Kung, also
known as Gong Pinmei, to make the trip, according to Liu Bainian, a
spokesman for the Chinese Catholic Patriotic Association.
   Kung, 87, of Shanghai, has a hearing problem and suffers
cardiovascular ailments.
   Liu provided no details on where and when Kung will seek
treatment.
   Kung was released from prison in 1985 and says he remains loyal
to the pope. He disavows the Patriotic Catholic Church, which
severed ties with the Vatican in 1957 and ordains its own bishops.
   Kung, appointed prelate of the Shanghai diocese by Rome in 1950,
was arrested in 1955 on charges of treason and sentenced to life
imprisonment for leading ``a counterrevolutionary clique under the
cloak of religion.''
   He was released following campaigns by international religious
and human rights groups and an appeal from the Vatican.
