<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Coins     04-06 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Turkey-Coins,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Auctioneer Gives Ancient Coins Back to Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. auction company will return 10
ancient coins, part of a 1,890-coin collection smuggled abroad four
years ago, the Foreign Ministry announced Wednesday.
   Numismatic Fine Arts International Inc. in Los Angeles already
has handed over the Lycian coins to the Turkish consulate there, a
ministry statement said.
   The Turkish government said the coins were dug up illegally in
the Mediterranean coastal village of Elmali. It gave no information
on who may have taken the coins and said the whereabouts of the
rest of the collection are unknown.
   Turkey has long been a popular hunting ground for smugglers of
antiques with its sites of more than a dozen ancient civilizations,
including Hittite, Greek, Hellenistic, Roman, and Byzantine.
   Turkey has stepped up efforts to retrieve some of its treasures
from foreign musuems. The government filed suit against the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York last year for the return of
a 2,600-year-old collection of gold and silver antique pieces.
</TEXT>
