<HEAD>Injuries Reported as Ammunition Explodes at Soviet Troop Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ammunition exploded at a base for
Soviet troops in Hungary on Wednesday, injuring several people,
according to an official report.
   The blast occurred at the Veszprem base about 60 miles southwest
of Budapest, injuring ``several people, including one Hungarian
citizen,'' the news agency MTI said in a terse, three-sentence
report.
   It added only that ``the consequences of the explosion have been
eliminated.''
   There were no details about how the ammunition came to explode,
where the incident occurred or how many people were hurt.
   Veszprem is the largest Soviet troop base in Hungary. There are
an estimated 100,000 Soviet soldiers stationed in the Warsaw Pact
nation.
   Gyula Horn, a senior official of the Hungarian Foreign Ministry,
told Western reporters last month that there have been talks about
withdrawing the Soviet forces. Horn said no agreement had been
reached.
