<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerImplants     04-06 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Implants,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Technique Means Instant Breast Replacement for Cancer Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new plastic surgery technique which moves fatty
tissue from the ``saddle bags'' area of the thigh offers victims of
breast cancer another option in reconstruction surgery, says the
surgeon who developed it.
   Medical science may someday eliminate breast cencer, said
Franklyn Elliott, an Atlanta plastic surgeon. ``But in the
meantime, we can take the fear out of the surgery. People won't be
so terrified. It won't be maiming to so many people.''
   The procedure developed by Elliott and his associate Dr. Philip
H. Beegle Jr., has been performed just four times at St. Joseph's
Hospital of Atlanta. The first was in December.
   After diseased cancerous tissue is removed, plastic surgeons
implant the fatty tissue and the artery that feeds it to replace
the lost breast tissue.
   The surgeons connect the artery and vein in the thigh tissue
into an artery and vein in the armpit area. The plastic surgeons
use a small piece of skin from the thigh to replace the areola and
nipple, which are removed as part of the cancer surgery.
   When the patient wakes up, she has two breasts, both of which
are her own tissue.
   For years, cancer patients who had to have breasts removed could
only wear a padded bra after the surgery. Then doctors developed
implants to replace the lost tissue. In the 1980s, a variety of
replacement surgeries were developed, using the patient's own
tissue from the abdomen or the buttock.
   ``We went to work in the lab and found this pocket of tissue
that is fairly easily removed and has its own blood supply,'' said
Beegle. ``It gives the patient another option.''
   Today's options for a breast cancer patient include breast
removal or, if the cancer is detected very early, the tumors can be
removed in a ``lumpectomy'' which is followed by radiation
treatment.
   If the treatment is a mastectomy, removal of the breast and
lymph nodes, the patient can select from several forms of
reconstruction, including a combination of her own tissue and a
small implant, Elliott said.
   Arthur Holleb, a former breast cancer surgeon and now chief
medical officer for the American Cancer Society in New York, said
breast cancer can bring psychological problems.
   ``The impact of the psychosocial decision is tremendous,'' he
said in a telephone interview from his office. The society, he
said, has a visitation program in hospitals which assists 70,000
breast cancer patients each year.
   ``The anxiety varies from woman to woman. The breast is so
important to most women,'' said John Bostwick, nationally known
plastic surgeon from Emory University.
   ``It's such a shock to a young woman to have a breast cancer,
particularly if she is young and healthy, and the treatment is
going to do a lot to hurt her feminity,'' he said. ``We find if we
can tell them we can do a reconstruction, it helps.''
   The replacement with ``saddle bags'' tissue is an easier
operation than replacement from the buttocks, Beegle said.
   ``I think their technique is very innovative for selected women.
It's going to be very worthwhile,'' Bostwick said.
   ``For the woman who doesn't have a lot of tissue in the abdomen,
it provides another alternative to to find the tissue'' for
reconstruction.
   In one patient, who lost both breasts, ``we used tissue from the
abdomen on one side and from the hip on the other,'' Elliott said.
``It allows us to have the luxury of the option.''
   Only about 10 percent of 15 percent of the breast cancer
patients in the Atlanta area now seek reconstruction, but the
number is increasing, the surgeons said.
   Early detection of breast cancer, through self-examination and
mammograpny has lowered the age of breast cancer patients, they
said, meaning the patient is more likely to seek reconstruction.
   This procedure doesn't leave a scar on the abdomen and the
incision to remove the thigh tissues is concealed under the buttock
so after recovery ``the patient will feel comfortable in shorts, a
tennis dress or a bathing suit, the scar won't show,'' Elliott said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     04-06 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budapest Launches Strongest Criticism Yet on Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary on Wednesday launched its
strongest criticism yet on communist ally Romania over an ethnic
dispute that has clouded relations between the Warsaw Pact
neighbors for two years.
   Two Hungarian newspapers printed editorials fiercely critical of
a reported Romanian move to use only Romanian-language place names
for cities and villages traditionally known to Romania's German and
Hungarian ethnic minorities in their own languages.
   About 1.7 million Hungarians and 220,000 ethnic Germans live in
Romania, mostly in the central province of Transylvania. Hungary
has expressed mounting concern over what it says are Romanian moves
to cut back Hungarian-language education and disperse the minority
throughout Romania.
   Romania charges that Hungary's complaints mask an effort by
Budapest to regain Transylvania, which was ruled by Hungary for
several centuries but given to Romania after World War I.
   Both claim that Transylvania is the area where their nations
were first settled, and they have squabbled over the region for
decades.
   In the past two years, however, the dispute has escalated,
pointing up the difference between Hungary's reformist communism
and the tight rule of President Nicolae Ceausescu in Romania, which
is increasingly isolated from its East bloc allies.
   The government daily Magyar Hirlap said violations of minority
rights to maintain their own language and culture can ``neither be
understood, or accepted ... at the end of the 20th century on our
continent.''
   The harsh editorial stopped short of blaming Ceausescu for the
move to use only Romanian place names, but said ``it could hardly
be a local excess ... (since) to our knowledge the strings reach
much higher.''
   Another daily, Magyar Nemzet, condemned Ceausescu's recently
announced program to wipe out up to 7,000 villages in Romania by
the year 2000 as ``drastic ... demolition'' and an attempt to quash
Romanian, Hungarian and other minority cultures.
   Magyar Hirlap also took Romania to task for its unprecedented
action in denying Hungary's Bucharest ambassador a traditional
address on national radio and television to mark Hungary's
Liberation Day April 4.
   The newspaper noted this was a break with tradition, and said
without further detail that ``it is regrettable that such themes
can emerge between two neighboring Socialist countries.''
   Western analysts said Wednesday's attacks were the sharpest yet
in the war of words between the nations.
   Hungarian dissidents, who demonstrated for human rights in
Romania outside the Romanian Embassy in Budapest on Feb. 1, have
charged the Budapest government is to some extent exploiting
popular Hungarian unease about the treatment of ethnic Hungarians
in Romania to divert attention from the country's economic crisis.
   But Hungary took unprecedented action last month when it
approved spending about $6 million to help an estimated 10,000
refugees who have fled the shortages and harsh living conditions in
Romania for Hungary. Many but not all of the refugees are ethnic
Hungarians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
