<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Fees, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Pay Mecham's Legal Fees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with trial formally closed,
picking up at 3rd graf previous.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham-Mofford, Bjt and PM-Mecham-Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate voted today to pay former
Gov. Evan Mecham's $202,433 in legal fees for the impeachment trial
that removed him from office.
   The 16-13 vote came shortly before the Senate formally closed
the impeachment trial that began Feb. 29 and resulted in Mecham's
ouster from office on Monday.
   Defense attorney Jerris Leonard had asked the Senate to begin a
``healing process'' by paying the fees.
   ``This has been an agony,'' Leonard said. ``I think it's the
right thing to do ... to show that this body not only has class,
but it has heart, it has compassion.''
   Republican Sen. Greg Lunn agreed, saying it would be a
``magnanimous gesture.''
   GOP Sen. Pat Wright said she thought Mecham's legal fees should
be paid because Arizona taxpayers funded the prosecution and trial,
and many ``resent deeply their tax dollars being used to convict a
governor that they supported.''
   However, Sen. John Mawhinney, also a Republican, argued against
paying the defense costs.
   ``We didn't start this process; the House of Representatives
didn't start this process'' when it impeached Mecham, Mawhinney
said. ``Evan Mecham, the governor, started the process.''
   Mawhinney said that if senators wanted to show compassion they
might want to pay the legal fees themselves, adding, ``I can't
believe you can do that with somebody else's money.''
   Democratic Sen. Chuy Higuera suggested that the state and Mecham
split the cost.
   The Senate voted Monday to remove Mecham, a first-term
Republican, from office for obstructing justice by trying to thwart
an investigation of an alleged death threat and for misusing
$80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership.
   GOP Sen. John Hays said he thought the matter should be referred
to the Legislature and suggested that the $92,000 governor's
protocol fund _ which remains in a bank _ might be used to pay
Mecham's expenses.
   Leonard said he expected to be paid whether the money came from
the state or Mecham himself.
   The attorney said that when he met with Mecham after his
conviction, ``I found not one sign of retribution in him of any
thought of revenge or rancor.''
   ``He said to us that when your first vote was completed ... that
he felt relieved,'' Leonard said.
   The prosecution took no position on whether Mecham's fees should
be paid. Prosecutor Paul Eckstein said the matter should be up to
the Senate's discretion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
