<DOCNO> AP880406-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsInstitutions     04-06 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Institutions,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S&L Deposits Up for Fifth Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposits at federally insured savings
institutions grew for the fifth consecutive month in February,
continuing a trend begun after the October stock market crash, the
government said Wednesday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates 3,126 savings
institutions, said net deposits increased by $5.2 billion, compared
with a $5.4 billion increase in January and a $1.1 billion net
withdrawal in February 1987.
   The increase came despite the deteriorating financial condition
of many thrift institutions, particularly in Texas where
institutions have been hit hard by the depressed energy and real
estate markets.
   A third of the industry lost money last year, pushing overall
1987 losses to a post-Depression record of $6.8 billion.
   Despite the losses, money has been flowing into S&L accounts,
which are insured up to $100,000, since the crash: $6.2 billion in
October, $3.2 billion in November, and $2.6 billion in December.
   That is reversing what was described as a slow-motion run on
S&Ls, which had net withdrawals in seven of the first nine months
of last year.
   ``I think you're still getting, as late as it seems, a kind of
stock market effect here,'' said Mark Obrinsky, an economist with
the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the industry's largest
trade group.
   ``Although the stock market hasn't declined since October, it
hasn't gone up much either. A lot of consumers are rethinking what
they're doing with their money and parking some or all of it into
thrifts and perhaps banks,'' he said.
   Unlike the early months after the crash, which saw an increase
in deposits of $100,000 and more, the increase so far in 1988 has
come in smaller accounts, which are institutions' least costly
source of funds.
   Meanwhile, in a separate report, the bank board said interest
rates for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages fell from 10.48 percent in
early February to 10.34 percent in early March, the lowest since
last April.
   Rates on the most popular type of one-year adjustable mortgages,
those with caps on how much the rate can change, fell less sharply,
from 8.72 percent to 8.65 percent.
   The bank board figures do not reflect the most recent nudge
upward in interest rates. According to the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp., 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages have edged up from
9.84 percent on Feb. 12, the low for this year, to 10.05 percent on
April 1. This survey did not include add-on fees, known as points,
which are included in the bank board averages.
   Mortgage lending by S&Ls rose slightly to $13.5 billion in
February from $13.1 billion in January, which was the lowest level
since February 1985, the bank board said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Ocean-Climate     04-06 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ocean-Climate,360</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Launch Ocean-Climate Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of weather scientists will be cruising
the Pacific Ocean over the next four months, but it's all for
research.
   Heat and moisture from the oceans have a major impact on weather
and climate. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
scientists want to learn more about how the air and water interact.
   The first leg of the work is under way, with the team sailing
from Dutch Harbor, Alaska, to Samoa.
   Scientists are measuring the amounts of carbon dioxide, carbon
monoxide, methane and other gases in Pacific surface waters and the
overlying air.
   Similar sampling was done in 1983, and the new study will allow
comparison of the changes in these gases.
   Concentrations of the gases in the upper atmosphere can prevent
heat from sunlight from being reflected out into space, possibly
leading to a warming known as the Greenhouse effect, according to
Tim Bates of the Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory in Seattle.
   At the same time the scientists will sample sulfur gases and
look for aerosols in the sea and air.
   These chemicals could increase the reflective power of the
clouds over the ocean, reducing the amount of sunlight and heat
reaching the surface.
   At Samoa, a second team of scientists will board the research
ship Oceanographer to begin a study of the periodic changes in
ocean temperature and air pressure known as the El Nino phenomenon.
   The El Nino has been blamed for unusual changes in weather
around the world, but scientists are not sure how these effects
occur.
   During a cruise from Samoa to Panama via Honolulu they will
measure air pressure and ocean currents and temperature, all
factors which appear to play a role.
   In addition they will perform maintenance on an array of moored
and drifting sensors which collect weather data and send the
information back via satellite.
   Joining the NOAA meteorologists on the first leg of the trip are
scientists from the University of Washington, Washington State
University and the University of Hawaii.
   On the second leg will be researchers from the University of
Washington, Scripps Institute of Oceanography, University of South
Florida and Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Iran-Contra-Pardons 1stLd-Writethru a0580 04-06 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra-Pardons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with Fitzwater comment on Reagan remark; No
Pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater today described as ``a throwaway remark'' a comment by
President Reagan indicating approval of the notion of pardoning
indicted former aide Oliver North.
   Reagan did not say that he would pardon former White House aides
or others accused in the Iran-Contra affair. But, after hearing a
proposal for pardons, he did say ``I like the sound of those
words,'' said one congressman quoted in The Washington Post.
   Another congressman quoted Reagan as saying, ``I like hearing
what you said,'' after Rep. Henry J. Hyde suggested the president
should pardon North and former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter at the end of Reagan's term.
   Hyde, R-Ill., suggested the pardons be signed during ceremonies
at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, according to the
Post.
   During a briefing for reporters at this seaside resort, not far
from Reagan's ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains, Fitzwater was
questioned about the president's intentions.
   ``I was there at that meeting, and Henry Hyde said he hoped that
North would be pardoned, and the president told him he is not
discussing pardons at this time,'' the spokesman said.
   ``And then there was some throwaway line, and I didn't give it
any significance then or at this time,'' Fitzwater said. ``I don't
believe you should make any assumptions or conclusions on the basis
of a throwaway remark.''
   Fitzwater said he could not remember Reagan's precise words, but
he did not dispute the quote attributed to Reagan.
   ``I have raised the issue with the president four or five times,
and every time he has said he wasn't discussing pardons,'' the
spokesman said.
   Hyde's proposal and Reagan's response reportedly were made March
22 during the president's appearance before the House Republican
Conference, a closed meeting attended by 160 of the 177 GOP House
members.
   The Post said the congressmen who quoted the president asked not
to be identified since it was a closed session.
   The Post quoted one congressman as saying he felt the
president's message was unmistakable and ``If I had been Ollie and
witnessed that, I would have been pretty upbeat.''
   The meeting occurred six days after North and Poindexter, along
with arms dealers Richard V. Secord and Albert A. Hakim, pleaded
innocent to federal criminal charges in the sale of arms to Iran
and the diversion of money to Contra rebels fighting the government
of Nicaragua.
   Three days later, Reagan predicted Poindexter and North would be
found innocent ``because I don't think they were guilty of any
lawbreaking or any crime.'' Speaking at a seminar sponsored by the
Center for the Study of the Presidency, Reagan called the
Iran-Contra affair ``the so-called scandal'' and said he still
considered North ``a hero.''
   The president later said he was referring to North's combat in
Vietnam.
   Fitzwater said a day after the indictments that there had been
no discussion of pardons. ``We don't discuss pardons. Period,''
Fitzwater said.
   Chief of staff Howard H. Baker later said Reagan would not
consider pardons until after North and Poindexter are tried.
   Fitzwater said today he had not been aware of Baker's remarks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
