<HEAD>Columbia Man Loses Court Fight Over Antique Junk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man's junk is another man's gold mine.
   A man was ordered to pay a fine or go to jail after a jury found
he violated zoning law by keeping eight Model-A Fords in his yard.
   ``Some people call it junk. I probably have $25,000 worth of
junk here,'' said Rawley Patton, who lost his case Tuesday in
magistrate's court.
   The six-person jury deliberated for 14 minutes after a two-hour
trial. Patton, who acted as his own attorney, was given the choice
of a $168 fine or 21 days in jail, and said he would pay the fine
and appeal ``until we have justice done.''
   Patton, 63, said the eight antique cars are being stripped to
make four or five working cars.
   He was accused of violating an ordinance forbidding unlicensed
or uninspected cars from being parked on residential lots.
