<1ST_LINE>u a PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0448 04-06 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines to Train in Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 7 grafs new on Marines being sent for training in Panama;
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Powell would.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 800 Marines are going to
Panama for training exercises, but the troop movement is not
related to the U.S. military security build-up prompted by Panama's
political turmoil, the White House said today.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the Marines, from
Camp Pendleton near San Diego, will begin arriving in Panama Friday
at an American jungle operations training center.
   ``This should not be confused with the current security
enhancement in Panama'' involving the deployment of about 1,300
troops earlier this week, Fitzwater said.
   He said the 800 Marines are scheduled to take three weeks of
training, but did not say whether a similar number is leaving
Panama.
   ``There's a constant turnover of training exercises,'' he said.
``They will be there for three weeks and then they will come out.
The only reason we announced this ... was so we could emphasize
that it was not related to the security build-up in the (U.S.)
Southern Command.''
   Administration officials are increasingly frustrated with the
failure of U.S. economic sanctions to dislodge Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega, the president's national security adviser
said Tuesday.
   Lt. Gen. Colin Powell, briefing reporters during Reagan's
vacation near here, would not rule out the possibility of sending
more American troops to Panama, beyond the additional 1,300
dispatched this week, as the United States considers new steps to
force out Noriega.
   Powell would not say how long U.S. officials would wait for the
sanctions to work.
   Powell said the administration continues to weigh military,
political and economic options, but he refused to comment on recent
reports saying a possible Noriega kidnapping had been discussed.
   ``There has been a lot of speculation about positions that
various parts of the administration hold on different subjects,''
he said during Tuesday's briefing, ``but it's really nothing until
the president calls it.''
   Noriega has clung to power despite the economic sanctions,
strikes in his country and the continued presence in hiding of
deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle. The general has been
indicted by a federal grand jury in Miami on drug-trafficking
charges.
   Powell voiced frustration with the impact so far of U.S.
economic sanctions including a freeze on Panamanian assets in this
country and withholding of payments to the Panama Canal Commission.
   He said that while the punitive measures ``are having a telling
effect'' on the Panamanian economy, ``they have not yet created
enough pressure to remove General Noriega. ... It hasn't been
sufficient to date.''
   Powell said officials are studying the implications of invoking
a law giving the U.S. government emergency power to seize tax
payments made to Panama by American businesses with operations
there.
   ``We have to be cautious before you invoke IEEPA (International
Emergency Economic Powers Act),'' he said, ``because it is a very
powerful tool.''
   ``The staff back in Washington is examining the pros and cons of
invoking IEEPA, and if it is a sensible thing to do to continue to
apply pressure on General Noriega, then we will provide that to the
president for his consideration.''
   A senior administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said it may not be possible to persuade U.S. businesses
to withhold the tax payments voluntarily.
   He said some businesses ``are having difficulty because of their
need to operate in Panama and because of what they believe are
their legal obligations.''
   This official also said that invoking the emergency powers law
could damage the Panamanian economy beyond recovery in any
post-Noriega era, saying ``we might regret it several months from
now.''
   Powell and State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said they
had no evidence to back up a Washington Times report Tuesday saying
that an international Marxist brigade of up to 1,200 troops had
been sent into Panama late last month to protect Noriega.
   ``There are indications that there have been some Cuban arms
that have been flown into Panama in recent weeks, but I have no
information supporting the presence of an international brigade,''
said Powell.
</TEXT>
