<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     04-06 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says His Base is Broadening, Dukakis Has Copied Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson put the best face
Wednesday on his loss in the Wisconsin presidential primary, saying
he has broadened his base with ``a dramatic increase in support
from whites.''
   Jackson also said the Wisconsin victor, Michael Dukakis, has
adopted his message because it has proven popular with voters.
   ``You look at the basic message formation now, even of our
rival, Mr. Dukakis, whose lead now is stop drugs, what he's done
about drugs, his lead now is save jobs, reinvest in America and
that's the right message. It's the clear Jackson message,'' Jackson
said here. Arizona Democrats hold caucuses on April 16.
   Jackson took heart from the estimated 25 percent of Wisconsin
white primary voters who exit polls said voted for him. In most of
the primaries to date, he has drawn about 10 percent of the white
vote.
   ``When we look at the results, we have an expanded support base
from among whites, a dramatic increase in support from whites,
strong support from inner city blacks,'' he said. ``When you look
at the demographics of Colorado and Milwaukee we broke through in
major ways, a historic breakthrough. Our campaign continues to
expand, continues to grow.''
   Jackson told reporters ``it is really premature to discuss what
will happen in June,'' if there is no clear-cut delegate leader
after the last primaries.
   But he said his showings to date indicate he is the people's
choice.
   ``Of 40 contests that have been run now, I've come in No. 1 or
No. 2 in 30 of them and I have a 250,000-plus popular vote lead and
so at this stage of the campaign I feel very good,'' he said.
   Jackson's claim is based on primary plus caucus votes. In
primary votes alone, Dukakis holds a lead.
   Jackson signaled Tuesday night that he planned to lay out more
details of his policies, after his vague statements drew criticism
in recent weeks.
   In Tempe, he outlined his plan for reducing the deficit and
paying for ``the dream'' _ his program of more domestic spending.
   He said $100 billion could be generated annually by 1993 to
reduce the deficit and pay for new programs by freezing Pentagon
spending at current levels and increasing taxes on individuals and
corporations.
   He said the tax rate for richest taxpayers should rise from 28
percent and 33 percent to 38.5 percent, a move he said would affect
the top 600,000 taxpayers. He said corporate taxes should move back
to the ``1970s level'' as a percentage of gross national product.
   ``Simply refusing to give the Pentagon an automatic allowance
for inflation would, over the five-year period, represent a
10-percent reduction in planned spending. This freeze is consistent
with keeping America strong,'' he said.
   He also listed other savings from changes in farm programs,
closing tax loopholes, including a limit on business entertainment
deductions, and taxes to ``discourage mergers and speculation.''
   He said some have recently estimated the cost of Jackson's
proposals for increased domestic spending at $50 billion to $100
billion a year. ``Some declaim that this is unimaginably large. It
is not,'' he said.
</TEXT>
