<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FriendsHospital Bjt   04-06 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Friends Hospital, Bjt,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friends Hospital Celebrates 175 Years As Facility for Mentally Ill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Quakers who founded Friends Hospital 175
years ago chose a site on the outskirts of Philadelphia so the
mentally ill could live and work in freedom from prying eyes and
barred windows.
   That was part of the philosophy the Quakers, led by Thomas
Scattergood, believed in when they opened the ``Asylum for Persons
Deprived of the Use of their Reason.'' The institution is observing
its anniversary this week.
   The ``moral treatment'' of the mentally ill was considered
revolutionary at a time when the insane were put in chains in
basements or on display for public amusement.
   ``Today, about every institution espouses `moral treatment',''
said Judith Kelius, the hospital's coordinator of community
relations. ``It was something that was accepted much more widely
after Friends opened.''
   The hospital was the first institution in the United States
exclusively for the mentally ill which was not under government
auspices.
   Believing that ``there's that of God in every person,'' the
Quakers' treatment included giving each patients as much
responsibility as possiblee and and giving each an occupation to
increase self-esteem.
   ``Just because you're sick doesn't mean you're useless,'' said
James Delaplane, today's director of the facility.
   The second non-Quaker director of the 11 who have served the
hospital, Delaplane said 70 percent of the Board of Managers and
Corporation members are Quakers, according to bylaws.
   ``It was set up to be Society of Friends dominated to assure the
philosophy and principles were adhered to,'' he explained.
   Scattergood founded the hospital after visiting the Retreat at
York, England, a hospital for the mentally ill founded by Quaker
William Tuke.
   ``Thomas Scattergood quite likely was a depressant himself,''
Delaplane said, noting descriptions of him as a ``melancholiac
person.''
   The original building, built in 1817 and used as administrative
offices now, gave each patient a room of his own with a window. Ms.
Kelius said planners for the building included a committee on light
and air.
   That tradition continues. Each patient has his or her own room,
though the bathroom is shared with one other patient.
   In 175 years, the hospital has added several buildings. The
Greystone House, once the director's residence, houses 13 patients
with long-term psychiatric illness in a program to teach daily
living skills.
   At the turn of the century, the Hygeia Building was constructed
for hydrotherapy, a treatment similar to a whirlpool with the
person wrapped in a towel-like material, according to Delaplane.
   Treatments that once included purging, bloodletting and spinning
a patient while seated in a chair were used at Friends Hospital,
but have been discarded.
   ``The medical approach ... changes with the vogue in medicine,''
Delaplane said. ``The moral treatment has not changed.''
   Patients have two hours daily of activity therapy which may
include occupational or recreational therapy, creative arts and
horticulture.
   The first year, Friends Hospital had 19 patients. In 1982, the
hospital expanded to 192 beds. Now, a day program with 24 people
allows patients to undergo the same treatment as regular patients,
but leave the hospital at night.
   At first, the Quakers only wanted to admit patients of their
faith and people who had not been ill for an extended period of
time. After finding that there were not enough patients to fill
beds, they opened up the facility to all faiths and long-term
illnesses.
   The 100-acre site of Friends Hospital in north Philadelphia is
no longer rural, but the hospital is still surrounded by open
areas, trees and gardens.
   ``With the development of the surrounding area, we've always had
a buffer,'' Delaplane explained. ``The fact of the open space has
been a community asset.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
