<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reform     04-06 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reform,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Prints Criticism of Itself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper that published a pro-Stalin letter and
subsequently came under fire appeared Wednesday to be atoning for
its sin by reprinting a Pravda article that criticized its action.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya, the official daily of the Russian
republic's party and government, published the unusual
self-criticism on its entire second page. The newspaper did not
make any independent comment on the criticism originally published
Tuesday in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya also received a scolding from other Soviet
journalists.
   Grigory Y. Baklanov, editor in chief of the monthly literary
journal Znamya, accused the editors of Sovietskaya Rossiya of
lagging behind the times in publishing the letter advocating
Stalinism on March 13. Appearing at a news conference on
disarmament, Baklanov pointed to a clock that was two hours slow.
   ``We've got a clock in front of us. It shows, I don't know why,
half past nine. Probably there's something wrong with that clock
and that clock was used apparently in the article of Sovietskaya
Rossiya.''
   Baklanov praised Pravda for setting the record straight.
   ``Its moral position is flawless. Its philosophical position is
deep and serious. It reflects revolutionary thinking,'' he said.
   Pravda, in an editorial, sharply condemned those advocating the
repressive ways of Stalin that led to the deaths or exile of ``many
thousands'' of people and the ``administrative-command methods'' of
economic management that discouraged local initiative.
   The daily said the letter in Sovietskaya Rossiya, written by a
Leningrad teacher, was ``an attempt, little by little, to revise
party decisions.'' It said Sovietskaya Rossiya's publication of the
letter worked against Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's programs
of ``perestroika,'' or restructuring of society.
   Gorbachev acknowledged perestroika and his policy of
``glasnost'' _ more openness _ have generated controversy.
   ``Some are panicking. There are people who think everything is
collapsing. Just as in the beginning of this century `matter
vanished' in the perceptions of some people as a result of new
discoveries in physics, now it seems to some that socialism is
vanishing,'' Gorbachev told West German Socialist leader Willy
Brandt on Tuesday, according to the Tass news agency.
   Moscow News, a weekly that has been in the forefront of
glasnost, also joined the chorus of condemnation of Sovietskaya
Rossiya. It said opponents of perestroika ``were not bothered by
the fate of the country, the fate of socialism in the years of
repression or stagnation, which brought the country to the
threshold of a moral, ideological and economic crisis.''
   The comments appeared in this week's edition of the newspaper,
put out by the Union of Soviet Societies of Friendship and Cultural
Relations with Foreign Countries and Novosti Press Agency.
   In addition to a brief editorial, Moscow News also published a
letter from a Muscovite condemning the approach of ``firmness''
advocated in the Sovietskaya Rossiya letter. It also reported that
anonymous typewritten leaflets have been found in mailboxes warning
that perestroika will lead to ``economic catastrophe and social
shock _ and then to enslavement of the country by imperialistic
governments.''
</TEXT>
