<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ScottishSiren Bjt   04-06 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scottish Siren, Bjt,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor Meets Woman behind Bank Machine's Enthralling Voice</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM STRACENER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 61-year-old college professor smitten by
the Scottish burr of a bank teller machine's recorded voice met the
woman behind the accent Wednesday _ with his wife of 25 years
watching closely.
   ``I guess the first thing I should say is, `Your transaction is
processing,''' said British radio talk-show host Sally Masterson as
she met Dick Ferry and his wife, Carol, after a trans-Atlantic
flight arranged by the Decatur newspaper.
   That's the phrase that inspired Ferry, an education professor,
to write a Feb. 4 newspaper column about his ``infatuation with the
talking teller.''
   The item intrigued the Decatur Herald & Review's editors, who
tracked down Ms. Masterson and arranged for her trip after deciding
that Ferry ``should get to meet his infatuation.''
   ``This is just great,'' said Ferry, decked out in a black suit
and red tie for their meeting at a private club.
   ``She is very sweet, she is very charming,'' he said later.
``She is a person I'd very much like to have for a friend.''
   Apparently, the feeling was mutual.
   ``I think he's smashing,'' said Ms. Masterson, 29. ``He's what I
call wacky, because he's got that wacky sense of humor.''
   Mrs. Ferry, who waited arm-in-arm with her husband for Ms.
Masterson's arrival, said interest in the meeting on both sides of
the ocean ``was really overwhelming.''
   The Herald & Review reported that the story made a splash in the
British press, where it was called a ``romantic rendezvous''
triggered by a Scottish accent that is ``driving an American
teacher wild.''
   ``We take it as a joke,'' Mrs. Ferry said. ``We're having fun
with it.''
   Ms. Masterson, who is single, made the teller-machine recording
three years ago in Dundee, Scotland, for NCR Corp. of Dayton, Ohio.
Dundee is the design and manufacturing center for NCR's automatic
teller products worldwide.
   The recording was provided as a demonstration tape to banks that
bought the machines, said Bob Farkas, an NCR spokesman.
   In his column, Ferry described Ms. Masterson's voice as a
``seductive, sophisticated high-English way of speaking.''
   ``I think I'm in love with a woman I've never seen,'' he wrote.
``My infatuation is with the talking teller at the Money Network
station at First National Bank downtown.''
   Mrs. Ferry said she first heard the voice last weekend.
   ``I made Dick withdraw some money so I could hear the voice,''
said Mrs. Ferry, 50. ``I liked it.''
   Before Wednesday's meeting, Mrs. Ferry called the episode ``a
little unreal,'' asking, ``How would anyone feel if a young sexy
person wants to meet your husband?''
   But Ms. Masterson seemed to have won her over as well.
   ``I thought she was charming,'' Mrs. Ferry said. ``I've
thoroughly enjoyed this.''
   Ms. Masterson's schedule for Wednesday included a taste of
small-town America in Taylorville, a city of 10,000 near Decatur,
as well as dinner at a country club and a nighttime tour of Decatur.
   She was also to attend a baseball game in St. Louis and make
public appearances at several banks in central Illinois before
returning to Britain on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
