<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Pardons     04-06 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Pardons,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Remark on Pardons Called Merely ``Throwaway Comment''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan was giving merely
a ``throwaway comment'' when he made a remark interpreted by some
congressmen as a sign he might pardon former aides Oliver North and
John Poindexter, the White House said Wednesday.
   ``I don't think it's safe to make any conclusions about the
president's attitude about pardons,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater told reporters as Reagan vacationed at his mountaintop
ranch.
   Fitzwater confirmed that the president, at a closed meeting with
Republican members of the House on March 22, had been urged by Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to pardon North and Poindexter, who have been
indicted on felony charges in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Hyde suggested Reagan sign pardons in the final days of his term
next January, possibly in a ceremony at the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial in Washington.
   Hyde's comments were greeted by applause from other GOP
congressmen. Reagan said, ``I like the sound of those words,''
according to one unidentified congressman quoted by The Washington
Post. Another lawmaker recalled the president as saying, ``I like
hearing what you said.''
   Some lawmakers have taken Reagan's comment as a hint that he
will pardon the two former national security aides, but Fitzwater
played down the significance of the remarks.
   He said Reagan ``told them he was not discussing pardons,
period, and then he had some throwaway line which was similar'' to
the remark quoted by the congressmen.
   ``I gave them no significance at the time. I don't give them any
significance now. Certainly you've heard the president say much
stronger things than that in terms of his feelings about North and
Poindexter,'' the spokesman said.
   He added, ``I don't believe you should make any assumptions or
conclusions on the basis of that throwaway comment.''
   Emphasizing his point, Fitzwater said, ``It's been three weeks
(since Reagan's comment). There couldn't have been too much _ you'd
have had 40 congressmen running out of the room, grabbing the
cameras like you can't believe.''
   Fitzwater said, ``I have raised the issue (of pardons) with the
president four or five times myself and I've heard it raised by
others, and every time the president says the same thing: `I'm not
discussing pardons.'''
   However, Reagan has made several comments that have fueled
speculation about pardons. Answering a question from a student last
month, he expressed the conviction that North and Poindexter ``are
going to be found innocent, because I don't think they were guilty
of any lawbreaking or any crime.''
   Reagan said, ``I still think Ollie is a hero.'' Days later, he
qualified his remark about heroism, saying he was referring to
combat honors North had won in Vietnam.
   White House chief of staff Howard Baker has said the president
``is committed to seeing that the legal system operates. And I do
not anticipate that he'll address the pardon issue until it does.''
   Fitzwater declined to interpret what Baker meant about seeing
the legal system operate. ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I've not
heard the president say that.''
   North and Poindexter, along with arms dealers Richard V. Secord
and Albert A. Hakim, have pleaded innocent to federal criminal
charges in the sale of arms to Iran and the diversion of money to
Contra rebels fighting the leftist government of Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
