<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0702 04-06 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz To Hold Talks With East German, Bulgarian Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with Bulgarian talks</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who is
cautiously expanding contacts with some of Moscow's staunchest
allies, will hold talks with the highest-ranking East German and
communist Bulgarian to visit Washington, officials said Wednesday.
   Hermann Axen, a member of the ruling East German politburo, will
meet Shultz on May 3 during a three-day visit to Washington. The
U.S. and East German sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the meeting was arranged after Axen was invited to give a
lecture at the Johns Hopkins University Institute for Contemporary
German Studies on May 4.
   Although Axen holds no office in the East German government, he
is the top international affairs officer of the communist Socialist
Unity Party, which controls government policy.
   Andrey K. Lukanov, Bulgarian minister for foreign economic
development, will meet Shultz during an April 25-26 visit to
Washington. Lukanov, a former deputy premier whose post was created
in a recent government reorganization, will be the first Bulgarian
cabinet minister to visit Washington since World War II.
   Since 1984, the State Department has gingerly increased its
overtures to Soviet bloc countries, not with great hopes of wooing
them from Moscow's domination but to chip away wherever possible at
hard-line human rights and economic policies.
   In visits over the past two years, Deputy Secretary of State
John C. Whitehead has told leaders in East Germany, Czechoslovakia,
Poland, Bulgaria, Romania and Hungary that U.S. eagerness to expand
commercial ties will depend on their willingness to improve human
rights conditions.
   The U.S. source said that during Axen's talks, State Department
officials will renew pleas for better human rights performance,
notably in the realm of religion. In what the official described as
a ``mixed bag'' of actions, East Germany last year allowed two
massive religious assemblies, and the East German Jewish community
was allowed to install its first rabbi since 1967.
   In recent weeks, however, there has been a crackdown on
environmental groups affiliated with churches, the official said.
   Axen and Shultz also will discuss the two countries' effort to
settle financial claims by Americans whose property on East German
territory was taken during and after World War II. The claims total
more than $70 million.
   A U.S. effort to get other countries to do more to stop
terrorism and the flow of drugs is another likely topic, the
official said.
   An East German diplomat said ``the main intention of these talks
will be to promote the relationship between both countries and
contribute to a further buildup of the relationship.''
   The U.S. and East German officials said they doubted there would
be serious talk about a visit to the United States by East German
leader Erich Honecker, as was reported in a West German magazine.
Honecker is known to be interested in such a visit ``but it isn't
ripe for discussion,'' the U.S. official said.
   In talks with the Bulgarian official, the State Department is
expected to reassert requests for better human rights policies,
notably toward Bulgaria's sizable Turkish and Islamic minority.
   Bulgaria wants to expand trade with the United States beyond the
current $130 million level. Before he leaves the United States on
May 2, Lukanov is expected to call for improved commercial ties
during talks at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Washington and in
meetings in Los Angeles, San Francisco, Chicago and New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
