<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-06 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk about forgetful!
   Florentino Santiago lost his winning $1.25 million lottery
ticket twice, then mislaid the keys to his safety deposit box,
where he had thought his treasure was safe.
   With his initial winning payment of $47,523 finally in hand, his
family said Tuesday that some of the money would go toward
repairing damage done to the house of the 77-year-old man when
relatives ransacked it searching for the misplaced ticket.
   The retired shoe-store owner lost the ticket the first time soon
after learning Jan. 6 that he had won the prize.
   The family tore apart his home for four days and finally found
the ticket in a pillow.
   The place was pillaged again for a week when he forgot his
second hiding place until _ a moment that some interpreted as
divine intervention _ the ticket was found in Santiago's Bible.
   Santiago put it into the safety deposit box. He was on the verge
of shelling out $75 for a duplicate set of keys when he found the
originals in a safe place at the back of his closet.
   Finally Santiago's wife, Carmen, sewed a small cloth pouch for
the ticket and he bound it to his arm using adhesive tape _ enough
to make it look like a cast. He kept it there until he collected
his prize March 31.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROSWELL, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When officer W.E. Bass gives out speeding
tickets, he sends drivers on their way with, ``Have a nice day.''
   Some apparentlydo, and they send Bass fan mail in return.
   ``I want to treat people the way I would want to be treated in
the same circumstance,'' said Bass, who writes about 125 tickets a
month and has received about 10 fan letters this year from
motorists caught speeding on the congested streets of this Atlanta
suburb.
   ``He pulled me over and was as nice as he could be. Most
policemen today seem to be on a power trip or ego trip,'' said
Acworth resident Sharon Guillebeau, who got a ticket for traveling
47 mph in a 30 mph zone. ``He was so different from the rest that I
wanted to commend him on his good attitude.''
   Not all motorists are fans, however.
   One driver kicked out his own taillights and dented his car
while Bass was writing the ticket. ``I almost had to arrest him,''
Bass said.
</TEXT>
