<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviet-Afghan-Future     04-06 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan-Future,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fate of Afghan Leaders Uncertain After Troop Withdrawal, Soviet
Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet expert on Afghanistan said
Wednesday that the pro-Kremlin regime in Kabul may survive the
withdrawal of the Red Army but that the lives of its leaders ``are
in the hands of the almighty.''
   In a remarkably pessimistic public assessment for a Soviet, Yuri
Gankovsky said the Kabul regime controls about 30 percent of
Afghanistan, including most administrative centers, that tribal
leaders control about 30 percent, and that the Islamic guerrillas
known as mujahedeen control just over 30 percent.
   The complicated balance of power hampers predictions of what
will happen when and if the Red Army pulls out, said Gankovsky.
   Although some guerrillas have close ties with the fundamentalist
Moslem government in Iran, Gankovsky said, ``my impression is that
an Islamic republic in Afghanistan is impossible'' because tribal
leaders are so strong.
   Many U.S. analysts believe that the pro-Kremlin government will
collapse immediately after a Soviet pullout, and that regime
officials who do not leave will be targets of revenge from the
families of the estimated 1 million Afghans who were killed or the
5 million Afghans driven into exile during the war.
   ``Individual acts of revenge may take place,'' Gankovsky said.
``But I hope that a blood bath will not take place.''
   ``It is impossible to predict the future of Najib,'' the leader
of the Kabul regime, he said. ``But we have the impression that the
regime of the People's Democratic Party may survive.'' Najib, also
known as Najibullah, uses a single name.
   As for for the fate of Najib and other leaders, Gankovsky said,
``their life is in the hands of the almighty.''
   Gankovsky, in a lecture at the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced
International Studies, declined to speculate how many members of
the current government might flee.
   But he said that ``some middle-sized leaders in Kabul want to
emigrate to the Soviet Union and other countries. That is their
private business.''
   Gankovsky, who retired last fall as head of the Middle and Near
East Section of the Oriental Institutes Section of the Soviet
Academy of Sciences, said he was unable to comment directly on
stalled U.N. negotiations designed to end the war.
   The Soviets say that U.S. covert aid to the guerrillas should
end within 60 days after an agreement is signed. But Pakistan,
representing the interests of the United States and the guerrillas,
insists that Kremlin aid to Kabul stop at the same time.
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev flew to the Soviet Central
Asian city of Tashkent on Wednesday to meet with Najib for talks
thought to center on plans for a withdrawal of Soviet troops even
if the U.N. talks collapse.
   Under the Soviet system, experts such as Gankovsky not only
write scholarly works but are asked to prepare classified reports
for the key decision-making body on foreign relations, the
International Department of the Central Committee secretariat.
   Gankovsky declined to say what advice he has the Kremlin about
Afghanistan, explaining that ``a lecture is not a confessional.''
   He denied that the Soviet Union plans to annex any part of
Afghanistan.
   And he avoided direct comment on speculation that Soviet
withdrawal from Afghanistan signalled an end to the so-called
``Brezhnev Doctrine,'' invoked in the past to justify military
intervention to prop up communist regimes in such nations such as
Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
   Instead, Gankovsky clamed that Afghanistan never had a communist
government.
   Although Najib and his colleagues represent a leftist faction
within the ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, said
Gankovsky, ``there are not any communists'' among them.
   ``The biggest part of them are Afghan nationalists. They are not
communists, they are not socialists,'' he said, drawing a fine line
which was challenged vocally by some Afghan emigres in the audience.
   The chances that a pro-Kremlin regime would prevail in
Afghanistan are bolstered by the high rate of party membership, 75
percent, among military and police officials, and by the large
number of Afghans, 400,000, employed by the state, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
