<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Meyerhoff     04-06 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Meyerhoff,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Matriarch of Baltimore Philanthopist Family Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lyn cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyn P. Meyerhoff, matriarch of one of
Baltimore's most generous philanthropic families, died Wednesday of
cancer at Johns Hopkins Hospital. She was 60.
   During her long fight against cancer, she launched the Jeane
Kirkpatrick Institute at Tel Aviv University, hoping to advance
American-style democracy by bringing U.S. government officials to
Israel to share their ideas.
   In 1983, President Reagan chose her as one of the public members
of the U.S. delegation to the U.N. General Assembly.
   In 1986 she helped establish the Harvey M. and Lyn P. Meyerhoff
Digestive Disease-Inflammatory Bowel Disease Center at the Johns
Hopkins Hospital.
   Her husband, Harvey M. Meyerhoff, is a real estate developer and
investor.
   Mrs. Meyerhoff, whose parents were Democrats, became active in
national Republican Party politics during Richard Nixon's campaign
of 1960. She remained a steadfast supporter of Nixon until his
resignation in 1974.
   Once an admirer of former Vice President Spiro T. Agnew, she was
co-chair of Citizens for Nixon-Agnew in Maryland and later said he
was her biggest disappointment in politics. She was called to
testify before a 1973 Anne Arundel County grand jury investigating
contributions to Agnew, a former governor of Maryland.
   Mrs. Meyerhoff was born Lenore P. Pancoe, in Winnetka, Ill., on
Aug. 5, 1927. She met her husband while both were students at the
University of Wisconsin.
   Besides her mother and husband, survivors include three
daughters, a son, two brothers, a sister and eight grandchildren.
</TEXT>
