<HEAD>Toddler Falls Through Hole In Car Floorboard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead and adds one graf to UPDATE with police saying car
may have been stopped.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-month-old boy escaped serious
injury when he fell through a hole in the floor of a car, which
then drove on without him, police said.
   The child apparently reached down to get a potato chip and
slipped through a hole in the back seat floor of the 1977
Chevrolet, police said after the incident Tuesday.
   The car's driver and the boy's 16-year-old mother, a passenger
in the car, apparently didn't realize the child was missing until
the car reached a stoplight, said Police Officer Louis Redpath.
   The driver, Debra Alwerdt, 26, of Springfield, was ticketed for
having an unsafe vehicle, police said.
   The hole, which had been covered by a mat, ``is big enough for a
small adult to go through,'' he said. ``We're just lucky the wheels
didn't get him.''
   Authorities believe the car may have been stopped in traffic
when the child fell, police spokesman Neil Williamson said
Wednesday.
