<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cowboy'sCasino     04-06 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cowboy's Casino,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Rustler Gets Casino Recommendation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted rustler and unrepentant
cowboy who has had frequent run-ins with the government was
recommended Wednesday for a gaming license at a tiny rural casino.
   Jimmy Williams, 57, whose faded jeans are held up by rope
suspenders, won an endorsement from the state Gaming Control Board
for a license to run two slot machines and a blackjack game at the
Golden Club in the isolated central Nevada town of Austin.
   Williams, who inherited a one-sixth interest in the club from
his mother, faces a final review before the board's parent Gaming
Commission on April 21.
   Control Board Chairman Mike Rumbolz said he had been concerned
because Williams' various run-ins with authorities hadn't been
fully disclosed. However, he blamed that on Williams' lawyer.
   Williams, wearing shiny black street shoes, a cowboy hat,
western shirt and jeans, said he forgot many of the incidents.
Sometimes, he said, he pleaded guilty just so he could get back to
the hills.
   ``There used to be no law out there,'' Williams said, explaining
conflicts with brand inspectors, the Bureau of Land Management and
other regulatory agencies.
   He said he spent 10 months in prison in 1962 for rustling. He
said he had hauled another rancher's sheep out of an area where
they were interfering with a camp he was running, and simply
released them elsewhere.
   In another case, Williams said he traded some pigs for a vehicle
jack, battery and other equipment that turned out to be stolen BLM
property.
   Williams also salvaged some discarded well pipe on BLM land,
planning to build corrals, and wound up with a grand larceny charge
which also was dismissed.
</TEXT>
