<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DemocraticOptimism 1stLd-Writethru a0726 04-06 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Optimism, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Victory Stirs Hopes of Avoiding Convention Fight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 2nd graf, The Massachusetts, and 1
new graf after 10th graf pvs, ``The super, to update with comment
from Michigan Democratic chairman</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' impressive Wisconsin victory
stirred cautious optimism among Democrats on Wednesday that the
race for their party's presidential nomination would end without a
bloodbath at the national convention in July.
   The Massachusetts governor had moved on to the next major
battleground, New York, even as Wisconsin voters were giving him a
20-point win over his chief rival, Jesse Jackson. Dukakis was
banking on another victory in the April 19 New York primary to
widen his lead in the race.
   ``Dukakis has rallied from his defeat in the Michigan caucuses
to win three straight states (Connecticut, Colorado and
Wisconsin),'' said Richard Wiener, the Michigan Democratic Party
chairman. ``It certainly is a good sign for his campaign, he has
momentum as he goes into New York.''
   Jackson's landslide victory in Michigan, following a strong
showing in Illinois, had given the civil rights activist a claim to
front-runner status in the race.
   ``The nominee will be determined in New York and Pennsylvania,''
said Rachelle Horowitz, political director of the American
Federation of Teachers and a member of the Democratic National
Committee. ``I think we have a two-person race and we have a
front-runner. The likelihood is we'll have a nominee and not a
brokered convention.''
   Former national party chairman John C. White, who has been
advising Jackson, said the Wisconsin result ``gives Dukakis a good
bump for New York. It got his chin above water.''
   A long list of Democrats have claimed momentum in the
presidential nomination race, none of them yet able to sustain it.
People like Gary Hart, Richard Gephardt and Paul Simon had moments
in the sun. Even Albert Gore Jr. and Bruce Babbitt. And this wasn't
the first time Dukakis could say he was on a roll.
   The Wisconsin vote ``gives a little boost to Dukakis,'' said
Joseph Crangle, Erie County, N.Y. Democratic chairman, and one of
the party's super delegates. ``But you've got to put a qualifying
clause there that you've got to have a pattern, you've got to go
two or three states in a row in order to say that you're a
front-runner.''
   Party chairman Paul G. Kirk Jr. predicted the Democrats would
choose their nominee on the first ballot of the Atlanta convention
and he vowed to oppose any effort to organize a stop-Jackson
movement.
   ``There's not going to be any organized cabal of party leaders
trying to hobble one candidate as opposed to another,'' said Kirk.
   A total of 2,082 delegates is needed for a convention majority.
To reach that number, either Dukakis or Jackson would need to win
more than 1,300 of the 1,600-plus committed delegates yet to be
chosen or draw strong support from the super delegates, the party
and elected officials whose 645 votes could be decisive.
   ``The super delegates are going to stay frozen for a while,''
predicted White.
   Wiener said the super delegates were ``looking for a candidate
who can ratle off a big string of wins.'' He said most of those
delegates accept the view that ``if there is a clear leader after
California and New Jersey (the last two big states to hold
primaries), that super delegates ought to play a leading role in
propelling that person over the top. At three in a row, Gov.
Dukakis has gotten a very good start on that.''
   An endorsement from New York Gov. Mario Cuomo would brighten
Dukakis' prospects in the state, but there was no sign the governor
was ready to tilt to his Massachusetts colleague.
   ``I'd like to have it,'' Dukakis said. ``He knows that. But it's
his decision to make, and I'll respect whatever decision he makes.
It's up to him.
   ``We're good friends and colleagues. We talk often. ... But he's
under no legal or moral obligation to endorse anybody.''
   Crangle said he had seen no indication that Cuomo was ready to
endorse.
   The Erie official and others cited the continued presence of
Gore in the race as another potential hazard for Dukakis.
   Crangle pointed out that in 1976, another Southerner, Jimmy
Carter, surprised people by getting a lot of support in the
northern and western portions of New York state. ``The question
mark, I think, is does Gore take anything away from Dukakis,'' said
Crangle.
   ``I don't know what the hell Gore is in there for,'' said
Kenneth Melley, political director of the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teachers union. Still, he added,
in light of Wisconsin, ``I think a lot of Democrats are breathing
sighs of relief.''
</TEXT>
