<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ElectionsRdp     04-06 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elections Rdp,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tulsa Voters Oust Mayor, Milwaukee Elects First New Mayor In 28
Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in Tulsa, Okla., have unseated their incumbent mayor,
Milwaukee voters have elected their first new mayor in 28 years and
the mayor of Columbia, Mo., survived a recall election provoked by
racial tension.
   Elsewhere, a campaign supported by presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson succeeded in defeating a Cleveland charter amendment that
was viewed as an attack on the city's highest elected black.
   Tulsa Mayor-elect Rodger Randle said Wednesday he will spend the
first 100 days in office balancing next year's city budget,
preparing a charter change proposal and making a blueprint for
economic development for his once oil-rich city. The budget is
expected to fall $6 million short next year.
   Randle said he also intends to propose a change in the city's
charter, which has been challenged by the NAACP as being unfair to
blacks. The National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People filed suit claiming the city's commission form of government
dilutes black voting strength.
   Randle, 44, soundly defeated Republican Dick Crawford, 54, in
Tuesday's election, claiming 55.3 percent or 45,517 votes to
Crawford's 34.2 percent or 28,142 votes.
   Crawford, elected in 1986, said he looks forward to spending
more time with his family, getting back into banking and refusing
to talk to reporters who once called at all hours.
   In Milwaukee, state Sen. John Norquist swept to victory over
former acting Gov. Martin Schreiber in the race to succeed Mayor
Henry Maier, who is retiring at age 70 after holding the office
since 1960.
   Complete, unofficial returns from the non-partisan election had
Norquist with 112,902 votes, or 54 percent, and Schreiber with
93,738 votes, or 45 percent.
   Norquist, 38, said the margin reflected ``a mandate for
change,'' a signal that people ``want the racial and economic
divisions to be bridged.''
   Columbia Mayor Rodney Smith, 59, a self-employed tree surgeon
elected as a write-in candidate in 1986, easily survived a recall
election prompted by remarks he made last October at a meeting with
blacks angry over the forced resignation of the black police chief.
   The white mayor told a predominantly black crowd that if they
didn't like Columbia they ought to leave.
   Final returns showed 9,041 voters, or 78 percent, wanted Smith
to remain in office while 2,493 voters, or 22 percent, favored
ouster.
   ``I had hopes it would be this way because I don't feel like
I've done anything that should've upset the community. I'm sorry
that it happened,'' Smith said Tuesday night.
   Supporters of a defeated Cleveland referendum, on whether the
city charter should be amended to limit the city council president
to two one-year terms, said they won't give up.
   Voters soundly defeated the charter amendment by a vote of
46,854 to 25,458 in a special election Tuesday. The measure was
aimed at ousting City Council President George Forbes, who has
headed the 21-member Council for the last 15 years.
   ``We'll come up with something again. Or we'll keep protesting
until some kind of change comes through,'' said Ann Chudner, a
leader of the Coalition for Ordinance Reforming Council's
Efficiency, which charged that Forbes abused his power.
   Jesse Jackson's picture was used on literature against the
amendment and a radio advertisement featured Jackson urging voters
to defeat it.
   Unofficial returns showed 46,854 votes against the measure, or
65 percent, to 25,458 in favor, or 35 percent.
   Kenosha, Wis., a city rocked by Chrysler Corp.'s announced
closing of an auto plant, also turned back an incumbent. With 33 of
34 precincts reporting, unofficial returns showed Alderman Pat
Moran with 12,329 votes to 10,130 for Mayor Eugene Dorff.
</TEXT>
