<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sunspots     04-06 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunspots,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Sunspot Theory Bolstered By Early Detection Of Solar Jet
Streams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A theory that upsets traditional notions
about 11-year sunspot cycles has been bolstered by the earliest,
most detailed observation ever made of solar jet streams that will
produce sunspots by 1997, scientists say.
   Astronomer Roger Ulrich and his colleagues at the University of
California, Los Angeles, were able to see the jet streams ``at
higher latitudes (on the sun) and earlier than we were ever able to
before,'' said astrophysicist Herschel Snodgrass of Lewis and Clark
College in Portland, Ore.
   ``We're seeing the very earliest stage of the next sunspot
cycle, not the one that is producing sunspots now, but that one
that will produce them when this cycle is over,'' said Ulrich, who
presented his findings Wednesday during a solar physics meeting in
Tucson, Ariz.
   Understanding the sunspot cycle is important because the spots
and related explosions called solar flares disrupt radar, radio and
other communications on Earth and, in extreme cases, are believed
to contribute to ice ages and major droughts, Snodgrass said
Tuesday by telephone from Portland.
   Ulrich said solar flares make Earth's outer atmosphere expand,
so learning more about sunspots is important in deciding when to
launch satellites, since atmospheric expansion produces
orbit-altering drag on spacecraft.
   Snodgrass and Air Force astrophysicist Richard Altrock said
Ulrich's observation of the jet streams, which are east-west
currents of gas parallel to the sun's equator, supports a theory
they developed independently with California Institute of
Technology astronomer Peter Wilson.
   Last year, they proposed that the 11-year sunspot cycle _ during
which the number of sunspots reaches a maximum, then a minimum and
then another maximum _ is merely part of a previously unknown 18-to
22-year cycle that produces visible sunspots only during its last
11 years.
   The theory says that during the earliest stages of this longer
cycle, jet stream-like gas currents appear near the sun's poles
like smoke rings, which then grow and roll down the sun toward the
equator, Altrock said by telephone from Sunspot, N.M.
   Only when the jet streams reach a solar latitude of 30 or 35
degrees do they produce sunspots, Ulrich said.
   He said he detected the jet streams at a latitude of 70 degrees
on the sun.
   ``These jet streams eventually will migrate into the region
where sunspots form,'' probably about 1997, Ulrich said.
   The last sunspot cycle reached its minimum in September 1986, so
the next maximum is expected about 1991 and the next minimum in
1997 or 1998, Snodgrass said.
   The current batch of sunspots ``is rising much faster than any
other we've seen,'' he added. ``There is evidence to suggest it's
going to be unusually strong and perhaps the maximum will be
reached earlier than usual, in 1989 or 1990,'' with the minimum
following in 1995 or 1996.
   Sunspots are relatively cool spots, 1,200 to 60,000 miles
across, that each appear for three to seven weeks where the solar
magnetic field is about 1,000 times stronger than in other
locations. Up to 30 appear at one time.
   Ulrich and his colleagues were able to see the solar jet streams
closer to the sun's poles in more detail than ever before by
measuring the speed of gases on the sun's surface 20 times daily
using the 150-foot-tall solar observatory and 75-foot-deep
spectrograph on Mount Wilson, in the San Gabriel Mountains
northeast of Los Angeles.
   Sunlight passes through a lens near the top of the observatory
tower. The lens focuses an image of the sun on a hole that lets the
light enter the spectrograph.
   The spectrograph breaks the sunlight into a rainbow of component
colors. That allows the scientists to measure the speed of solar
gases and detect jet streams.
   ``It's the same way a radar gun on the highway measures the
velocity of a car,'' Ulrich said.
   The jet streams may help scientists understand why the number of
sunspots varies, Ulrich said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
