<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-06 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Windy City Lives Up To its Nickname, Heavy Rain In Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong, gusty wind shook the Chicago area Wednesday,
thunderstorms rumbled from the Great Lakes into parts of the South
and locally heavy rain fell on the parched Northwest.
   A strong storm system over the Indiana-Ohio border pulled
northwesterly wind through downtown Chicago at 35 to 48 mph,
gusting above 60 mph at times and reaching a peak gust of 75 mph.
   The wind pushed up waves up to 10 feet high on the Lake Michigan
shores of Illinois and Indiana.
   The wind also blew across much of Illinois and western Indiana,
with gusts to 61 mph at Lafayette, Ind.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered from the Great
Lakes through the Ohio Valley into the southern Atlantic states and
the Florida Panhandle. Showers were heavy at times across parts of
Lower Michigan, and Lansing had 1.3 inches of rain by midafternoon.
   Thunderstorms produced high wind that downed power lines around
West Campbellsville, Ky. Thunderstorms with strong, gusty wind were
reported in parts of the Carolinas during the afternoon.
   Showers were scattered across the Pacific Northwest into
northwestern Montana. Diablo Dam in the upper Skagit Valley in
northwestern Washington state reported 3.95 inches of rain in 24
hours. Quillayute, Wash., recorded 2.36 inches of rain in 24 hours.
   Record highs Wednesday were 67 at Binghamton, N.Y., and 81 at
Youngstown, Ohio.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Pellston and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.; Bloomington and
South Bend, Ind.; and Hyannis, Mass., to 101 at Palm Springs and
Thermal, Calif. The early-morning low for the day was 9 degrees at
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.
   For Thursday, widespread showers were forecast from the eastern
Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley through the central Appalachians
and mid-Atlantic states. Showers and a few thunderstorms were
forecast across Virginia and North Carolina. Scattered showers were
forecast from the Pacific Northwest through the northern Rockies,
with snow showers possible east of the Continental Divide across
Montana.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted from northern Washington into
northwestern Montana, and across the northern Great Lakes; in the
50s from the northern Pacific Coast into the northern Rockies, and
from the upper Mississippi Valley through the Ohio Valley and
central Appalachians into the mid-Atlantic region and New England;
in the 80s from the southern California valleys to the southern and
central high Plains into the southern Plains and Texas; around 90
across the desert Southwest; and in the 60s or 70s across most of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
