<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RaucousParty     04-06 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Raucous Party,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partygoers Wreck Couple's Home, Son May Be Afraid to Face Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Partying vandals made a shambles of
a suburban house left in the care of the owners' 20-year-old
mentally retarded son, who fled and apparently was afraid to come
home.
   The young man's mother, Corinne McConaghey, ``tells us he's
capable of functioning in society, so everybody's best guess is
just that he's frightened,'' Police Sgt. Doug Larsson said
Wednesday.
   The McConagheys returned home Monday after a week in Florida,
but did not file a missing persons report on their son, Michael,
until Tuesday.
   Telephone calls to the McConaghey home were not answered
Wednesday.
   ``I think my Michael is still around, but he's just deathly
afraid to come home. We want him to come home, and we're not
angry,'' Mrs. McConaghey said in an interview Tuesday with The
Daily Herald of Arlington Heights.
   Michael, who had been left in charge of the house in the past,
invited a few friends over for a party, Larsson said.
   Over the next few days, word of the open-house bash spread and
groups of 10 to 15 party-goers, some driving 20 miles from Chicago,
dropped by at all hours.
   ``We originally thought this was a marathon kind of party, where
people heard about this on a party-line (call) or the radio ... and
maybe 100 or so people descended on the house for a whole
weekend,'' said Larsson.
   ``But as we piece this together, it's something that got out of
hand. Kids apparently learned about it by word-of-mouth and just
kept showing up in clusters and leaving.''
   ``That is a very expensive neighborhood,'' he added. ``Somebody
would have called us earlier if there had been big, loud parties
going all the time.''
   When police were finally called by a neighbor Sunday, officers
found Michael home alone and the house in ruins.
   Police Cmdr. Richard Hammer said Michael appeared disoriented
said about 100 people had visited over a two-day period. He said he
passed out at one point and woke up to find the mess.
   Police say Michael apparently fled shortly after they
interviewed him.
   Virtually every room in the two-story house was wrecked, all the
upstairs doors were kicked in and there was a large hole in one
wall, police said.
   Total damage and theft costs _ including telephones, video
recorders and some computer equipment _ could exceed $25,000.
   The family's 1986 Buick was stolen but recovered later from a
nearby forest preserve, its radio missing.
   At least one person was arrested with items taken from the
McConaghey home, and Larsson said Wednesday police expect to make
additional arrests.
   Mrs. McConaghey said she hopes the people who wrecked her house
will understand someday what they did.
   ``I hope this is something they will never forget ... when they
are older and in their own houses.''
</TEXT>
