<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-PLO     04-06 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-PLO,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Declines to Present Arguments at World Court Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has declined to present
arguments before a world court hearing on the closure of the
Palestine Liberation Organization mission to the U.N., saying
international arbitration of the case is not ``appropriate.''
   In a letter to the International Court of Justice in The Hague,
U.S. ambassador to The Netherlands John S. Shad noted that the 1987
Anti-Terrorism Law ordering the closure of the PLO Observer Mission
is being appealed in a U.S. court.
   ``Since the matter is still pending in our courts, we do not
believe arbitration would be appropriate,'' Shad wrote. A copy of
the letter was made available to The Associated Press.
   ``The United States respectfully declines the court's invitation
to submit further views on this issue'' at a hearing scheduled for
April 11, he added.
   Shad noted that Attorney General Edwin Meese III had concluded
that the law, which was signed last December by President Reagan,
calls for the closure of the mission ``irrespective of any
international legal obligations that the United States may have
under the Headquarters Agreement.''
   The 1947 agreement regulates the presence of foreign missions to
the U.N. in New York. The PLO and the United Nations contend that
the agreement, which regulates the presence of foreign missions to
the U.N. in New York, supersedes American law.
   The World Court has been asked by the U.N. to decide whether the
United States must submit to arbitration of the dispute over the
PLO mission. The U.S.-U.N. treaty calls for arbitration of disputes
but the United States has refused to submit to arbitration in this
case.
   Several weeks ago the Justice Department filed suit in U.S.
District Court in New York after the PLO refused to close down its
office. The PLO is expected to respond by April 11 and the United
Nations is expected to file a friend of the court brief supporting
its position.
   The PLO will not present any arguments before the world court
either, said its lawyer, Ramsey Clark, a former U.S. attorney
general.
   The U.S. State Department ordered the PLO office in Washington
to shut down last year, contending the organization was a terrorist
group. Congress used a similar argument in ordering the closure of
the U.N. mission.
</TEXT>
