<HEAD>Iraq, Iran Trade Missiles; Iran Claims Two Jets Downed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with new death tolls, bombing
of football stadium; picks up 11th pvs: It said...; SUBS 16th graf
pvs, ``Iranian communiques...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT missile
target to Tehran, sted Baghdad.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired four missiles into Tehran
Wednesday and its warplanes bombed eight other Iranian cities. Iran
said 40 civilians were killed, including three children who died
when a hospital nursery was hit.
   Iran said it fired two missiles into ``military centers'' in
Baghdad in retaliation and shelled Iraqi border towns.
   The Iraqi News Agency reported only one Iranian missile
exploding in Baghdad, saying it hit a residential neighborhood,
killing several civilians.
   Iraq said two Iranian jets bombed a packed football stadium in
the town of Kalar in the northeastern Sulaymaniyah province,
killing five schoolchildren and wounding 35 others.
   ``We will take revenge, and the Iranian regime will have to pay
dearly for its shameful crimes,'' the official Iraqi News Agency
quoted a military spokesman as saying.
   The Iraqis also said their fighter-bombers hit a ``very large
maritime target,'' which usually means a supertanker, near Iran's
Lavan Island oil terminal in the central Persian Gulf during the
night.
   There was no immediate independent confirmation of the strike.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi charged that the Iraqis
were stepping up their missile and air strikes to disrupt elections
Friday for Iran's 270-seat Majlis, or Parliament.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted him as
saying, ``These raids will fail to prevent the elections. On the
contrary, it will make our people more determined to cast their
votes.''
   The Iran news agency said five short-range missiles were fired
into Iraq's southern port of Basra.
   It said its anti-aircraft missiles batteries shot down a
Soviet-built Iraqi MiG-23 jet and a Sukhoi Su-22 fighter-bomber
during two of the bombing raids. The MiG pilot was killed, it said,
but there was no immediate word on the Sukhoi pilot.
   Iraqi communiques said air force jets and helicopter gunships
flew more than 200 combat missions Wednesday and that only one
plane was lost.
   Iraq's missile barrage was seen as Baghdad's response to an
Iranian push into the northeastern mountains of Kurdistan.
   IRNA said Iranian air force fighters carried out six attacks on
Iraqi troop concentrations north of the Iranian bridgehead around
the strategic Lake Darbandikhan.
   It said Iranian artillery shelled the nearby provincial capital
of Sulaimaniyeh, including a power station, as fighting continued
in the region 75 miles east of Iraq's big Kirkuk oilfields.
   Iranian communiques said the Iraqi missiles hit residential
districts in Tehran, killing 16 civilians and wounding scores more.
   Three of the dead were children killed when a nursery in a
hospital was hit, the Iranians said. A hospital official told an
Associated Press correspondent that eight children were killed
there.
   IRNA said 21 other civilians were killed and dozens wounded in
Iraqi air raids on the western cities of Ilam, Dezful, Shustar and
four ther towns.
   Iran retaliated with artillery bombardments of Basra and other
Iraqi border cities throughout the day.
   Kamal Kharazzi, Iran's chief military spokesman, told a news
conference in Tehran: ``It isn't easy to intercept and track the
missiles.''
   He said: ``They move at very high speed. It's an exceptional
achievement that Iran has worked out any warning system at all.''
   Half of Tehran's 6 million population have fled the capital
since the ``war of the cities'' flared up Feb. 29. Both sides have
fired nearly 300 missiles into each other's cities, killing
hundreds on both sides.
   An Associated Press correspondent said lines of cars were seen
heading out of the city in the past two days. He said most people
were spending their nights in shelters, basements and underground
parking lots for safety.
</TEXT>
