<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RobesonJudgeship     04-06 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robeson Judgeship,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says `Minority' Judgeship Should Not Be Allowed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white prosecutor running unopposed for
a judgeship that was created as an opportunity for minority
candidates says he opposes a plan agreed to by legislators to give
the county a second new judge.
   ``I'm very disappointed that the people who entered into this
agreement didn't consult with me or my advisers on it,'' Robeson
County District Attorney Joe Freeman Britt said about the plan,
which emerged Monday after the death of Britt's Lumbee Indian
opponent left no minority candidates in the contest. ``Personally,
I felt it was an unnecessary move.''
   Britt contended the plan to give the county two Superior Court
judges does not follow state law and ``is unfair to taxpayers.'' In
North Carolina, smaller counties are lumped into districts that
share judges.
   The General Assembly created a judgeship last year specifically
for Robeson County, which has a population that is 37 percent
Indian and 26 percent black, to give minority candidates a better
chance to become judge.
   But Britt, 52, automatically became the Democratic nominee for
the judgeship when his opponent, Julian Pierce, was slain March 26
in what police described as a romantic dispute. There is no
Republican candidate.
   Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, the state's ranking Democrat, met with
legislators from Robeson County and minority leaders Monday to
develop the plan for a second judgeship.
   ``I don't really see how it can be justified,'' Britt told The
Fayetteville Observer on Tuesday. ``It's very unusual to have two
judges from an area the size of Robeson County.''
   ``Apparently a lot of people have been impressed by the claims
of support by Pierce supporters,'' Britt said. ``What's happened is
a very small group of people have run a very good bluff for some
politicians.''
   Franklin Freeman, director of the Administrative Office of the
Courts, said, the judgeship would cost the state $110,000 a year.
Since Superior Court judges in North Carolina can be assigned to
hear cases in any county, he said the extra judge's time would not
be wasted.
   ``There's no question we can fully utilize this new judgeship.
This will provide the extra judge power we believe is needed to
handle the extra case filings across the state.''
</TEXT>
