<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cranston Says Convention May Turn To Cuomo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats may turn to New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo as their presidential nominee if neither Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis nor Jesse Jackson ``starts to win consistently
and by strong margins'' in the remaining primaries, Sen. Alan
Cranston said Wednesday.
   The California Democrat said he is remaining neutral in the
primaries and will vote at the national convention for the
candidate who ``appears to be best for the party.''
   Cranston told reporters that if either Dukakis or Jackson
emerges only a few delegates ahead of the other, that won't be
enough to persuade him or other ``super delegates'' to give the
nomination to the leader.
   ``My definition of someone emerging strongly is someone starting
to win consistently and by strong margins, and winding up with a
very significant lead in delegates on the eve of the convention,''
Cranston said.
   ``But if ... nobody's demonstrated the capacity to win and take
charge, then quite possibly the convention will look to someone
else for the nomination,'' he said. ``That person might well be
Governor Cuomo.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Kean Wants Equal Rights Amendment, Urban Issues In GOP Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Thomas H. Kean says he wants the Equal
Rights Amendment and urban issues to be addressed at the Republican
National Convention in August.
   He told reporters Tuesday that he has long pressed for the ERA
to be a plank in the GOP platform and he will push the amendment at
the party's convention in New Orleans, as well as proposals to
boost aid to cities and improve the quality of education.
   At the same time, Kean played down the importance of party
platforms. ``What does make a difference is what the candidate
says, because that will be, in effect, the platform,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Ministers Say Attacks On Jackson May Cost Gore Black Votes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some black ministers in the Nashville
area say Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s criticism of Jesse
Jackson could cost him black votes at home, says the Rev. James
Thomas.
   Since Jackson's victory and Gore's poor finish in Michigan,
``Gore, in desperation, has stooped to attacking the man and not
the message, the individual and not the issues, the person and not
his platform,'' Thomas told reporters Tuesday.
   ``I think it's racial although I can't pinpoint it,'' Thomas
said.
   Thomas, pastor of the Jefferson Street Missionary Baptist
Church, said ministers in the Nashville region are ``well aware of
the Democrats' hidden agenda _ the `stop Jesse Jackson' movement.''
   Interpreting Gore's comments as racist or personal would be
extreme, Gore spokesman Mark Armour said, who added that Gore is
attempting to highlight his national government experience and
Jackson's lack of such experience.
   ``Neither Reverend Jackson nor (Massachusetts Gov.) Michael
Dukakis has had a single day's experience in national government,''
Armour said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jackson's Mother Seeks To Be Delegate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Jackson, Jesse Jackson's mother,
is vying for a delegate slot at the Democratic National Convention
in Atlanta, but neither she nor party officials expect her to get
any special treatment in her bid.
   Mrs. Jackson is among delegates to the state convention
competing to become national convention delegates from South
Carolina.
   ``It would be a kind gesture by South Carolina Democrats to
choose Mrs. Jackson as a national delegate,'' Chris Verenes,
executive director of the state party, said Tuesday.
   But, he said, ``the delegate-selection process is very
complicated, and there is no party rule that says Mrs. Jackson
should get special treatment.''
   Mrs. Jackson also said she does not expect any favors at the
party's April 16 state convention.
   ``I naturally would like to go to the national convention to do
everything I could for my son ... it would be a great honor,'' she
said. ``But I'm involved because I believe in constructive change
and helping everybody.''
</TEXT>
