<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0723 04-06 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0723,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Palestinians Must Renounce Terror to Negotiate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with interview, review of day's activities</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians who renounce terror and
recognize Israel are welcome at Arab-Israeli peace talks, but not
the PLO or those ``who have committed acts of terrorism,''
Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Wednesday.
   Shultz spoke in an interview that was televised in Israel as he
met with King Hussein of Jordan. It was taped in Jerusalem earlier
Wednesday.
   The secretary, who called Hussein ``a man of peace,'' hopes to
persuade the king and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel to
drop their reservations and agree to negotations.
   ``Say yes to this initiative,'' Shultz implored Shamir in a
statement after a final meeting with the prime minister Wednesday.
``Let us redouble our efforts to make it (peace) a reality.''
   As he passed the halfway point in his latest Middle East
venture, Shultz acknowledged having little to show for his second
visit to the region in a month.
   He said he was still committed to making the U.S. peace plan
work, but declared: ``In all candor, I am not able to say that it
is happening. While we have made some progress, differences have
not been substantially narrowed.''
   On departure from Ben Gurion airport, Shultz pledged U.S.
support for Israel and its security, but said in apparent criticism
of Shamir's reluctance: ``More fundamentally, security and progress
for Israel comes from peace between Israel and its neighbors. It is
possible. It can happen.''
   His next stop was Cairo, where President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt
reaffirmed approval of the U.S. plan and said after talking with
Shultz that he hoped Shamir would change his ``conception ... for
the hope of peace.''
   Palestinian representation is among the most difficult unsettled
issues. In 1974, all Arab countries including Jordan declared the
PLO the sole legitimate representative of the Palestinians.
   Mubarak and President Hafez Assad of Syria have called publicly
for a PLO seat in the negotiations, as have ranking Jordanian
officials.
   Shultz's plan would include Palestinians in a joint delegation
with Jordan, and U.S. officials have indicated the arrangement is
satisfactory to Hussein.
   In 1985, the king appeared to have worked out such an
arrangement with Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. It fell apart, and with it the prospects
for Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   In the interview with Israel television, Shultz said Hussein is
showing himself ``ready to be engaged'' in the latest U.S. effort
by raising questions about the proposal. It calls for talks on
Palestinian self rule, then negotiations on an overall settlement
of the 40-year Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``He is a partner and is ready to talk and think and work and
try to find answers,'' Shultz said.
   He said Palestinians who take part in negotiations must be
legitimate representatives of the people in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, adding that ``in no way'' could Israel
simply choose Palestinians it likes.
   On the other hand, he said, the PLO is committed to violence and
Israel's destruction so Palestinians who want to negotiate should
be willing to ``step up and say `I renounce terrorism. I accept 242
and a basis for negotiation.'''
   His reference was to the U.N. Security Council resolution that
implies recognition of Israel and calls for it to withdraw from
occupied territory. It was passed after the 1967 Middle East war,
in which Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza from Jordan and
Egypt.
   In an interview Tuesday with Jordanian editors, the secretary
ruled out a Palestinian state, said total Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank and Gaza was ``not in the cards'' and accused the PLO
of trying to exterminate Israel.
   His comments were not published or broadcast in Jordan. One
official said fear of inflaming anti-American opinion in Jordan,
which has a Palestinian majority, was among the reasons for
withholding them.
</TEXT>
