<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StagDinner     04-06 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stag Dinner,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forty & Eight To Admit Women To `Stag' Dinner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lasociete is cq in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE ST. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterans' group Wednesday agreed to
admit ``anyone presenting a ticket'' to an oyster dinner it has
held for men only for 39 years but said this is the last year it
will conduct the event.
   ``Men have a right to have a stag party,'' the West Virginia
chapter of the Forty & Eight Lasociete said in a statement. ``This
has always been a classy affair sponsored by a classy organization.
We are not pigs and neither are we backward.''
   The dinner, expected to attract 1,200 people Friday, is a
favorite campaign stop for candidates. But Republican congressional
candidate Marianne Brewster said she had been told she would not be
admitted because she is a woman, even though she bought a ticket.
   Other candidates subsequently said they would not show up unless
women were allowed.
   Attorney General Charlie Brown, also seeking re-election this
year, entered the fray Tuesday with a letter to McDowell County
school Superintendent J. Kenneth Roberts pointing out that the
dinner site, a high school in the county, is public property and
anyone with a ticket must be allowed to attend.
   ``We all would agree West Virginia needed progressive changes,''
Brewster said Wednesday. ``This is one giant step in that
direction.''
   The Forty & Eight chapter said no one will be allowed into the
event without a ticket, no tickets will be sold at the door and it
will discontinue the dinners, its only fund-raising event, after
this year.
   ``It is unfortunate that outsiders who could have directed
attention to the event and what results from it instead chose to
enhance their own welfare,'' the organization said. ``They should
have been making statements about the good things that result from
the event.''
   Money from the $15-a-ticket dinner goes toward sponsorship of
groups such as the Little League and Special Olympics, the
statement said.
   Forty & Eight, based nationally in Indianapolis, began as an
honorary society for American Legion members, but the groups are
now separate and Legion officials in West Virginia dissociated
themselves from the stag affair.
   ``We split in 1972. We don't even allow Forty & Eight lapel pins
on people in our parades, that's how much we split,'' said Robert
Vass, state adjutant for the Legion.
   ``It's just a redneck approach,'' he said of the stag dinner.
``This is 1988! You don't disenfranchise a congressional candidate
because she's a woman.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
