<DOCNO> AP880406-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Relief     04-06 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Relief,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famine-Plagued Regions Too Dangerous For Relief Workers,
Government Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday advised
international relief agencies to remove their foreign workers from
two drought-stricken northern regions because of increasing rebel
violence.
   The government's Relief and Rehabilitation Commission said the
Tigray and Eritrea regions no longer are safe for the foreign
agencies.
   ``In recent weeks the emergency relief aid distribution by the
(commission) and international donor organizations has been
disrupted by terrorists engaged in destructive activities against
the unity, integrity and freedom of Ethiopia,'' the commission said
in a two-page statement distributed to foreign aid groups.
   ``In addition to the destruction of trucks flying the United
Nations flag and transportation of relief supplies, the bandits
have time and again kidnapped expatriates in the regions,'' it said.
   The commission said foreigners should stay out of the north
``until the areas are freed from terrorist activity and tranquility
is restored to the life of the civilian population in the areas.''
   The government agency asked donors and international relief
agencies to turn over their operations to the commission to
guarantee the continuity of aid to the starving.
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said Ethiopia's food crisis is becoming more severe because
there is not enough security for aid workers.
   ``We're naturally concerned that any diminution of the
international relief effort will have a negative impact on the
lives of starving people,'' she said.
   ``Clearly, in an unpredictable war situation, safety for relief
personnel is also a serious consideration,'' she said. ``We hope
that the Ethiopian government will take steps to ensure the safety
of relief personnel as well.''
   Last week, President Mengistu Haile Mariam told Ethiopians in a
radio address that government troops were facing a ``grim
struggle'' against separatist rebels in Eritrea and Tigray.
Mengistu said the government was mobilizing troops to crush the
rebellions.
   Separatist rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Eritrea and
14 years in Tigray.
   The fighting has disrupted relief efforts in both regions, where
crop failures threaten 3.5 million people with starvation. Overall,
nearly 7 million Ethiopians are facing famine.
   There are about 60 non-governmental relief organizations working
in Ethiopia, but only a few operate in Eritrea and Tigray. Agencies
operating in the area include the International Committee of the
Red Cross, Doctors Without Borders of Belgium and Catholic Relief
Services.
   Most of the relief agencies in Ethiopia arrived during a 1984-85
drought and famine that killed an estimated 1 million Ethiopians.
It prompted the biggest aid effort in history.
   Most foreign agencies pared their expatriate staffs after the
1984-85 emergency and turned over programs to Ethiopians. Exact
numbers of foreign workers still in Ethiopia were not immediately
available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
