<DOCNO> AP880406-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Kuwait-Shiites     04-06 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Shiites,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Hijackers' Demands Similar To Those of Hostage-Takers in
Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Hijack, Bjt
^By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The demand made by hijackers of a Kuwaiti
jet is the same as that made by Moslems holding Americans hostage
in Lebanon _ freedom for 17 pro-Iranian extremists jailed in Kuwait
for bombing U.S. and French embassies there in 1983.
   The Arab hijackers forced the airliner to fly to Iran on Monday.
   Their nationality and identity remain unknown, but speculation
arose that they might be part of an Iranian-linked network of
terrorists.
   Kuwait, a small, oil-rich desert emirate caught in the crossfire
of the Iran-Iraq war, refuses to free any of the 17 prisoners and
reiterated Tuesday that Kuwait will not bow to ``blackmail.''
   The passengers and crew held hostage aboard Kuwait Airways
Flight 422 have apparently become pawns in a war between followers
of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and foes of his Islamic revolution.
   The same could be said about Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, and educator Thomas
Sutherland, two Americans held captive in Lebanon since 1985.
   Kuwait is a conservative state ruled by Sunni Moslems, historic
rivals of the Shiite sect who make up the vast majority of Iran's
50 million people.
   Kuwait fears that Iran's fundamentalist Islamic revolution will
spread, inciting its Shiite minority to revolt.
   Other Arab neighbors of Iran in the Persian Gulf have similar
fears.
   Spurred by Khomeini's revolution and by the 1982 invasion of
Lebanon by Israel, Lebanon's Shiites launched suicide bombings
against the Israelis and later against U.S. and French troops who
took part in an ill-fated multinational peacekeeping force in
Lebanon.
   Shiite extremists have targeted Kuwait in particular over the
past five years. Iran accuses Kuwait of aiding Iraq in the Persian
Gulf war.
   The 17 prisoners in Kuwait were convicted of bombings in 1983
that killed five people and wounded 86, culminating in attacks on
the U.S. and French embassies in Kuwait.
   Later terrorist attacks on Kuwait included an abortive 1985
assassination attempt on the emir, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah.
   Three of the 17 prisoners _ two Iraqis and a Lebanese identified
as Elias Fuad Saab _ were sentenced to death.
   The Shiite kidnappers in Lebanon are concerned in particular
about Saab, whose real name is Mustafa Youssef. He is a cousin of
Imad Mugniyeh, believed by Western and Lebanese intelligence to be
the mastermind of Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, and other extremist
Shiite factions responsible for suicide bombings, kidnappings and
aircraft hijackings in recent years.
   Western intelligence officials believe Saab rigged the bombs
used in the Kuwait attacks.
   Kuwait has so far not carried out any of the executions, but
that seems to have been its only concession. It has arrested dozens
of other Shiites for sabotage since 1983.
   Mugniyeh, 36, is a key figure in the security apparatus of
Hezbollah, or Party of God, an Iranian-backed Shiite movement
believed to be the umbrella for factions holding most of the 22
foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   His family has been long linked with the Hamadis, another Shiite
clan involved in kidnappings.
   U.S. authorities identified Mugniyeh and Mohammed Ali Hamadi,
held in West Germany on charges of smuggling explosives, as two of
the four Lebanese Shiites involved in the June 1985 hijacking of a
TWA airliner in which U.S. Navy diver Robert Dean Stethem was
killed.
   The Hamadis allegedly kidnapped three West Germans in Beirut
trying to force West Germany to free Mohammed and a brother, Abbas,
who now is on trial in Duesseldorf for kidnapping two Germans. A
third Hamadi brother, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, is Hezbollah's security
chief in Beirut.
   Members of the Mugniyeh family are thought to have kidnapped
Anderson, who was seized March 16, 1985, and is the longest held of
the missing foreigners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
