<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-JapanWhales 2ndLd-Writethru a0810 04-06 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Whales, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0810,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Imposes Sanctions Against Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Under provisions
...'' to add that Japan currently has no fishing quota.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan informed Congress
Wednesday that he has stripped Japan of certain fishing rights
because of that country's alleged violation of an international
whale conservation program.
   Reagan said the Commerce Department had certified the violations
based on permits Japan has issued for the killing of Southern
Hemisphere minke whales for research purposes.
   ``The sanctions are the strongest possible'' under legislation
authorizing presidential action, Reagan said in a letter to House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   The administration maintains that Japan has run afoul of an
International Whaling Commission whale conservation program by
issuing permits for research that has never been approved by the
IWC.
   The issuance of the permits by Japan to its citizens came
despite a 1987 whaling commission resolution recommending that no
such licenses be granted until questions about the research program
were resolved, Reagan's letter said.
   It noted that shortly after the certification of the violations
by Commerce Secretary C. William Verity, the whaling commission
adopted a second resolution recommending that Japan not go ahead
with its research program.
   ``Japan has continued its whaling activities notwithstanding
this second resolution,'' the letter said.
   Under provisions of the Magnuson Fishery Conservation and
Management Act and the Fishermen's Protective Act, Reagan directed
the State Department to withhold 100 percent of the fishing
privileges ``that would otherwise be available to Japan'' in waters
under U.S. authority.
   The current Japanese fishing quota in the 200-mile offshore U.S.
economic zone is zero.
   Reagan said he was denying Japan's request to fish for 3,000
metric tons of sea snails and 5,000 metric tons of Pacific whiting.
   ``In addition, Japan will be barred from any future allocations
of fishing privileges for any other species, including Pacific cod,
until the secretary of commerce determines that the situation has
been corrected,'' he said.
   Ken Cook, spokesman for the U.S. affiliate of the World Wildlife
Fund, said the announced fishing sanctions ``would hurt some,'' but
came too late to save any of the 300 minke whales Japan plans to
take in this year's research program.
   Reagan's letter to Wright said that ``the immediate and
prospective effects of a 100 percent reduction of fishing
allocations, coupled with presidential review in the near future,
is the most effective means of encouraging Japan to embrace the IWC
conservation program.''
   ``Therefore, I will not impose at this time'' any sanctions
against Japanese fish products imported into the United States, it
said.
   Reagan ordered Verity and Secretary of State George Shultz to
report by Dec. 1 on Japan's willingness to comply with the whaling
conservation program.
   He also said he was directing Verity and Shultz to continue
talks with whaling commission member countries ``to ensure that we
bring to a halt all whaling that diminishes the effectiveness of
the IWC's conservation program.''
   ``Our actions taken today and in the future should encourage all
nations to adhere to the conservation programs of the IWC,'' the
president's letter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
