<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN To Send Team To Investigate Iraqi Charges About Chemical
Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-man U.N. team will leave for Baghdad
on Thursday to investigate Iraq's charges that Iran has used
chemical weapons, spokesman Francois Giuliani said Wednesday.
   The same team went to Tehran last week to look into Iranian
charges that Iraq used gas bombs last month that killed 5,000
people, but no report has been released. The Persian Gulf neighbors
have been at war since September 1980.
   Iraq was angered by the U.N. team's visit to Tehran. It accused
the United Nations of siding with Iran and asked Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar, for whom Giuliani speaks, to conduct a
similar investigation of Iran's tactics.
   Tehran radio quoted Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati as
saying the decision to send the team to Iran was ``surprising'' and
he had written to Perez de Cuellar to complain.
   The secretary-general has said there was evidence that Iraq has
used chemical weapons and appealed to both sides to stop attacking
civilian targets.
   Perez de Cuellar met Wednesday with Iran's deputy foreign
minister, Mohammed Javad Larijani, and is to meet next week with
Tariq Aziz, the Iraqi foreign minister.
</TEXT>
