<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DutchKidnap     04-06 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dutch Kidnap,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Dutch Kidnap Case Reported Solved, But Victim Presumed Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANDSMEER, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister said the
Netherlands' longest running kidnap case was solved with five
arrests on Wednesday, but said the victim was ``almost certainly
dead,'' Dutch television reported.
   Retail tycoon Gerrit-Jan Heyn, 65, was kidnapped nearly seven
months ago. In reporting on Justice Minister Frits Korthals Altes'
announcement, the TV account gave no details on what happened to
Heyn.
   It said six suspects were arrested in a pre-dawn raid Wednesday
in Landsmeer, 10 miles north of Amsterdam, but one was released
later in the day. The report did not identify any of the group, in
line with Dutch police practice.
   The television report said the five were thought to hold part of
a ransom of more than $4.3 million in cash and diamonds paid for
Heyn on Nov. 27.
   Among those held was a 45-year old architect, whose house police
staked out for weeks, the TV report said. It was there the six were
arrested, it said.
   Police were not immediately available to comment on the
televison report.
   Heyn, vice chairman of the Ahold grocery concern, was kidnapped
on Sept. 9 near his sumptuous villa in Bloemendaal, 20 miles west
of The Hague.
   A month later, the kidnappers mailed one of Heyn's fingers to
Ahold as proof they were holding him. They never gave further proof
Heyn was still alive.
   A 70-member police team was organized to solve the kidnapping.
It soon imposed an information blackout on the case, which was
lifted in December when authorities launched a national publicity
blitz and promised a million-guilder ($550,000) reward for
information leading to the kidnappers' arrest.
   Police arrested a suspect in January but had to release him for
lack of evidence.
</TEXT>
