<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     04-06 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Brushes Off Threats From Renegade Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on Wednesday
shrugged off new threats of violence by the escaped leader of a
1987 coup attempt, but other officials said the military had
readied itself for possible attacks.
   A statement attributed to former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan vowed he would ``act boldly'' after having fled a prison
ship in Manila Bay Saturday. It said Honasan promised last November
``not to engage in hostile acts'' against the Aquino government so
she could make good her promises of political reform. But the
statement said it later became obvious that her administration
imperiled the nation and so, ``We are now withdrawing that
declaration.''
   Mrs. Aquino said, ``I think he will have to admit that the
government had adequately answered already the legitimate
grievances, and I think the Filipino people definitely will go
against Honasan. He will not be able to get support.''
   Honasan had been detained since Dec. 9 for last year's Aug. 28
coup attempt that left 53 people dead and hundreds wounded.
   National Security Adviser Emanuel Soriano dismissed Honasan's
statement as ``just hot air'' but added: ``Of course, we will be in
a situation of watchful waiting.''
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
said that while Honasan would ``lie low for a while,'' he would
``eventually move in the direction of taking some action to
destabilize the government.''
   Maceda added, ``However, the armed forces of the Philippines
leadership has already put into action instructions and strategies
to neutralize any effort on the part of Honasan to contact, regroup
or reconsolidate his friends or forces within the military.''
   The 160,000-member armed forces was put on alert and a
nationwide search was mounted for Honasan after he escaped with 14
of his guards. But military spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo said
troops found no trace of him.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos described the Honasan statement as
``a call to violence'' and said he ordered the military to verify
its authenticity.
   The statement was distributed to news agencies Wednesday.
   Honasan had accused the government of being soft on communist
rebels when he attempted his coup.
   Communist New People's Army rebels meanwhile kidnapped town
mayor Manuel Pandayos and two other officials on Monday in Quirino
in northern Ilocos Sur province, the military said.
   On southern Mindanao island, 20 raiders thought to be Moslem
rebels attacked the American-owned Sibuco Timber Co. in the
mountain village of Camarangan and killed seven workers, the
military said.
   In the central town of Himamaylan on Negros island, five family
members, including three children, were killed Wednesday during
what the military said was a raid on a communist hideout. A
survivor denied that the families had ties to the rebels.
</TEXT>
