<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Elections     04-06 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Elections,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Reported Killed In Election Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Najib is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas opened fire on polling
stations during national elections, killing at least three people,
the government radio station reported Wednesday.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said seven other people
were wounded in the attack by opposition forces in the eastern
province of Kunar near the Pakistani border.
   The elections for 62 Senate and 229 National Assembly seats
began on Tuesday and are to run until April 14.
   The radio station earlier said that voting in the eastern
provinces of Kandahar, Bamian, Kunar and Kapisa and the district of
Khost was ``taking place in difficult conditions.''
   It said the opposition had fired on some voting centers in these
areas, which are under the control of communist government forces.
   The Moslem guerrillas claim to control about 80 percent of
Afghanistan, most of it outside the big cities.
   One-fourth of the seats in the Senate and the National Assembly
are being set aside for the rebel candidates even if they do not
participate, the government says.
   The insurgents have not commented officially on the elections,
which are the first since the communists seized power 10 years ago.
Guerrilla officials speaking privately dismissed them as a farce.
   Western diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
have said the vote is meaningless at a time when peace talks are
taking place in Geneva and the Soviet Union is reportedly preparing
to withdraw an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   ``Since the beginning of the elections, extremist opposition
elements have attacked homes and residences with heavy arms. Their
inhuman action was repeated today,'' Radio Kabul said. It said a
number of houses were destroyed, but gave no further details.
   President Najib cast his vote Tuesday, when about 147,300 people
out of the 955,000 registered to vote cast ballots, the radio said.
   The communist party came to power in an April 1978 coup. Soviet
forces intervened in December 1979 to help the faltering government
fight the anti-communist Moslem guerrillas.
   The United States and Pakistan have supported the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
