<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     04-06 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Mediator Discusses Hostages With Shiite Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French mediator met with Lebanon's
justice minister Wednesday and said there were signs that French
hostages held in Lebanon would be freed shortly.
   Lucien Bitterlin, a former Gaullist parliament deputy who heads
a pro-Arab lobbying group, talked for an hour with Justice Minister
Nabih Berri, leader of the Syrian-backed Shiite Amal militia.
   ``There are encouraging signals, as I gathered from Minister
Berri, that an adequate solution for the issue of the French
hostages would be achieved shortly,'' Bitterlin told reporters
without elaborating.
   He said the discussions focused on the fate of at least three
Frenchmen held by the pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad underground faction.
   It was the first time Bitterlin declared publicly he was
involved in efforts to free the hostages. He has made at least
three negotiating trips to Beirut since December.
   The hostages are Marcel Fontaine, 47, vice consul at the French
Embassy in Beirut, Marcel Carton, 64, the embassy's protocol
officer, and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann, 43.
   Fontaine and Carton were abducted separately on March 22, 1985,
and Kauffmann on May 22 the same year. The kidnappings were claimed
by Islamic Jihad or Holy War, a group of Shiite Moslems loyal to
Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Bitterlin had said during previous trips that he was negotiating
the release of eight Europeans seized last year by a radical
Palestinian guerrilla faction headed by Abu Nidal. He said he had
not discussed that case Wednesday with Berri.
   Shiite militants loyal to Iran are believed to hold most of the
22 foreign hostages in Lebanon, including nine Americans. The
longest held hostage is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
