<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 08,0852</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mainline Denomination Abandoning Pro-Choice Abortion Stand</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mainline American denomination, the American
Baptist Churches, is backing away from its support of abortion
rights, officials indicated this week.
   It was the first such definitive shift projected among the
larger, socially activist Protestant bodies.
   Similar reassessments have come in some other major
denominations, either stiffening opposition to abortion, or
qualifying acceptance of it. But some still take an essentially
pro-choice position.
   The turn away from it planned by American Baptists stemmed both
from simmering discontent with the past stance and the swelling
tide of abortions in the country.
   ``The great proliferation of abortion has made us stop and look
at what's happening here,'' says Gloria Marshall of Alto Loma,
Calif., head of a task force which has been re-examining the issue
for more than two years.
   ``It's a process of reevaluation and reassessment,'' she said in
a telephone interview. ``This is a continuing necessity if the
church is to carry out its prophetic role on such a key social
issue.''
   She said positions can't be fixed ``in concrete,'' but ``are
pulled along by social changes on the issue and as we understand
more about it.'' She termed the projected new stand
``responsibility to choose life.''
   It attempts a path-breaking middle ground.
   ``It is a pro-life stance in affirming the sacredness of life as
a gift of God,'' she said. But it avoids both the ``pro-life'' and
``pro-choice'' terms commonly used in the polarized conflict over
abortion.
   Mrs. Marshall, a former missionary in Zaire and wife of a
minister, said: ``We've sought a different vocabulary for dealing
with a very complex subject. We've tried to find a common ground
for ministering to people about it.''
   The newly prepared statement, expected to be approved in a final
presentation to a policy-making general board in June, acknowledges
keen diversity among the denomination's 1.6 million members on the
issue.
   Howevever, the statement breaks with the previous 1981 stand,
which saw abortion in terms of religious liberty as a ``matter of
responsible personal choice.''
   The new document, recognizing ``life as a sacred and gracious
gift of God,'' says:
   ``As American Baptists we oppose abortion, as a means of
avoiding responsibility for conception, as a primary means of birth
control, without regard for the far-reaching consequences of the
act.
   ``We denounce irresponsible sexual behavior and acts of sexual
violence that contribute to the large number of abortions each year.
   ``We grieve with all who struggle with the difficult
circumstances that lead them to consider abortion. Recognizing that
each person is ultimately responsible to God, we encourage women
and men in these circumstances to seek spiritual counsel as they
prayerfully and conscientiously consider their decision.''
   A sister church, the larger 14.6-million Southern Baptist
Convention, takes a firmly anti-abortion position, toughening that
stand in 1984 to ask for laws prohibiting all abortion except to
``save the physical life of the mother.''
   Changes also have come among more liberal mainline bodies,
including:
   The Presbyterian Church (USA) in 1985 qualified its acceptance
of choice in the matter, opposing abortion ``as a method of birth
control'' or for ``convenience or to ease embarrassment.''
   The Church of the Brethren in 1984 explicitly condemned
abortion, after previously taking a more pastoral view of it.
   The former Lutheran Church in America, now merged into the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, in 1980 sharpened its
rejection of abortion, saying it destroys life, and urged laws
protecting it ``from conception to birth.''
   Numerous denominations have steadily rejected abortion,
including Eastern Orthodox churches, Roman Catholicism, the
Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod, Mormons and conservative
evangelical denominations.
   However, several mainline bodies, such as the United Methodist
Church, Episcopal Church, United Church of Christ and Christian
Church (Disciples of Christ), uphold choice about abortion, and the
legalizing of it.
   The seven-member American Baptist task force, including three
supporters of legalized abortion, three opponents and one
undetermined about it, has held hearings across the country,
gathered questionaires and a flood of letters.
   Mary Mild, staff assistant on the project at the denomination's
headquarters in Valley Forge, Pa., said there has been some
discontent with the previous stance of 1981. ``Enough people were
not happy'' with it as ``reflecting where we really are,'' she said.
   The revision expresses no opinion of the 1973 Supreme Court
decision legalizing abortion, neither for nor against, but condemns
harassing either abortion clinics or doctors refusing to do
abortions.
   The seven-page statement stresses education and ministry to
reinforce responsible sexuality, to help those facing problem
pregnancies and to provide needed financial aid to women carrying
such pregnancies to birth.
   While not citing any circumstances that justify abortion, as was
done previously, the new statement urges a ministry of ``love and
spiritual counsel to those who choose to terminate their
pregnancies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv08   04-06 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 08,0624</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 8, and thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increasingly volatile topic in
this election year _ the place of religion in American public life
_ will be examined by about 100 scholars April 11-12 at the
University of Virginia.
   The gathering is part of a project by the Williamsburg Charter
Foundation to forge a new consensus on the subject.
   The chairman of the non-partisan, widely representative
organization, Alonzo L. McDonald of Troy, Minn., businessman and
former diplomat, says ``deep polarization'' has developed about
religion and politics.
   He says ``the time is ripe for re-thinking the principles that
should guide debate about religion in the public arena.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 17 years of work, the Bible Society
of Kenya has printed the first complete translation of the Bible in
the language of the Masai, traditional herdsmen and warriors of
that country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-night prayer vigil on behalf of people
with AIDS was scheduled this weekend at the Fordham University
Church in the Bronx.
   The Rev. Paul W. Brant, campus ministry director, says
participants will spend the night, from 9 P.M. to 9 A.M. Saturday,
``praying for all men, women and children with AIDS, for their
loved ones, for all who work with them, and for a cure.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys or brain surgeons can live however they
please and still perform flawlessly in the courtroom or operating
room, but this doesn't apply to ministers in the pulpit, one of
them says.
   Th Rev. Joel Gregory of Fort Worth, president of the state
Baptist Convention, told its executive board that when a minister
strays, he ``loses it all.''
   Without mentioning names, he alluded indirectly to the
scandal-toppled TV preachers Jim Bakker and Jimmy Swaggart, citing
``high-profile individuals who contradict that which they spoke.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon leaders say a record 227,284
converts to the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in 1987
brings total membership to 6.5 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopal bishops from across the
country are to take part in the consecration Saturday of Oris G.
Walker Jr. as Bishop Coadjutor of Long Island, raising hopes of
women in that diocese seeking ordination.
   Walker, from Detroit, has voiced support for such ordinations,
although women have been turned down for it in that diocese, third
largest in the country, ever since the denomination authorized
women's ordination in 1976.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Orthodox Christians celebrate Easter
this Sunday, April 10, a week after the celebration by Western
Christians.
   The later Orthodox observance is based on a decree of the
Council of Nicaea in 325 A.D., saying Easter should be celebrated
after the Hebrew Passover observance to maintain the biblical
sequence of events.
   The Jewish Passover lasted through this week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A personnel shakeup has hit the the biggest
agency of the United Methodist Church, the Board of Global
Ministries.
   Two top-level executives, Peggy Billings, head of the world
mission program, and the Rev. John A. Murdock, head of health and
welfare ministries, were notified they were not being named to
another term.
   Earlier this year, the Rev. Rene O. Bideaux, head of national
missions, announced he was resigning in June to return to parish
ministry.
   The Rev. Randolph Nugent, the agency's chief executive, said the
new actions did not result from criticism of the board's mission
policy by the evangelical caucus, Good News, which has opposed Ms.
Billings.
</TEXT>
