<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv16-17   04-06 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 16-17,0744</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, April 16-17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bonneville SSE An Impressive Road Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Pontiac Bonneville SSE is more than a
technology buff's dream come true.
   It's an impressive road car and comfortable large sedan that
even a techno-phobe can appreciate.
   Inside the aerodynamically styled vehicle, a driver can tune the
radio without taking his hands off the steering wheel. The radio
buttons are built into the wheel, around the horn. An electronic
compass senses the earth's magnetic field. Thus, changes in the
SSE's direction are continuously displayed on an electronic map on
the dashboard.
   And a new, smooth, fuel-injected 3800 V6, wonderfully firm
suspension, Goodyear Eagle GT+4 radial tires and antilock brakes
join to provide stable road handling and enjoyable ride.
   Yes, the SSE is a car to show off to friends and neighbors. But
it doesn't come cheaply. Base price is $21,879.
   You get what you pay for: The SSE is so loaded with standard
equipment there are only three options (alarm system, interior
leather and power sunroof).
   Additionally, the SSE is priced below many of its foreign
competitors, such as the Audi 5000, which starts at more than
$22,000, and Volvo 760, which starts around $31,200.
   New for the 1988 model year, the SSE is the top of the
Bonneville line which was redesigned inside and out for the 1987
model year.
   The lowest-priced Bonneville, the LE, has a base price of
$14,099 and nearly the same stylish exterior as the SSE but without
the fancy handling package and technology frills.
   There's also a middle offering _ the Bonneville SE that starts
at $16,299 and shares the new 3.8-liter V6 with the SSE but not the
same suspension.
   Pontiac, a division of General Motors Corp., expects to build
only 14,000 Bonneville SSEs this model year, and spokesman Reginald
Harris says, ``We expect to sell them all with no problem. The
initial reception to the car has been great, exceeding our
forecast.''
   Pontiac projects total Bonneville sales this model year of
110,000, up from 93,575 in the 1987 model year, he added.
Bonnevilles rank third in volume at Pontiac, behind the Grand Am
and Pontiac 6000 models.
   The majority of buyers targeted for the 1988 Bonnevilles are
male and married, Pontiac says. Average age is 49 for the LE and 45
for the SSE. The division looks for 44 percent of the LE buyers and
64 percent of the SSE buyers to be college graduates.
   Average household income of targeted buyers is $41,000 for the
LE and $61,000 for the SSE. Many of these (SSE) buyers are
intenders of high-level imports who previously haven't had a
domestic choice, the division said. They're attracted to very
expressive styling and are very discriminating in quality and
function of features.
   The test Bonneville SSE was fun, though there were a few
glitches. At night, the dashboard lit up like a Christmas tree
because of all the electronics and buttons, including those for
automatic heat and air conditioning.
   However, one of the buttons for setting interior temperature
sometimes stuck.
   An electronic screen on the dashboard indicated when the next
oil change, tire rotation and tune-up were needed and monitored
doors and the trunk to make sure they were secured.
   But I drove 5 miles with the trunk ajar, and no warning appeared
on the screen.
   The 10-way, adjustable front bucket seats were roomy and had
countless comfortable settings, including three buttons for power
lumbar support at three different spots in the back of the seats.
   But the power headrests were bulkier than I was used to and I
found myself craning to look around them when backing up.
   Still, the trunk was flat and spacious, and the Delco sound
system was superb.
   There was comfortable seating in the rear, and a rear arm
rest-console provided a spot for beverages and storage if only two
people rode back there.
   However, because the model is so new, Consumer Reports does not
yet have repair records.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 16-17</NOTE>
