<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s largest shareholder,
Carl C. Icahn, has appealed a federal bankruptcy court's approval
of Texaco's bankruptcy reorganization plan, restating objections
already rejected by the judge.
   The plan still will take effect on schedule Thursday unless
Icahn also persuades the bankruptcy court judge to halt the
process, which will include $5.6 billion in payments to the oil
giant's creditors.
   The nation's third-largest oil company filed for Chapter 11
protection from its creditors a year ago due to its legal battle
with Houston-based Pennzoil Co. over the acquisition of Getty Oil.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
warned consumers about new operator service companies that are
charging telephone callers up to 10 times the rates of the major
long-distance carriers.
   The FCC's warning Tuesday was prompted by a recent surge in
complaints about these new alternative operator services, known as
AOS companies, said Greg Vogt, chief of the FCC's telephone
enforcement division.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The richest 1 percent of Americans paid more
than one-fourth of all individual income taxes in 1986, due in
large part to an extraordinary increase in investment income, the
Treasury Department said.
   The portion of taxes paid by those with incomes of less than
$50,000 a year dropped from 66.8 percent in 1981, before enactment
of across-the-board tax cuts, to 45.7 percent in 1986, the
department said Tuesday.
   During the same period, the share borne by those making over
$100,000 more than doubled, from 15.2 percent of the total to 30.6
percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lack of political progress toward
substantially cutting the budget deficit and reforming federal
market regulation threatens to cause another stock crash, the
chairman of the American Stock Exchange said.
   ``The conditions that created the atmosphere in which a market
meltdown nearly occurred are still present _ creating a kind of
economic time bomb that threatens the whole system,'' Arthur Levitt
Jr. told a National Press Club luncheon Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New college graduates this spring will face a
tight job market, with competition-conscious companies less willing
to offer extended on-the-job training, a veteran placement
professional says.
   ``Employers ... today have neither the time nor inclination to
`bring somebody along' gradually,'' said James E. Challenger,
president of Chicago-based Challenger, Gray & Christmas Inc., which
descibes itself as the nation's oldest outplacement firm.
   An increasingly competitive marketplace is facing all companies,
Challenger said in an analysis of the 1988 college graduate job
outlook, released Monday.
</TEXT>
