<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-06 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0560</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates are not headed skyward despite a
slight uptick in recent weeks, economists say.
   Interest rates rise when lenders become fearful of inflation,
but so far inflation remains under control in spite of surprisingly
strong economic growth, a number of economists interviewed Tuesday
said.
   Consumer prices are rising at an annual rate of between 4
percent and 4.5 percent, roughly the same as they have for the past
three years. And that has allowed Americans to enjoy a rare
combination of fairly robust growth and slowly rising prices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. fired one of its longtime
advertising agencies, and a source familiar with the decision said
it was because the tobacco and foods giant was upset with a
no-smoking ad that the agency recently made for another client,
Northwest Airlines.
   The agency is Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Inc., which has been making
Nabisco cookie ads for 12 years and Life Saver candy ads for 18
years.
   Industry sources estimated Tuesday the agency was handling about
$100 million in advertising billings for RJR Nabisco, making it a
major account by ad industry standards.
</TEXT>
