<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-06 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Drop Sharply, Volume Light</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have skidded below the
$17-a-barrel range following a Kuwaiti news report that OPEC's
pricing committee would not recommend a full ministerial conference
of the cartel at its April 9 meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May delivery price of
West Texas Intermediate crude oil fell 22 cents per barrel to
$16.79 on Tuesday. Most of the drop came in the afternoon, but
volume was relatively light.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale No. 2
heating oil fell 0.80 cent a gallon to 45.20 cents, and unleaded
gasoline fell 0.71 cent a gallon to 48.64 cents.
   The oil market has been focusing on Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries' price and production policies because of a
persistent output glut and widespread reports of cheating among the
cartel's 13 members on their self-imposed production limits.
   The April 9 meeting in Vienna had incited some hope that OPEC
would act aggressively to stabilize prices and enforce production
discipline to limit excessive supplies. Traders said the Kuwaiti
news report dampened the optimism and forced a selloff in the
futures market.
   But they said the light volume of trading suggested most oil
market participants are reluctant to buy or sell pending the
outcome of the price committee meeting.
   The committee has no power to alter OPEC policy but it can call
for a full ministerial meeting, considered its strongest option.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
