<DOCNO> AP880406-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PerfectGrass Bjt   04-06 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perfect Grass, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Search Of The Perfect Grass Seed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reed Funk's grass has shimmered in the Rose
Bowl, in Yankee Stadium, on the Masters golf course and across
thousands of private lawns.
   He's got a famous touch with turf, but the 59-year-old
researcher and academician says the grass is always greener
somewhere else.
   ``You start out with a variety and then immediately start
working on a replacement that's better, because nothing is
perfect,'' he said.
   Colleagues and others involved in the turf industry say Funk has
taken an unknown field and made it his own, revolutionizing the
development of grass and gaining international prominence in the
process.
   A Rutgers University researcher and turf science professor, Funk
has been developing scores of grass varieties for more than 20
years. In his New Brunswick offices and on 200 acres of test fields
in Adelphia, Funk combines various strains of grass seed in search
of the best combination.
   Funk has created fine-textured turf grasses, lush dark green
grasses, shade and drought-tolerant grasses, and grasses that repel
disease and insects, bearing such names as Rebel, Gator and Prelude.
   ``He is often referred to as the Albert Einstein of the seed
industry,'' said John Morrissey, executive vice president of Lofts
Seed Inc. of Bound Brook. ``There is nobody, probably in the world,
who is as knowledgeable on new varieties in the turf grass
industry.''
   Morrissey, who has done business with and consulted Funk for
about 20 years, said Funk's students are courted heavily by the
grass seed industry because of his track record.
   Funk's work and the work of students and faculty in the Cook
College soils and crops department at Rutgers have kept hundreds of
thousands of dollars in royalties flowing into the university's
turf research department.
   ``He's one of these fellows who's intelligent and he works
efficiently,'' said Ralph Engel, who retired two years ago after
serving as a long-time professor of turf science at Rutgers.
   ``He works lots of hours and he's put it all together,'' said
Engel, a 25-year associate of Funk.
   When the golf world's luminaries descend on the Augusta National
course in Georgia for the Masters Tournament on Thursday, they will
tread a course seeded partly with Funk's Palmer strain, named after
golf legend Arnold Palmer. The strain carpets many courses
throughout the Northeast, Funk says.
   Funk's Adelphi bluegrass, a hybrid of Kentucky bluegrass, long
has been used by groundskeepers at Shea Stadium in Flushing, N.Y.,
said stadium manager John McCarthy.
   ``It's a sturdy grass and ideal for the temperature of New
York,'' McCarthy said.
   Funk gravitated to turf research after an early life dominated
by agriculture. He was raised on a 600-acre dairy farm in Richmond,
Utah, and earned undergraduate and master's degrees in agronomy
from Utah State University.
   After earning his doctorate from Rutgers in 1961, Funk narrowly
missed getting an appointment to research sugarcane growth in
Hawaii. But the miss freed him to become Rutgers' first full-time
scientist working with turf grasses.
   He said his first creation to achieve widescale popularity was
the Manhattan perennial rye grass in 1967, which was considered a
marked improvement over other rye grasses. Funk said that grass
still is used in European soccer stadiums.
   This spring, Funk's Pinnacle grass _ which is resistant to a
number of insects _ should start cropping up on lawns, parks and
cemeteries in the Northeast.
   Over the past 20 years, Funk has become highly regarded for his
ability to adapt grasses to the needs of different climates and
situations, said Morrissey, of Lofts Seeds.
   But Funk's colleagues say he never is satisfied, and they
repeatedly are disarmed by his humility despite his grand
reputation and stellar credentials.
   ``He's the first one we've looked to,'' said Morrissey. ``The
great leader is Funk, who has developed probably more proprietary
turf types than any one in the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
