<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated-Campeau Bjt   04-06 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated-Campeau, Bjt,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau: Store Closings, Layoffs Possible at Federated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four days after he won his fight for Federated
Department Stores Inc., Robert Campeau was looking to expand the
retailer's top performers while cutting costs throughout the
company.
   The chairman of Campeau Corp. said Tuesday that Federated's
Bloomingdale's division, which now has 17 stores, potentially could
be a national chain and said he was considering opening branches in
Canada as well.
   But, Campeau told a news conference, expansion would come second
to cost-cutting and productivity.
   ``Our emphasis in the future is to raise the sales per square
foot,'' Campeau said.
   Campeau and Robert Morosky, the president of Campeau's Allied
Stores unit, said they would review each of Federated's divisions
to see where improvements could be made, and did not rule out
layoffs.
   ``There will be some streamlining,'' Campeau said. ``You cannot
survive and compete by having jobs and jobs and jobs.''
   ``That doesn't mean we will be laying off en masse,'' he said.
``We do want to expand.''
   Federated, the nation's fifth largest retailer, agreed Friday to
be taken over by Campeau, a Toronto-based developer, in a $6.58
billion buyout. The agreement ended a 2-month-long battle that
included a bidding war between Campeau and R.H. Macy & Co. Inc.
   Campeau said his company planned to retain Federated's Ralphs
supermarkets division in California. The 127-store chain was among
the divisions Campeau had been expected to sell when it began its
tender offer.
   Campeau said Ralphs would be sold into a wholly owned Campeau
Corp. subsidiary, with the proceeds of the sale used to help pay
for the Federated acquisition.
   Morosky reiterated that Campeau planned to retain six Federated
department store divisions: Bloomingdale's, Abraham & Straus,
Rich's, Burdine's, Goldsmith's and Lazarus. But some stores in
those divisions may be shut, Morosky said.
   ``Maybe they're better off as real estate locations,'' he said.
He declined to say which stores might be targeted for closing.
   Campeau was expected to deal with Federated as he did Allied
after it was acquired in 1986, by paring its unprofitable stores.
   Campeau already has agreed to sell four of Federated's
department store divisions, and expects to sell its Gold Circle
discount stores and its specialty store operations as well. Morosky
said Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Gold Circle's management have
expressed interest in the 76-store chain.
   Campeau refused to discuss a meeting he held with Macy Chairman
Edward Finkelstein last Thursday during which their takeover fight
was resolved, but described Finkelstein as ``relieved,'' and
himself as ``delighted.''
   Campeau said the takeover will cost his company a total of $8.8
billion, including the price of Federated shares, refinancing of
debt and expenses. He said he expected earnings of $375 million to
$400 million from the combined operations of Allied and Federated,
based on the companies' 1987 sales.
   He said he did not expect to use junk-bond financing in the
Federated acquisition except in the Ralphs transaction.
</TEXT>
