<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AdTurmoil     04-06 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ad Turmoil,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Order in Lord Geller Breakaway Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The combatants in the legal dispute over a
top-level walkout from the Lord, Geller, Federico, Einstein
advertising agency each say they are pleased by a New York state
judge's first ruling in the case.
   Justice Herman Cahn of the New York Supreme Court issued a
preliminary injunction Tuesday prohibiting the executives who left
Lord Geller from soliciting Lord Geller employees to work for their
new firm.
   He also enjoined two top defectors, Richard Lord and Arthur
Einstein Jr., from ``soliciting or accepting, directly or
indirectly'' any of Lord Geller's current clients.
   But the judge refused to prohibit the new agency from using the
name ``Lord'' in its title. The defectors have called their new
agency Lord, Einstein, O'Neill & Partners.
   A spokesman for the Lord Geller agency, James Fingeroth, said
the agency was ``very pleased'' by the ruling and felt that
securing a preliminary injunction against some types of activity
was a significant step in its favor.
   Lord Einstein said in a statement that the ruling ``paves the
way for Lord Einstein to devote its full energies to service the
needs of its clients.''
   Thomas Schwarz, attorney for Lord Einstein, said Lord and
Einstein never intended to solicit Lord Geller clients. He also
said the ruling leaves the agency free to hire any Lord Geller
employees who may apply on their own.
   The ruling came in a suit filed by Lord Geller's parent, WPP
Group PLC, accusing the departing executives of breaching their
fiduciary duties in leaving the firm and conspiring to take away
Lord Geller's business.
   Six top executives walked off the job at Lord Geller on March
18, saying they felt unduly constrained under WPP's management.
   Lord Geller was part of JWT Group Inc., which the British firm
WPP acquired for $566 million in July 1987 in the biggest ad
industry takeover to date.
</TEXT>
