<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Saatchi-Nabisco Bjt   04-06 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saatchi-Nabisco, Bjt,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Fires Saatchi & Saatchi, Citing Philosophical
Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food and tobacco giant RJR Nabisco Inc. has
fired a longtime advertising agency, and one source familiar with
the decision said it reflected RJR's displeasure over the agency's
no-smoking ads for another client.
   RJR cited recent philosophical differences Tuesday for its
decision to dismiss the ad agency Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Inc., and
declined to elaborate.
   But a source familiar with the decision said RJR was displeased
at the ads Saatchi recently developed to tout Northwest Airlines'
new no-smoking program.
   Industry sources estimate the agency was handling as much as
$100 million in ad billings for RJR Nabisco candy, cookies and
chewing gum, making it a major account by ad industry standards.
   In announcing the dismissal in a statement from Atlanta, the
company said, ``It is important as RJR Nabisco Inc. shapes and
executes its marketing and sales objectives it deals with
advertising agencies that have a wholly-consistent philosophical
approach to its plans and programs.''
   ``During this important period, philosophical differences have
developed between RJR Nabisco Inc. and one of its agencies, Saatchi
& Saatchi DFS Inc.,'' the statement said. As a result, RJR said it
had ``elected to conclude its relationship'' with Saatchi, the
successor to agencies that have created ads for Life Savers candy
for 18 years and various Nabisco cookies for 12 years.
   RJR executives refused to elaborate on the statement, or to
comment on the suggestion that it was unhappy with Saatchi's
no-smoking ads for Northwest.
   Saatchi said it was ``very saddened and disappointed'' at RJR's
action, but its executives also declined to comment on what may
have led to the decision.
   But one source familiar with the events, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said the company was unhappy with Saatchi's ads for
Northwest, which announced plans two weeks ago to ban smoking on
most of its North American flights starting April 23.
   The airline has promoted the plan heavily in print and broadcast
ads. The plan goes farther than required by government regulations,
which ban smoking on flights of less than two hours starting later
this month.
   In one television commercial announcing the plans, a lone smoker
is shown puffing on a cigarette on an airplane.
   As the camera pans back up the aisle, a narrator announces
Northwest's plans to offer ``a smoke-free environment'' on all of
its North American flights. The other passengers stand up and
applaud.
   ``Upset is too mild a term,'' the source said when asked to
describe RJR's reaction to Saatchi's work for Northwest.
   The New York Times quoted an RJR Nabisco employee, who asked not
to be identified, in today's editions as saying the company did
take away Saatchi's assignments because of the Northwest ads, but
mainly because the company had not been told of them in advance.
   Ironically, Saatchi & Saatchi DFS' New York unit, Saatchi &
Saatchi DFS Compton, does no cigarette advertising for RJR Nabisco,
whose R.J. Reynolds Tobacco unit markets Camel, Winston, Salem and
Vantage cigarettes.
   Saatchi does create advertising for True cigarettes, which are
made by Loews Corp.'s Lorillard division, an RJR competitor.
   Saatchi's assignments for RJR Nabisco include Life Savers Roll
Candy, Care Free Sugarless Chewing Gum and Oreo, Chips Ahoy! and
Almost Home cookies.
   Saatchi & Saatchi DFS's U.S. billings amount to about $1.6
billion, according to the trade journal Advertising Age. It is a
unit of London-based Saatchi & Saatchi PLC, the biggest ad holding
company in the world.
</TEXT>
