<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers Bjt   04-06 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, Bjt,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Sides With Koppers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court in California has
upheld a victory for Koppers Co. in its fight against a $1.7
billion hostile takeover attempt by British industrialist Brian C.
Beazer and the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Separately, Koppers said its board of directors decided it could
not take a position on the outstanding hostile bid by the Beazer
group because of the court ruling, other outstanding litigation and
Koppers ongoing attempts to seek alternative courses of action.
   U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals Judges Alfred T. Goodwin and
Harry Pregerson late Tuesday denied the Beazer group's appeal of a
lower court order issued Monday that blocked its $60 a share
hostile tender offer.
   The one-sentence ruling was announced from the appeal court's
headquarters in San Francisco.
   U.S. District Judge Manuel Real in Los Angeles issued a
preliminary injunction suspending the tender offer indefinitely
because of on antitrust questions. He issued the order after
Koppers argued that competition could be weakened in the local
market for sand, gravel and hard stone for construction if
California properties of Beazer and Koppers were combined.
   Attorneys for the Beazer group had argued that a delay in
closing the tender offer could jeopardize financing for the
takeover.
   Koppers shares declined $1 to $56.25 a share Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   In Pittsburgh, Beazer met Tuesday with Koppers Chairman Charles
R. Pullin, neither ``was prepared to discuss much of mutual
interest at that meeting,'' Koppers stated in a news release.
   Pullin requested the meeting, according to Beazer spokeswoman
Lissa Perlman in New York. But Pullin was not prepared to discuss
the hostile tender offer or Beazer's proposal to negotiate a
friendly merger with the Pittsburgh construction materials and
chemicals company, she said.
   Beazer, on the other hand, declined to discuss anything but the
takeover or a friendly deal.
   Beazer was in Pittsburgh testifying before U.S. District Judge
Maurice Cohill in a hearing on Koppers' lawsuit contending the
Beazer group violated securities laws in launching its tender offer
March 3. The offer expires at midnight EDT Thursday.
   Cohill issued no ruling Tuesday.
   Koppers has disputed the accuracy of disclosures made in
documents issued in conjunction with the tender offer.
   In his testimony, Beazer identified documents suggesting
Koppers' chemicals businesses could be sold after the takeover for
as much as $700 million. The takeover plan calls for getting at
least $400 million for those operations, although Beazer said no
serious bidders had yet been found.
</TEXT>
