<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-USConstruction     04-06 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Construction,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese, U.S. Construction Firms Launch Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujita Corp., a major Japanese construction firm,
has launched an equally-owned joint venture with a U.S. design
engineering firm, a Fujita official said today.
   Fujita's linkup with Los Angeles-based Daniel, Mann, Johnson and
Mendenhall is the first such joint construction venture established
between Japanese and U.S. firms, said Hajime Shigeoka, Fujita
spokesman.
   DMJM Fujita Co., headed by Fujita President Kazuaki Fujita, will
conduct market research in and outside Japan and will gather
information on construction technologies, Shigeoka said. The new
firm also will plan, design, supervise and undertake contruction
projects.
   Fujita and DMJM have engaged in technological cooperation since
1965, according to Shigeoka.
   ``We will jointly launch business activities to cope with a new
age,'' Shigeoka quoted Fujita as saying.
   Shigeoka said the new company, with a capital of about $80,600,
was set up on Feb. 22 in Tokyo. The announcement of the venture was
delayed as company officials watched developments in U.S.-Japan
talks on American access to Japan's construction market.
   The construction issue has caused friction in trade relations
between the two nations, with many U.S. companies contending they
are virtually shut out of the Japanese construction market while
Japanese companies enjoy liberal access to U.S. customers.
   Late last month, Japanese and U.S. government officials agreed
Japan would encourage foreign participation in major public works
projects financed by the Japanese government, and in other projects
with central or local government funding.
</TEXT>
