<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IntelMicrochips     04-06 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intel Microchips,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intel Unveils New Generation Of Microchips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A research team for Intel Corp. has
developed a new series of microchips capable of executing 7.5
million instructions per second, the company has announced.
   The microchips, known as the 80960 family, are designed for such
uses as helping control robots, airplanes, automobiles and
telecommunications, according to J. Randolph Young, director of
Intel's Oregon Microcomputer Engineering Group.
   The microchips perform at two to three times the speed of
previous microchip generations used for similar machine-controlling
operations, Young said.
   In industrial markets, the chips are expected to supplement or
replace other Intel chips that have been available for as long as
10 years, he said Tuesday.
   The new chips' circuitry incorporates about 500,000 transistors
into a half-inch square of silicon. The circuitry involves parallel
architecture that allows the chip or a combination of chips to
attack various parts of a problem simultaneously, Young said.
   Unlike Intel's standard microprocessor and its predecessors, the
new chip is programmed only once for a specific function, he said.
   Two of the new chips were designed for commercial use and the
other two are for military applications, Young said.
</TEXT>
