<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Obit-Boss     04-06 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Boss,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>W. Russell Boss, Former President of Cross Pen Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   W. Russell Boss, a former president
and chairman of penmaker A.T. Cross Co., has died at age 79.
   Boss died Monday at Holy Cross Hospital in Fort Lauderdale.
   Boss began working as sales manager and treasurer of Cross in
1937, shortly after the death of his father Walter Russell Boss
Sr., owner of the Rhode Island-based company.
   Over the next 27 years, Boss rose to become chairman and
president of the company and helped it evolve from a private,
family-owned business with a dozen employees to a public company
with $155.4 million in revenue and more than 1,400 employees
worldwide.
   Boss in 1979 relinquished the chairmanship he had held since
1971 to his eldest son, Bradford R. Boss of Barrington, R.I. He
remained vice chairman until 1985, when he was named chairman
emeritus.
   The Providence, R.I., native served on the American Automobile
Association's governing board and bred thoroughbred horses in
Florida.
   Boss was survived by his wife Doris, two sons, a sister and six
grandchidren.
   Services were scheduled for Saturday in Cranston, R.I.
</TEXT>
