<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GE-Roper     04-06 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GE-Roper,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE REaches Agreement To Acquire Roper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. and Roper Corp.
said today they have reached a definitive merger agreement that
will allow GE to move ahead with its proposed $507.6 million
aquisition of Roper.
   GE also extended its tender offer deadline by seven hours, until
midnight Monday. GE, based in Fairfield, has offered $54 a share
for Roper's outstanding stock.
   GE was tendered nearly 7.6 million shares as of Tuesday, while
it needs only 4.7 million to take control of Roper, GE spokesman
Jack Batty said today.
   The definitive agreement with Roper was the final hurdle prior
to stockholder approval in a complicated acquisition that was made
simpler last week when Whirlpool Corp. dropped out of the bidding.
The battle for Roper, an appliance and lawn equipment manufacturer
based in Augusta, Ga., began in November.
   Whirlpool, based in Benton Harbor, Mich. bid $50 a share, or
$470 million, in its merger attempt. It decided to let GE complete
a deal unopposed after the two appliance giants agreed to share
Roper products.
   The agreement between GE and Whirlpool allows GE to acquire
Roper and its manufacturing capacity. Whirlpool, in return, will
get rights to the Roper name for major appliances. GE will supply
Whirlpool with Roper-brand electric and gas ranges for at least two
years. Roper also will continue to sell its products to Sears,
Roebuck and Co.
   The parties also agreed to other commercial relationships
whereby GE would sell to Whirlpool certain industrial components
and materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
