<DOCNO> AP880406-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Saudi-Aramco     04-06 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi-Aramco,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Oil Minister Replaces American as Aramco Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAHRAN, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabian Oil Minister Hisham
Nazer has replaced an American to become the first Saudi chairman
of Arabian American Oil Co., his country's major oil-producing
company.
   Nazer took over from John J. Kelberer, who headed Aramco for 10
years. Aramco President Ali I. Naimi will succeed Kelberer as chief
executive.
   The appointment of Nazer, announced late Tuesday in Houston,
reflects the shrinking role in Aramco of the four big U.S. oil
companies that were formerly partners in the venture: Exxon Corp.,
Texaco Inc., Chevron Corp. and Mobil Corp.
   The Saudi government has gradually taken over control of Aramco
from the four companies starting in the 1970s, so that it is now
100 percent Saudi-owned. The four oil majors now mainly provide
technical assistance to the Saudis.
   Kelberer will remain on the board of directors as vice chairman,
although he has effectively retired.
   Kelberer has undergone a number of major surgical operations in
recent years and is understood to have sought retirement after
turning 60 two years ago. He has worked in Saudi Arabia for more
than 37 years, as Aramco's chairman and chief executive for the
past decade.
   The change in Kelberer's position leaves only two Americans in
operating positions equal to vice president or higher at Aramco
headquarters in Dhahran. Of Aramco's 42,000 or so employees in
Saudi Arabia, only about 2,500 are Americans.
   The Saudi government appointed Nazer oil minister in November
1986, replacing Sheik Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
   Nazer is studying a possible reorganization of the kingdom's oil
industry, according to U.S. sources. The new structure, which is
expected to include the creation of a Saudi national oil company,
could be built on either Aramco or Petromin, the sources said.
   Petromin is the marketing company for Saudi petroleum products.
   In addition to his posts as oil minister and Aramco chairman,
Nazer also heads Petromin and the Royal Commission for Jubail and
Yanbu, the body overseeing the country's petrochemical industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
