<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Economy     04-06 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Economy,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Finds No Signs of Economic Recession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a slight drop in the European
Economic Community's economic sentiment indicator in February, the
12-nation trading bloc is not heading for a recession, the EEC
reported Wednesday.
   The EEC Commission, citing the latest business and consumer
survey, said there were ``no signs of an approaching recession.''
It said the stock market crash and the turbulence on
foreign-exchange markets last fall affected ``economic performance
less than originally feared.''
   The commission said the EEC's economic indicator, which is based
partly on the results of the survey, dropped to 102.7 in February
from 102.9 in January, but was above the 102.6 level recorded in
November 1987 after the October crash.
   The indicator comprises an industrial confidence indicator, a
construction confidence indicator, a consumer confidence indicator
and stock price indexes.
   EEC economists reported that production expectations continued
to point toward further growth over the next few months, while the
outlook for exports looked brighter than anticipated.
   Lower-than-expected production results in Britain since last
December have led industrialists there to revise their production
expectations significantly downward, the commission said.
   The consumer confidence indicator lost a point in February over
the preceding month, and consumers remained cautious about
purchasing durables, the commission said.
   Retailers also continued to feel slightly pessimistic about
future prospects, but their assessment of the overall business
situation remained positive, according to the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
