<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     04-06 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0330</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged higher in early trading
today, extending a rally in the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose 16.92
points on Monday, was up another 6.14 points at 2,003.65 after 90
minutes of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 673 up, 495 down and
525 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 43.29 million shares at
midmorning, compared with 45.28 million shares at the same point in
Tuesday's session.
   Analysts say investors' uncertainty about the direction of the
economy and interest rates have put a damper on stock price gains.
They say some investors have also been unable to shake worries
inspired by last October's price crash.
   In the credit markets today, the federal funds rate, a key
interest rate indicator which is what banks charge each other for
short-term loans, edged over 7 percent. Rising rates normally
depress stock prices.
   But Jack Baker, head of block trading for Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc., said investors might be taking heart from strength
in the dollar and in foreign stock markets.
   F.W. Woolworth led the NYSE's list of most actively-traded
stocks, falling 1\ to 55]. The stock shot up more than $11 a share
in the previous two sessions after a group led by Dart Group Corp.
Chairman Herbert Haft expressed interest in acquiring a stake in
the retailer.
   A number of utility issues were also among the most active
issues.
   Among the blue-chip stocks, International Business Machines was
off | at 106~, General Electric was unchanged at 40| and Coca-Cola
was up [ at 38\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.33 to 146.62. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index slipped 0.01 to 295.06.
</TEXT>
