<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-06 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0290</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices moved higher this morning on
the Chicago Board of Trade, while other commodities were mixed in a
narrow range.
   Follow through buying from Tuesday's strong runup kept the wheat
pit busy, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   After the close of trading on Tuesday, the Agriculture
Department announced that it is offering China 2 million tons of
subsidized wheat.
   This and an expected Soviet bid Thursday on a half million tons
of wheat put traders into a buying mood, said Lespinasse.
   Soybean futures opened a little easier following weaker European
markets, but firmed up a little in early dealings in Chicago.
   On the opening, wheat was 2\ cents to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.09{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to \ cent lower with May at $2.08{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents higher with May at $1.67 a bushel; and soybeans were 3{ cents
lower to } cent higher with May at $6.71{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while hogs were mostly lower on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with the April
contract at 74 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .43 cent to .60
cent higher with April at 80.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .20
cent lower to .05 cent higher with April at 45.35 cents a pound;
and frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .12 cent higher with May
at 53.32 cents a pound.
   On Tuesday, pork bellies were sharply lower while most livestock
contracts were higher.
</TEXT>
