<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-BankMergers-List Adv10   04-06 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bank Mergers-List, Adv 10,0411</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-Bank Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostile takeovers have been relatively rare in the nation's
banking industry. Of the 1,743 merger deals that have been
consummated from 1981-1987, only three significant hostile offers
have succeeded.
   Here is a list of the hostile takeover attempts during that
five-year period, according to the bank analyst Keefe, Bruyette &
Woods, Inc.:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Southeast Banking Corp. made a $240 million cash bid for Florida
National Bank. Florida National struck a deferred merger agreement
with Chemical New York.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Huntington Bancshares madea successful $96 million cash-stock
bid for Union Commerce.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1983</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Barnett Banks made a successful $75 million cash bid for Florida
Coast.
   Norstar Bancorp made a successful $95 milion cash-stock bid for
Security New York.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Midlantic Banks made a $70 million stock or cash bid for
Statewide Bancorp. Marine Midland, acting as a ``white knight,''
made an equity infusion into Statewide.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Meridian Bancorp made a $113 million stock bid for Commonwealth.
Commonwealth accepted a higher $119 milion bid from Mellon.
   Comerica made a $350 million stock bid for Michigan National.
Marine Midland, acting as a white knight, made an equity infusion
into Michigan National. An additional capital restructuring was
undertaken.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Fleet Financial Group made a $540 million stock offer for The
Conifer Group. Conifer accepted a higher $656 million stock swap
from white knight Bank of New England.
   First Interstate made a $3.2 billion stock bid for BankAmerica
Corp. It withdrew the bid after BankAmerica announced the sale of
certain assets and proposals to issue new capital.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Wilmington Trust made a $190 million stock bid for Delaware
Trust. Delaware accepted a comparably priced stock swap deal from
white knight Meridian Bancorp.
   Marshall & Ilsley made a $560 million cash or stock bid for
Marine Corp. Marine Corp. accepted a lower $525 million stock swap
from white knight Banc One.
   Bank of New York made a $1.4 billion cash-stock bid for Irving
Trust. The proposal, twice revised downward, is pending.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 10</NOTE>
