<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FashionChannel     04-06 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fashion Channel,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cable Shopping Service Suffers $20 Million Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fashion Channel Network home shopping
service reported a first-year loss of $20 million and announced the
departure of its chairman and chief executive.
   The company, which sells clothes, cosmetics and accessories over
cable television, had sales of $5.5 million in its first four
months of operation, according to the announcement Tuesday.
   The Fashion Channel, which formed about a year ago and went on
the air in October, announced that co-founder Charles W. Gee would
no longer serve as chairman and chief executive officer.
   Gee was the last of three founding top executives to leave the
management. In January, the company announced the departures of
Raymond L. Klauer, a former May Co. California president, and Wayne
C. Smith.
   Gee will remain as a director.
   Fashion Channel's newly named president, Donald Miller, said he
has been talking to several parties interested in buying part of
the company, including Shop Television Network, which is backed by
J.C. Penney and STN of Hollywood; QVC and Cable Value Network.
   ``The company is still operating,'' Miller said Tuesday. ``It's
busniess as usual and we're holding down the fort. But it's not
fun.''
   The company attributed much of the loss to start-up costs.
   The company's stock took a drastic plunge in the October market
crash, just over two weeks after it was first offered to the public.
   Since then, Fashion Channel has been forced to move merchandise
by cutting prices drastically, said analyst Larry Gerbrandt of Paul
Kagan Associates in Carmel. Gerbrandt also blamed the loss in part
on overbuying of goods that proved unattractive to customers.
</TEXT>
