<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brazil-Argentina     04-06 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Argentina,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South American Leaders Meet To Discuss Economies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidents of Brazil, Argentina and
Uruguay met Wednesday for the fifth time in three years to discuss
ways to unify their economies.
   Argentina's Raul Alfonsin met with Uruguay's Julio Maria
Sanguinetti and Brazil's Jose Sarney.
   Argentina and Brazil _ South America's largest countries _ have
been meeting since 1985 on ways to integrate their economies along
the lines of the European Economic Community.
   So far, 21 agreements have been signed between the two
countries. On Thursday, Alfonsin and Sarney plan to sign additional
pacts eliminating trade tariffs for automobiles, automotive parts
and food goods.
   Neighboring Uruguay so far has been mostly an active observer in
the project.
</TEXT>
