<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Turner'sCastle     04-06 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turner's Castle,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turner Property To Be Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Feds are finally getting Glenn Turner's
castle.
   A federal court and the Internal Revenue Service have begun
foreclosure proceedings on the three-story, long-uncompleted castle
owned by the hillbilly entrepreneur who made and lost a fortune by
selling motivational-training and cosmetics franchises in the 1970s.
   The IRS has been trying for 10 years to collect a $15 million
back-taxes claim against Turner, 53, who was in and out of trouble
with the law for years because of what investigators said were
illegal pyramid schemes that defrauded thousands of investors.
   He is currently serving a seven-year prison term in Arizona on
fraud convictions.
   Now, one of his prized possessions, the 16-room castle and 79
surrounding acres on Bear Gulley Lake in neighboring Seminole
County, Fla., is being sold at auction to satisfy an IRS judgment
against him in U.S. District Court in Orlando.
   But the IRS figures it will be lucky to get even a fraction of
the final amount set by the court: $9.275 million.
   The estate was appraised by the county at $1.13 million in 1987,
and recent appraisals by private companies list its value at
between $1.6 million and $2 million.
   Senior U.S. District Judge George Young will hold a hearing
April 26 to decide if two bids for the property _ or any new ones
made in the interim _ will be accepted.
   Once the property is sold, Seminole County has the right to be
paid first from the proceeds. County Tax Collector G. Troy Ray said
about $16,900 in unpaid property taxes is owed on the property for
1987.
   Turner and his family haven't paid property taxes since 1979,
but private investors have bought tax certificates equal to the
back taxes each year. Under such an arrangement, the investors pay
the taxes and earn 18 percent interest until the property is sold
and the tax funds are paid back to them.
   Those tax payments will come from the sale, too.
   Court documents indicate there are dozens of other Turner
creditors, but it is unlikely that they will be paid until all of
the IRS judgment is satisfied, officials said.
   Bids on the Castle property will be advertised over the next few
weeks to notify any potential bidders of the pending sale. Besides
the castle, there is a boathouse with a three-bedroom apartment and
a stable.
   The castle and boathouse have been vacant for several years, and
the castle has been used only for tours and charitable events.
   Turner's financial empire crumbled in 1973 after he reportedly
made about $300 million through aggressive marketing of his
Orlando-based Dare To Be Great motivational classes and Koscot
cosmetics distributorships.
   The self-styled country boy, son of a South Carolina
sharecropper, rose to fame through inspirational speeches that
promised great wealth if people bought distributorships in his
operations.
   The companies collapsed under lawsuits filed by investors and
investigations by state and federal agencies.
   Turner and a longtime partner, Edward Rector, 57, were sentenced
to prison in Arizona on charges of operating a pyramid scheme there
and defrauding investors through a later self-motivational company
called Challenge Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HelpWanted     04-06 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Help Wanted,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Help-Wanted Index Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of help-wanted advertisements in
major newspapers rose slightly in February, indicating employers'
hiring plans are little changed, the Conference Board said
Wednesday.
   The business research group's Help-Wanted Index rose to 156 in
February from 153 in January, when the barometer dipped slightly.
It stood at roughly the same level as in December.
   ``Want-ad volume suggests that hiring intentions are flat at
best, as business executives take a hard look at plans for further
expansion of operations,''said Kenneth Goldstein, a Conference
Board economist.
   With the growth in the labor force, stagnant hiring plans could
result in higher unempoyement, Goldstein said. The Labor Department
has reported the unemployment rate was 5.6 percent last month.
   The index measures the volume of classified advertising in 51
major newspapers across the country. It is considered sensitive to
changes in the demand for labor and to overall business conditions.
   Advertising volume rose in the West South Central, Middle
Atlantic, New England, Pacific and South Atlantic regions. Volume
fell in the East North Central, East South Central, West North
Central and Mountain regions.
</TEXT>
