<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0199</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures advanced while the other grains and
soybeans were mostly lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat continued the gains posted during a sharp runup on
Tuesday, and overnight news gave the market fresh incentive.
   The Agriculture Department announced after the close of trading
on Tuesday that it was offering China 2 million tons of subsidized
wheat.
   This along with expectations that the Soviet Union will bid on a
half million tons of wheat this week combined to create a sense of
optimism in the wheat pit, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Soybeans struggled a little higher during the day, but collapsed
under late selling pressure.
   On the close, wheat was 1} cents to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.09 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.07\ a bushel; oats were 1
