<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DividendReport     04-06 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dividend Report,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Finds Quarterly Corporate Dividends Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slightly more companies raised their
first-quarter dividends over a year ago, reflecting an increased
confidence that the economy isn't headed into a recession following
the stock market crash, Standard & Poor's Corp. reported Tuesday.
   For the first three months of 1988, dividend increases rose 4.8
percent, to 482 from 460 in 1987, S&P said. At the same time,
decreased and omitted dividends fell to 47 from 58 in the quarter,
it said.
   ``The rebound in dividend increases shows that fears of a
recession due to the market crash have abated,'' said Arnie
Kaufman, editor of S&P's Outlook newsletter.
   ``Recovery in the manufacturing sector is enabling many formerly
depressed businesses to participate in dividend largesse after
years of struggling to merely hold the line.''
   Despite the Oct. 19 stock collapse, Kaufman said corporations
were optimistic the economy would continue to expand this year
because of recent upbeat trade, employment and consumer spending
reports.
   Companies reporting dividend actions to S&P comprise a
substantial portion of all public companies in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
