<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-JapaneseInvestment     04-06 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japanese Investment,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Real Estate Purchases in U.S. Totaled $12.77 Billion, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors bought $12.77 billion
worth of U.S. real estate in 1987, a 70 percent increase over the
previous year, according to a new report.
   The purchases were concentrated in markets traditionally favored
by the Japanese _ Hawaii, California and New York _ but investors
are broadening their sights to include other areas as well,
according to a study released Wednesday.
   The study, conducted for the last three years by Kenneth
Laventhal & Co., a nationwide accounting firm, is based on
information from clients, public records and other sources, and is
described by the company as a slight underestimation.
   The buying binge is spurred by the rising value of the yen in
relation to the dollar, the tight real estate market in Japan and
attractive rates of return on U.S. commercial real estate ranging
from 6 percent to 9 percent a year, said Jack Rodman, managing
partner of the company's Los Angeles office.
   Japanese real estate purchases mushroomed in the three years of
the study: $1.86 billion in 1985, $7.53 billion in 1986 and $12.77
billion in 1987.
   In 1987, Hawaii was the favorite shopping spot, attracting $3.3
billion from Japan, the study found. California was second, with
$2.98 billion, and New York was third, with $2.34 billion.
   Far behind, in order, were Arizona, Illinois, Texas, Washington
state, Florida, Washington, D.C., and Massachusetts.
   Office buildings commanded the most dollars from Japan _ $5.19
billion in 1987. Investment in hotel and resort properties soared
160 percent in 1987, to $4.57 billion, partly because of several
big purchases in Hawaii. Investment in residential property was
$1.3 billion.
   The study found increasing Japanese interest in so-called
secondary real estate markets, including Phoenix, Orange County,
Calif., Chicago, Miami and Seattle. For the first time in the three
years of the study, 56 percent of the purchases were in secondary
markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
