<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Phillips-Settlement     04-06 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phillips-Settlement,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE, Phillips Petroleum Agree on Overcharge Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said Wednesday it had
agreed on a $30 million settlement of old alleged price-control
violations with Phillips Petroleum Co. of Bartlesville, Okla.
   The department had accused the company of selling
price-controlled oil to two buyers in exchange for discounts on
simultaneous purchase from them of oil that was not subjected to
controls, enabling Phillips to gain $51 million more on the sales
in 1979-1981 than it should have. Most crude oil was subject to
price controls at the time.
   In agreeing to the settlement, Phillips did not admit to any
violation of or failure to comply with the price-control
regulations.
</TEXT>
