<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-06 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0195</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rolled up one of its biggest
gains of the year today, taking its cue from a stronger dollar and
a decline in interest rates.
   The market took off in the early afternoon after trading in a
narrow range earlier in the day.
   Analysts said the gain was due to a strengthening of the dollar
in foreign exchange trading, which in turn prompted a decline in
interest rates.
   The dollar moved higher, they said, on speculation that the
major industrial nations may be moving toward a reaffirmation of
support for the currency against the Japanese yen. A meeting is
planned for next week.
   Such an agreement could mean that the Federal Reserve would no
longer feel it necessary to tighten its credit policy and push
interest rates higher in a bid to head off inflation.
   The advance in the Dow Jones industrial average of 30
industrials was so strong that it triggered for the first time a
voluntary plan under which the New York Stock Exchange hopes to
curb price volatility.
</TEXT>
