<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspageStocks     04-06 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage Stocks,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Market Posts Year's Second-Biggest Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged Wednesday, putting in
its second-best performance so far this year after taking a cue
from a stronger dollar and lower interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 16.91 on
Tuesday, jumped another 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67.
   It was the biggest rise in the key blue-chip indicator since it
climbed 76.42 points on Jan. 4, the first trading day of the year.
   Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 3 to 1 on the New York Stock
Exchange. Big Board volume totaled 189.76 million shares, compared
with 135.29 million on Tuesday.
   The Dow's advance was so strong it triggered a 50-point
voluntary restriction on computerized program trading on the New
York Stock Exchange for the first time since the limit was
announced Feb. 4.
   Program trading, a technique used by brokerages to profit on
price differences between stocks and the corresponding stock-index
futures, has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market
and frightening investors.
   The market climbed steadily throughout the afternoon after
trading in a narrow range earlier in the day.
   Analysts said the gain was due to a strengthening of the dollar
in foreign exchange trading, which in turn prompted a decline in
interest rates in the credit markets.
   The dollar moved higher, they said, on speculation that the
major industrial nations may be moving toward a fresh agreement to
support the U.S. currency. A meeting of the industrial powers is
planned for next week.
   Such an agreement could mean that the Federal Reserve would no
longer feel it necessary to tighten its credit policy and push
interest rates higher in a bid to head off inflation.
</TEXT>
