<2ND_LINE>BC-Moore McCormack-Southdown, 1st Ld-Writethru,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore McCormack Agrees To Be Acquired By Southdown</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to UPDATE with closing stock prices.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moore McCormack Resources Inc. said Wednesday it
has agreed to be acquired by Southdown Inc. for $512 million in
cash after resisting repeated overtures from the Houston-based
cement company.
   Moore McCormack's board recommended shareholders relinquish
their shares to Southdown's existing $40-a-share tender offer. The
offer expires at midnight EDT Wednesday, but Southdown said it
would accept Moore McCormack shares for payment following the
expiration of that deadline.
   Under terms of a definitive merger agreement, Southdown also
will acquire Moore McCormack's convertible issues and debt. The
companies have agreed to dismiss all pending litigation between
them.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Moore McCormack fell 75
cents to close at $39.75 a share; Southdown rose 50 cents to $40.75
a share.
   Southdown also said it would terminate a previous agreement to
sell Moore McCormack's oil and gas subsidiary, called Moore
McCormack Engery, to Castex International Corp. for $125 million in
cash.
   A Southdown spokeswoman had no comment on whether Moore
McCormack management would be asked to stay on board.
   Moore McCormack, a Stamford, Conn.-based cement and energy
concern, had said it was negotiating with other unidentified
parties about the acquisition of the entire company. The Moore
McCormack board met Tuesday to weigh bids for the company _
including Southdown's _ as well as a recapitalization plan the
board had engineered as a defensive measure.
   Southdown's latest offer for Moore McCormack's 12.8 million
outstanding shares represents the fourth time the company has
sweetened its bid.
   Southdown approached Moore McCormack on Feb. 23 with an initial
$31-a-share tender offer, which valued the company at $391 million.
That bid, as well as a sweetened $35-a-share offer that followed,
were rejected as inadequate.
   ``The board of directors of Moore McCormack continues to believe
that remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the
long-range term,'' the company had said in a statement following
the two offers.
   Moore McCormack responded to the two bids by unveiling a $400
million recapitalization plan that would have paid shareholders a
hefty dividend and authorized the sale of certain assets. The
company had even lined up loans to finance the payout and related
costs.
   A day after the recapitalization plan was unveiled, Southdown
responded with an offer that would have paid shareholders $35 in
cash plus debt securities valued at $5 for each share they held.
The bid was amended to a straight $40-a-share in cash last week.
   Moore McCormack posted a profit of $21.6 million on revenue of
$357.8 million in 1987. The company makes cement, concrete products
and aggregates, primarily in the southeastern United States, and is
engaged in oil and gas exploration and production mainly in Texas
and Louisiana.
   Southdown produces and sells cement and ready-mixed concrete and
is active in oil and gas production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
