<DOCNO> AP880406-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-06 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Plunge on Dollar's Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures retreated sharply Wednesday, triggered
by the surging value of the dollar.
   On other markets, wheat and cattle futures moved higher; other
grains and beans were mostly a little weaker; and stock index
futures posted substantial gains, following a rally on the stock
market.
   There were strong movements on most of the financial markets.
   ``The story that seemed to light the fire under all these
markets was a Japanese news account that (major financial
ministers) would reaffirm the lower the lower limit of the dollar
at about 125 yen,'' said Craig Sloane, an analyst in New York with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   There have been unconfirmed reports that the finance ministers
from the five major industrial nations will meet next week in
Washington. This supposedly would be in conjunction with scheduled
meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
   The Japanese wire service, Nikkei, reported Wednesday that the
Group of 5 nations will affirm the dollar-yen rate.
   ``This was just a report,'' said Sloane, `` and we don't have
any idea if there's any truth to it. But with the yen at 125 this
morning ... the dollar went higher,'' he said.
   ``This pushed the precious metals to the brink,'' he said,
``with silver especially putting in a very poor performance.''
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold settled $4.40 to
$5.70 lower with June at $451.30 a troy ounce; and silver was 22
cents to 22.5 cents lower with May at $6.465 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange recorded
one of the busiest days since the October stock crash. Estimated
volume of the Standard & Poor's 500 index was an estimated 62,286,
compared with a monthly average in March of about 48,000.
   A surge in the Dow Jones Industrial average triggered a curb at
the New York Stock Exchange on program trading, under which traders
buy or sell stocks and take the opposite action in index futures.
This came late in the session, however, and apparently didn't have
a large impact on trading at the Merc.
   The June S&P 500 contract settled 7.90 points higher at 267.40.
The underlying index was up 6.98 points at 265.49.
   Cattle futures advanced on follow-through buying from Tuesday's
late recovery at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, but the
underlying factors don't look good, said Charlie Richardson, an
analyst with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   ``Feedlots are selling a little cheaper for the first time in
two or three weeks,'' he said, adding that the boxed beef trade is
declining.
   ``Salesmen are saying they're having trouble moving beef at the
retail counter and they're disappointed with the performance at
Easter,'' said Richardson.
   Live cattle futures settled .12 cent to .48 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in April at 74.02 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .02 cent to .40 cent higher with April at 79.57 cents a
pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .28 cent higher with April
at 45.70 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower
to .02 cent higher with May at 53.22 cents a pound.
   Wheat futures advanced while the other grains and soybeans were
mostly lower on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat continued the gains posted during a sharp runup on
Tuesday, and overnight news gave the market fresh incentive.
   The Agriculture Department announced after the close of trading
on Tuesday that it is offering China 2 million tons of subsidized
wheat.
   This along with expectations that the Soviet Union will bid on a
half million tons of wheat this week combined to create a sense of
optimism in the wheat pit, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Wheat settled 1} cents to 3} cents higher with the May contract
at $3.09\ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
May at $2.07{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to \ cent higher
with May at $1.65 a bushel; and soybeans were 3 cents to 4{ cents
lower with May at $6.67\ a bushel.
   Energy futures were little changed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 3 cents
higher with the April contract at $16.30 a barrel; heating oil was
.02 cent lower to .18 cent higher with May at 45.34 cents a gallon;
and unleaded gasoline was .07 cent lower to .22 cent lower with May
at 48.42 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
