<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LotteryContract     04-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery Contract,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lottery Keeps Computer Vendor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pennsylvania Lottery said Wednesday
it has decided to stick with its computer vendor, Control Data
Corp. of Minneapolis, in a new five-year, $143 million contract.
   Companies from Rhode Island, Maryland and Georgia were
unsuccessful in their bid for the contract with the lottery, the
nation's third largest. The Pennsylvania Lottery had gross revenue
of of $1.3 billion in 1986-87 and profits of $570 million.
   Control Data's Automated Wagering Division, based in New York
City, will supply a minimum of 3,200 new sales terminals and a
primary and backup computer with new telecommunications features,
said Revenue Secretary Barton Fields. The new equipment is to be
installed by next January.
   After a three-month review, lottery officials decided Control
Data's 11 years' experience as the lottery's computer supplier and
its proposed system were among the reasons to keep the company,
Fields said.
   ``CDC, by virtue of its state-of-the-art technology and
expertise, is the supplier best suited to serve the lottery into
the 1990s,'' Fields said in a statement.
   Other vendors who had submitted proposals were G-Tech Corp. of
Warwick, R.I., General Instruments Corp. of Hunt Valley, Md. and
Scientific Games of Atlanta.
   The new contract will take effect Jan. 1, 1989, and the $143
million is the estimated worth over five years.
   ``The Pennsylvania Lottery system will be the newest and most
powerful lottery system available to the lottery industry today,''
said James Chidester, vice president of wagering services for the
Automated Wagering Division.
   Control Data, with over 50 percent of the market for on-line
lottery equipment, supplies lotteries in five states besides
Pennsylvania and recently was awarded the contract for Florida's
new lottery, the company said. The other states with Control Data
equipment are Maryland, Delaware, New York, Illinois and Washington.
</TEXT>
