<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FreeDrugs Bjt   04-06 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Free Drugs, Bjt,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Searle Expands Free Drug Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   G.D. Searle & Co. said Wednesday it will expand a
program of giving heart disease drugs to the poor, a move observers
say puts the company at the helm of the pharmaceutical industry's
efforts to help the indigent.
   Under a year-old pilot program, Skokie-based Searle gave $9
million worth of high blood pressure medicine to 20,000 patients.
The company said it would expand its ``Patient In Need'' program by
making all seven of its heart medicines available.
   The plan will roughly double the cost and the number of patients
involved, company officials said.
   To kick off its expanded program, Searle planned on Wednesday to
deliver $1 million worth of certificates for drugs to clinics and
hospitals in 10 major cities.
   ``I personally believe that all drugs that treat
life-threatening diseases should be involved,'' said Dr. Sheldon G.
Gilgore, Searle's chairman and chief executive officer. He noted
that congressional sources put the number of Americans without any
health insurance at 37 million.
   Judee Shuler, a spokeswoman for the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers
Association, said all drug manufacturers do something to help poor
patients, ``but Searle is more extensive.''
   Most of Searle's drugs are cardiovascular medications, and
Gilgore called on other pharmaceutical houses to follow suit with
their drugs.
   ``This area is extremely tricky,'' said Thomas Nefi, a spokesman
for E.R. Squibb & Sons Inc. of Princeton, N.J. ``Drugs are a
commodity rigorously controled by the federal government. It's not
like making shoes and giving them to the poor.''
   Nefi said he was not familiar with the details of Searle's
program, but he noted that ``the distribution mechanism is going to
be difficult, and I would like to see how they're going to do it.''
   Searle's expanded effort will distribute the drugs in the same
manner as the pilot program, said spokesman William I. Greener.
   Participating doctors are issued certificates from Searle.
Patients receive both a prescription and a certificate, both of
which must be presented to a pharmacist.
   Patients get the drugs for free, while pharmacists mail the
certificates to Searle for reimbursement.
   The company classifies poor people as those with annual
household incomes of $8,000 for one or two people, or $11,000 for
three or more family members. To qualify, patients must not have
insurance or other assistance that would pay for the drug.
   Several other drug makers have some form of indigent care
program.
   Merck Sharp & Dohme, a division of Merck & Co., donates drugs to
various charitable groups, such as the Catholic Medical Mission
Board, which distributes them to physicians who pass them on to the
needy at home and abroad.
   Merck also will give free drugs to individual doctors who
request them for poor patients, said spkeswoman Nancy Gellert.
   ``We feel we give a pretty broadly based coverage,'' she said.
   Roxane Laboratories in Columbus, Ohio, gives a drug to poor
terminal cancer patients in severe pain, said company spokesman
Gerald C. Wojta. The company announced its plan several years ago.
   Wyeth Laboratories, a division of American Home Products Corp.,
has a ``compassionate program for the tryly needy through the
physician,'' said spokeswoman Audrey Ashby. ``It's judged on a
patient-by-patient basis.''
   Searle is a research-based company that develops, manufactures
and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide. It is a wholly
owned subsidiary of Monsanto Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880406-0279 </DOCNO>
