<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Koppers 1st-LdWritethru   04-06 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers, 1st-Ld Writethru,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with federal judge's ruling in first four grafs,
edits throughout to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Wednesday that Britain's
Brian Beazer cannot proceed with his $1.7 billion hostile tender
offer for Koppers Co. until at least April 15.
   A U.S. District judge in Los Angeles on Monday suspended the
$60-a-share offer indefinitely on antitrust grounds. U.S. District
Judge Maurice Cohill in Pittsburgh said if Beazer succeeds in
overturning the California ruling, his order immediately blocks the
offer until he rules on Koppers' arguments that the unwanted
suitors violated securities law.
   Cohill said he will rule by April 15 on the Pittsburgh
construction materials and chemicals company's request for a
preliminary injunction.
   It was not immediately clear how this latest barrier would
affect the tender offer from BNS Inc., the takeover company formed
by Beazer and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. Attorneys for the Beazer
interests said a delay could scuttle its tender offer.
   Meanwhile, Koppers Chairman Charles R. Pullin said Wednesday he
expects Beazer's tender offer will be declared inadequate by
Koppers board of directors.
   ``My judgment is that with more time we will find that (the bid)
is inadequate,'' Pullin testified in federal court, one day after
Koppers' board said it was reserving judgment on the offer.
   Under questioning by BNS attorney Edwin Mishkin, Pullin said he
also expected someone to beat the $60-a-share offer.
   ``I'm not sure I could hazard a guess as to when'' a better
offer might come, Pullin said.
   The chairman said he expected some stockholders would consider
$60 a share as an adequate offer. He said he also expected some
shareholders would want to accept the $60 a share. Arbitrageurs
likely would tender their stock as well, he said.
   The offer from Beazer, head of the construction and building
materials concern Beazer PLC, and Shearson Lehman Hutton was to
have expired at midnight Thursday. The two are partners in BNS
along with the National Westminster Bank PLC, which launched the
tender offer March 3.
   Pullin told Cohill on Wednesday that the board is considering
selling an interest in all or part of the company. Koppers prefers
to sell no more than 20 percent to 25 percent of its valued
construction materials and services group, he said.
   Koppers has said it also is considering a recapitalization plan
and, if necessary, the sale of the entire company as a defensive
measure. Charles Barber, a Koppers director, noted in testimony
Tuesday that a recapitalization plan is still in the formative
stages.
   A management-led buyout of Koppers' chemicals businesses also
has been considered an alternative to the BNS offer.
   ``Some management people have talked about a leveraged buyout,
which would keep (the company) here in Pittsburgh,'' Pullin
testified during a hearing to consider Koppers' request for an
injunction.
   So far, however, a leveraged buyout of the company's chemical
operations ``hasn't been actively pursued,'' partly because of the
costs involved, he added.
   Pullin said the Koppers board met Tuesday with its financial
advisers, who gave ambiguous opinions on Beazer's valuation of the
company.
   Dillon Read & Co., engaged to advise non-management directors,
was unable to say the $60-a-share offer was adequate, but First
Boston Corp., which is advising all the directors, was unable to
say the offer was inadequate, Pullin said.
   Koppers closed on the New York Stock Exchange on Wednesday at
$55.37{ a share, down 87{ cents.
   The U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday denied an
emergency motion to overturn the lower court. But the appeals court
will take the appeal during the coming week, Cohill said.
</TEXT>
