<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-06 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Move Broadly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fortified by a stronger dollar, lower interest
rates and an afternoon of frenzied buying, the stock market soared
Wednesday as the Dow Jones industrial average posted its second
biggest gain of the year.
   But despite the strong gain, some analysts were skeptical about
how long it could last.
   ``It was a very impressive rally, but it's still a manic
depressive market, so I'm not trusting it yet for any sustained
move,'' said Thomas Czech, head of the investment policy group at
the brokerage Blunt Ellis & Loewi in Milwaukee.
   The Dow Jones industrials, the market's best-known indicator,
advanced 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67. It was the ninth
biggest gain ever in the Dow Jones industrials and the largest gain
since it climbed 76.42 on Jan. 4.
   The Dow's gain was so powerful that it triggered a 50-point
voluntary restriction on computerized program trading on the New
York Stock Exchange for the first time since the limit was
announced Feb. 4.
   But even after the restriction was triggered, stock prices
continued to rise until the market closed.
   Gainers swamped losers by a margin of nearly 3 to 1 in the
overall tally of NYSE-listed issues, with 1,187 up, 414 down and
384 unchanged. The NYSE index rose 3.47 to 149.76.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 189.76 million shares, up from
135.29 million shares on Tuesday.
   The stock market opened with some modest gains but gave most of
them back by noontime before sweeping broadly ahead in the early
afternoon.
   Analysts said the trigger for the market's rise was a news
report from Japan that said officials of the seven major industrial
countries are likely to agree on a plan of support for the dollar.
   A strong dollar would diminish inflationary pressure, and
perhaps ease the pressure on the Federal Reserve to tighten its
credit policy, said Newton D. Zinder, who follows stocks for the
investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton.
   Expectations that the Fed would tighten its policy and raise
interest rates had been depressing stock market psychology, he said.
   Larry Wachtel, a market watcher for Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said the dollar's strength soon rippled through the bond
market, sending long-term rates lower. That in turn made yields on
stocks look more attractive, he said.
   In each of the markets, he said traders who had sold borrowed
contracts in expectations that the dollar, bonds and stocks would
fall suddenly saw prices rising and felt compelled to buy in an
effort to cut their potential losses.
   ``Too many people were selling the market short,'' he said.
   The voluntary restrictions on program trading were called into
play after the Dow Jones average passed the 50-point gain mark at
about 3:19 p.m. EDT, a spokeswoman for the exchange said.
   Program trading, a technique used by brokerages to profit on
price differences between stocks and the corresponding stock-index
futures, has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market
and frightening investors.
   Among actively-traded issues on the NYSE, American Telephone &
Telegraph rose 1\ to 28[, Texaco rose 1\ to 49, Exxon climbed 2 to
44 and General Electric rose 1[ to 41}.
   F.W. Woolworth fell 1} to 54~. The stock shot up more than $11 a
share in the previous two sessions after a group led by Dart Group
Corp. Chairman Herbert Haft expressed interest in acquiring a stake
in the retailer.
   Elsewhere in the retail group, Sears rose 1\ to 37[, K mart
climbed 1[ to 35\ and J.C. Penney rose 1 to 48}.
   The automakers rolled up some impressive advances after
reporting strong late-March sales. General Motors rose 3] to 74,
Ford jumped 1~ to 46\ and Chrysler rose 1\ to 24{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $55.65 billion, or 2.16
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 225.98 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 8.54 to 308.71,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 6.98 to 265.49.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 2.51
to 297.58. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 377.74, up 4.33.
</TEXT>
