<HEAD>More Suitors Approach MGM-UA; Company Trims Losses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 new grafs, to UPDATE with earnings report,
editing to conform, picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The committee... ADDS
2 grafs detail on earnings.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Inc. said Wednesday
that more suitors have come forward since the filmmaking company
announced Monday it was considering several unsolicited takeover
bids.
   Separately, the company reported it had reduced its losses by 73
percent for the second quarter and 84 percent for the half, partly
because of its successful film ``Moonstruck.''
   Disclosure of the new bids came as the company announced a
special committee of its board has been formed to weigh the offers.
The committee does not include financier Kirk Kerkorian, who owns
79 percent of the company's 50.1 million shares.
   ``The committee will promptly consider the inquiries received
before Monday's announcement, as well as additional inquiries
received in the last two days,'' said MGM-UA's chairman and chief
executive, Lee Rich.
   The company again declined to identify the suitors or to
indicate whether it would be amenable to a takeover, saying only,
``We have a duty to our shareholders to explore these matters.''
   Analysts have suggested Kerkorian may be offering to buy the
rest of the stock and take the company private. Other likely
investors listed by analysts were investors Marvin Davis and Burt
Sugarman, whose separate bids for other companies are stalled and
considered unlikely to succeed.
   Kerkorian had been majority owner of the old Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
and United Artists studios, then sold them in 1986 to media
entrepreneur Ted Turner for $1.5 billion plus assumption of some
debt. As part of that deal, Kerkorian immediately repurchased the
UA segment.
   Later, Turner sold off all of the MGM unit except for its film
library that he is using on his Atlanta-based superstation WTBS.
Kerkorkian purchased the studio and Lorimar-Telepictures Corp.
bought some other assets.
   Kerkorian paid a total of $730 million to buy back the two
segments and has had spotty success in his attempts to rebuild the
companies.
   For its second quarter ended Feb. 29, the comapny posted a net
loss of $4.6 million, compared with a deficit of $17.1 million a
year earlier. Revenue for the period rose 48 percent to $157.9
million from $106.2 million.
   For the half, the company trimmed its losses to $2.6 million
from $14.4 million, as revenue rose 43 percent to $339.9 million
from $237.2 million.
</TEXT>
