<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   04-06 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Jump For Domestic Automakers In Late March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyer incentives and economic confidence boosted
late-March and first-quarter sales reported Wednesday by the Big
Three automakers.
   Some import carmakers also reported increases although many
posted declines for the March 21-31 sales period and for the
quarter, blaming the weaker dollar that effectively raised their
prices for American buyers.
   Domestic car sales totaled 332,721 for the 10 days, up from
282,358 for the nine-day sales period of late March 1987. Domestic
sales for the first quarter totaled 1,914,022, up from 1,666,748 a
year earlier.
   Import car sales, reported monthly, totaled 255,867 for March,
up from 237,677 in March 1987, and totaled 700,572 for the quarter,
up from 639,403 in the 1987 first quarter.
   First-quarter sales of imported light trucks slid to 168,908
from 204,424 in the 1987 first quarter. Domestic light truck sales
jumped to 1,044,984 for the quarter from 840,073 a year earlier.
   Sales were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 8.4 million
for the late March period, up from a strong 8.1 million rate for
the period last year, and were 7.5 million for the month, up from
7.3 million for March 1987.
   ``Sales are robust for the month, continuing what was going on
in January and February,'' said Cynthia Certo, analyst at
Integrated Automotive Resources Inc. in Wayne, Pa.
   She added buyers appeared confident in a strong election-year
economy and unworried about last October's stock slump.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. each reported more than 18
percent jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter while General
Motors Corp., the top seller, reported a 9.5 percent rise.
   Dealers incentives helped, said Robert L. Rewey, a Ford vice
president.
   ``Cash-allowance buyer incentive programs are in effect a
temporary price cut and the buyers are reacting to the bargain
prices,'' Rewey said.
   GM sold 159,728 domestically produced autos for the 10 days, up
from 136,082 in the nine-day late-March period last year, and
942,830 for the quarter, up from 849,470 in the 1987 first quarter.
GM's daily sales rate was up 9.5 percent.
   Ford domestic auto sales totaled 93,590 for the 10 days, up from
79,249 a year earlier, and 553,545 for the three months, up from
462,629 for the 1987 first quarter.
   Ford set a record with sales of 150,522 domestically made light
trucks for the month of March, up from 132,126 in March 1987 and
the most for any March for Ford.
   Chrysler sold 48,125 domestic cars for the 10 days, up from
41,652 in the year-ago period, and 283,491 for the quarter, up from
236,280 in the first quarter of 1987.
   Some import carmakers also reported increases. For example,
Toyota sales rose to 42,734 for March from 37,099 in March 1987,
and 127,050 for the quarter, up from 101,117 in the first quarter
of 1987.
   But Nissan sales slid to 39,536 for the month from 41,824 in
March 1987, and to 92,163 for the quarter, down from 119,452 a year
ago.
</TEXT>
